{"id": "3846", "revid": "47838920", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3846", "title": "Athena/Boons (Hades)", "text": "Many of Athena's boons add Deflect to your abilities. Deflect is a mechanic unique to Athena boons which allows an ability to repel projectiles and damage back at the attacker. A projectile hit with a Deflecting ability will be sent back towards the enemy who cast it and deals a portion of the enemy's health instead of its base damage. A well-timed Deflecting ability can also negate a melee attack, dealing damage to the attacker instead.\n\"(Note: Portion of damage not known. It doesn't appear to be eight times the base damage at least in every case. Needs verifying.)\""}
{"id": "5041", "revid": "48934972", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5041", "title": "Athena/Boons (Hades II)", "text": "Athena boons revolve around in applying her unique buff Deflect to Melino\u00eb's attacks which allows melee or range attacks to be reflected back to the attacker. Additionally, Athena can restore &lt;a href=\"Death%20Defiance/Hades%20II\"&gt;Death Defiance&lt;/a&gt; charges. Athena's elemental affinity is &lt;a href=\"Fire\"&gt;Fire&lt;/a&gt;. Athena has no &lt;a href=\"Infusion\"&gt;Infusion&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Duo%20Boons/Hades%20II\"&gt;Duo Boons&lt;/a&gt; with the other gods. Athena offers her boons whenever &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; speaks to her after a Divine Intervation on &lt;a href=\"Mount%20Olympus\"&gt;Mount Olympus&lt;/a&gt; or wields the &lt;a href=\"Gorgon%20Amulet\"&gt;Gorgon Amulet&lt;/a&gt; keepsake on any biome."}
{"id": "1543", "revid": "29110118", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=1543", "title": "Athena/Quotes (Hades)", "text": "\"The following are quotes from &lt;a href=\"Athena\"&gt;Athena&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Hades%20%28game%29\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;\".\nFirst Meeting.\n Zagreus: \n\"It's got to be her. Then, here goes nothing... \"Ahem\". In the name of Hades! Olympus, I accept this message.\" \n Athena: \n\"Hail, noble Cousin. Now, let's get you from that miserable place. I'll see that all of us upon Olympus do our part, beginning here with me.\" \nKeepsake Dialogue (&lt;a href=\"Owl%20Pendant\"&gt;Owl Pendant&lt;/a&gt;).\nKeepsake Equipped.\n Athena: \n\"You bear my Owl Pendant, noble Cousin! Wherever it should go, I faintly see its shimmer from afar. Even where you reside! For owls see in total darkness, after all.\" \nReactions.\nSeeing &lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt; at Low Health.\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"You're badly injured aren't you, Cousin? I wish that I could will the pain away, though at the least I can provide you this.\" \nDialogue 02.\n Athena: \n\"Look at you, Zagreus, you're barely fit to fight from all the injury that you've sustained! I'll try to keep you going for as long as possible.\" \nDialogue 03.\n Athena: \n\"It seems to me that you've sustained life-draining injuries already, Zagreus. But don't lose hope. We can sustain you in a proper fighting shape.\" \nDialogue 04.\n Athena: \n\"You may have suffered many wounds but shall not perish imminently, Cousin. Not if I have anything to say about it. Here.\" \nDialogue 05.\n Athena: \n\"Oh, Zagreus... your recent battles evidently haven't gone as hoped. Nevertheless, always strive onward, while you still draw breath.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Trial%20of%20the%20Gods\"&gt;Trial of the Gods&lt;/a&gt; (Rejection).\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"I thought we were on better terms, Cousin. I ask only for your cooperation, yet still you turn your back...?\" \nDialogue 02.\n Athena: \n\"I'm disappointed you would spurn me like this, Cousin. Know that I retaliate not out of spite, but by necessity.\" \nDialogue 03.\n Athena: \n\"You'd choose one of my relatives, instead of me...? Though I myself was first to contact you? Alas, I must respond to you in kind.\" \nDialogue 04.\n Athena: \n\"Upon Olympus, I'm your closest confidant. You'd best remember this before you spurn me again.\" \nDialogue 05.\n Athena: \n\"We Olympians, we are a prideful family, Cousin. You cannot simply choose a favorite without spurring one of us to wrath.\" \nDialogue 06.\n Athena: \n\"I understand you've made your choice, Cousin. And I, in turn, now have my family's reputation to uphold.\" \nDialogue 07.\n Athena: \n\"If you had given due consideration to this matter, then I doubt you would have chosen this outcome.\" \nDialogue 08.\n Athena: \n\"No one in our family can avoid taking sides forever, Zagreus. But you can take the more sensible side, at least.\" \nDialogue 09.\n Athena: \n\"A senseless, punishable choice. But if you wish to face the consequences, so be it.\" \nDialogue 10.\n Athena: \n\"You could have avoided this outcome any number of ways, yet still you risk incurring my wrath.\" \nDialogue 11.\n Athena: \n\"Are you testing the limits of my patience with you, Zagreus? Then, I shall test your limits, in turn.\" \nDialogue 12.\n Athena: \n\"I knew there was a possibility that you would side against me once again, but your doing so never ceases to amaze, Cousin.\" \nDialogue 13.\n Athena: \n\"If this is your idea of humor, Zagreus, then I shall make it clear to you again that I am unamused.\" \nDialogue 14.\n Athena: \n\"I think we understand by now that when you test my patience, I shall test your ability to survive.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Trial%20of%20the%20Gods\"&gt;Trial of the Gods&lt;/a&gt; (Making Up).\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"\"Oh\", let's continue on, already, Zagreus. There isn't any point in feuding, and there's much to do before your quest is done.\" \nDialogue 02.\n Athena: \n\"Now then! I hope we can move past this little incident, and keep our focus on the task at hand.\" \nDialogue 03.\n Athena: \n\"I'm satisfied we understand each other better, now, don't we. What do you say we carry on, and get you from this place?\" \nDialogue 04.\n Athena: \n\"All is forgiven, Zagreus, and I take no offense. Exacting vengeance is just something we Olympians all do from time to time.\"\nDialogue 05.\n Athena: \n\"I'd say I've bickered with you quite enough for now, Cousin. Let us continue down a more productive path.\" \nDialogue 06.\n Athena: \n\"We've better things to do, I think, than fight amongst ourselves over a matter such as this.\" \nDialogue 07.\n Athena: \n\"I would very much prefer to think we both know better than to let old grudges stew forever, Zagreus.\" \nDialogue 08.\n Athena: \n\"You see I have my father's temper, Zagreus. I am able to keep it in check, though I expect you to do your part.\" \nDialogue 09.\n Athena: \n\"Conflict between the members of our family is inevitable, Zagreus. All we can do is learn and grow from it.\" \nDialogue 10.\n Athena: \n\"I see no benefit to staying angry, Cousin. I promised Nyx that I would help rather than hinder you.\" \nDialogue 11.\n Athena: \n\"Your father also made some questionable choices, Zagreus. But all of us are family, after all.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Trial%20of%20the%20Gods\"&gt;Trial of the Gods&lt;/a&gt; (Killing &lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt;).\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"Wound the pride of an Olympian, and pay the price.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Athena: \n\"Know that this could have been avoided, Zagreus.\"\nDialogue 03.\n Athena: \n\"Perhaps next time you shall cooperate with me again.\"\nGeneric Greetings.\nLong Lines.\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"Keep fighting, Cousin. Fight from out of that eternal gloom. I trust that you'll be joining us upon Olympus shortly.\" \nDialogue 02.\n Athena: \n\"I have your back, Cousin. Rise now to your rightful station with my blessings!\" \nDialogue 03.\n Athena: \n\"May the light and fury of Olympus guide you from the dark, Cousin. I've a token of it for you here.\"\nDialogue 04.\n Athena: \n\"Push forward, noble Cousin. I shall be keen to see you circumvent the perils that the Fates arranged for you this time.\" \nDialogue 05.\n Athena: \n\"Vanquish all who stand against you, noble Cousin. I and your relatives upon Olympus shall assist you in so doing.\" \nDialogue 06.\n Athena: \n\"Sometimes I think about what you've endured, to have been living in that loathsome squalor, Cousin. I swear, you'll have your justice.\" \nDialogue 07.\n Athena: \n\"Do not fear your father's cruel legions, Cousin! Their lives are long since forfeit, and they cannot stand against one of your birthright, nor against my power.\" \nDialogue 08.\n Athena: \n\"Yours is a brazen plan of action, Zagreus, and I admire it. The boldest strategy often prevails. Especially with my support.\" \nDialogue 09.\n Athena: \n\"Take heart, Cousin; for you have found me even in the suffocating darkness of the Underworld. May my power be of some assistance.\" \nDialogue 10.\n Athena: \n\"Your struggles have not gone unnoticed, Cousin, so take heart. Eternity awaits you once you finally break free.\" \nDialogue 11.\n Athena: \n\"Here on Olympus is the opposite of everything about that lifeless squalor you reside in, Zagreus. Fight on and come to us!\" \nDialogue 12.\n Athena: \n\"Cousin, I grow angry merely thinking of your situation. May what power I can offer be of service as you struggle towards your fate.\" \nDialogue 13.\n Athena: \n\"Your father chose to sever ties with all of us, and stew alone within his land beneath the earth. But you are not beholden to his actions. Fight!\" \nDialogue 14.\n Athena: \n\"Your labors make you stronger, noble Cousin. And, the blessings I now offer ought to make you stronger still.\" \nDialogue 15.\n Athena: \n\"I've found you once again, dear Cousin, and my strength is yours; so much of it as I can send there to the bowels of the earth.\" \nDialogue 16.\n Athena: \n\"I'm here again to lend to you my power, noble Cousin. Though your own strength of will is how you'll finally break free of that cruel place.\" \nDialogue 17.\n Athena: \n\"I'm pleased to see your father's stubbornness is manifest in you as such determination, Zagreus. My blessing be with you.\" \nDialogue 18.\n Athena: \n\"What wretched fools dare stand against you, Cousin? Punish them, so that they learn something they ought have learned in life.\" \nDialogue 19.\n Athena: \n\"Hold fast to your resolve, Cousin, and climb on toward the surface. No matter how often your foothold falters, I am here.\" \nDialogue 20.\n Athena: \n\"I shall not keep you, Zagreus, except to offer you some of my power to improve your chances of escape. Now quickly choose, and go.\" \nImproved Relationship Lines.\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"I so look forward to our meeting face to face amongst the gods, dear Cousin. Olympus shall be merrier and wiser once you're here.\" \nDialogue 02.\n Athena: \n\"Hail and good tidings to you, noble Cousin. May you be swift and thorough vanquishing the dead who dare oppose you.\" \nDialogue 03.\n Athena: \n\"Remain relentless in your effort to escape, dear Cousin. In spite of all our differences, perseverance is a quality we all possess.\" \nDialogue 04.\n Athena: \n\"You can always count upon assistance from me, Zagreus. I always shall prioritize the needs of our family above everything else.\" \nDialogue 05.\n Athena: \n\"Let my voice be a glimmer in the darkness, noble Cousin; though, may the blessing I am about to provide be even more than that.\" \nAbout Characters.\n&lt;a href=\"Nyx\"&gt;Nyx&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"I have grown closer than expected with the goddess Nyx in all of this, Cousin. It is quite evident to me how much she cares for you. I must admit I envy your relationship, sometimes. For I've made do without a mother's presence in my life.\" \nDialogue 02.\n Athena: \n\"Lord Ares has suggested he and goddess Nyx have grown much closer to each other, in all this. Nothing untoward, if you must know. Ares and I have often disagreed, about so many things, and yet we share a fondness for the Night herself, it seems.\" \nDialogue 03.\n Athena: \n\"Sometimes I think about the goddess Nyx, and how I long for her to be the mother that I never had, Cousin. Is it improper that I say such things to you? One would expect I would already have somebody on Olympus, yet... it often feels as though I am the mother, here.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Olympians\"&gt;Olympians&lt;/a&gt;.\n Athena: \n\"You've met your distant relatives by now. We don't all share the same demeanor, nor see eye to eye. Though, all of us, I think, wish you the best.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Athena: \n\"I understand you've been in contact with my father. Your uncle Zeus, I mean. He's taken interest in your plight; you should feel honored!\" \n&lt;a href=\"Artemis\"&gt;Artemis&lt;/a&gt;.\n Athena: \n\"I'll tell you something, Cousin: If even Artemis is aiding you, it's proof your cause is just. She doesn't often take an interest in family affairs.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Aphrodite\"&gt;Aphrodite&lt;/a&gt;.\n Athena: \n\"Cousin, you've met Aphrodite, no? She likes beguiling others with her charms; but her intentions with you I believe are pure. You'll find our strengths are complementary.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Ares\"&gt;Ares&lt;/a&gt;.\n Athena: \n\"My warlike brother Ares reached you, didn't he. I've always found his conduct quite disturbing. At least it seems he's helping you for now.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Dionysus\"&gt;Dionysus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Athena: \n\"Did Dionysus truly visit you before? He tends to seek out revelry, not conflict. I'm pleased to know he's making himself useful here.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Hermes\"&gt;Hermes&lt;/a&gt;.\n Athena: \n\"You arrived sooner than anticipated, Cousin, and my estimations seldom are inaccurate. All for the best, of course. Perhaps you're simply faster than I thought.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt;.\n Athena: \n\"You've met the master of the seas, Poseidon, haven't you? Our uncle's affable but quick to anger. Be on your guard with him, is my advice.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Demeter\"&gt;Demeter&lt;/a&gt;.\n Athena: \n\"The biting cold surrounding you must mean the Goddess of Seasons decided to take an interest in your struggle, Zagreus? I did not count on Demeter being a part of this. Take heart, though use discretion around her.\" \nWith Other Characters.\n&lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"Noble cousin, my lord father has taken keen interest in your journey and your plight, and now seeks to aid you with the thunder of heaven itself. And you've my support, as well, of course.\" \n Zeus: \n\"I thank you for the generous introduction, fair Athena, and I always rest assured when you are close at hand. I trust with our combined might, our good Zagreus is virtually certain to succeed!\"\nDialogue 02.\n Zeus: \n\"Why, look, Zagreus, here comes brave Athena, first to reach you among all my kin, in all her shrewdness. So proactive, you contacted Zagreus prior to even telling me, my dear!\" \n Athena: \n\"Lord Father, would that I could settle even more such matters quickly and discreetly, so that only the most vital of them rise up to the level of your notice, sir. Though, I'm certain Zagreus and I are very grateful you have intervened.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Aphrodite\"&gt;Aphrodite&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"Your predicament has pulled our family together, united in a desire to assist you, Cousin. Even those who typically do not think much of those other than themselves.\" \n Aphrodite: \n\"Oh, if only I had wisdom such as yours, Athena dear, so that I was more capable of picking up on subtle jabs and insults such as that! You're not fooling anybody with your feigned benevolence, you know.\" \n Athena: \n\"The world is not all lies and deceit as you make it out to be, Aphrodite. Sometimes, a lending of assistance is no more than it appears to be. Now either back up Zagreus, or stand aside.\" \nDialogue 02.\n Aphrodite: \n\"You must forgive us, little godling, meaning our extended family here upon Olympus! Some of us are terribly stuck up, and must be making matters much more complicated than they have to be.\" \n Athena: \n\"I wonder, dearest Aphrodite, whether you'd be willing to repeat such things directly to my countenance?\" \n Aphrodite: \n\"Oh, you must know full well that I would do much more than that directly to your countenance, Athena dear! Quite frankly, you could use a lot of work!\" \nDialogue 03.\n Aphrodite: \n\"Dearest, you must know, Goddess Athena and myself, we don't always share a common view, perhaps because she overthinks things constantly, while my heart leads me on!\" \n Athena: \n\"I'm glad we understand each other, then. It would be most embarrassing to be caught bickering amongst ourselves in front of Zagreus.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"When I first notified Lord Father Zeus and other members of our family of your existence, Zagreus, it was Uncle Poseidon here who first leapt up, and pledged his power over sea and earth to you. Is that not so, Uncle?\" \n Poseidon: \n\"Exactly so, Athena! You, with that fine memory of yours! For it isn't everyday I learn my doleful brother Hades sired a fine son! He does not know how good he has it, there! And \"you\", Nephew, could have it even better, \"here\"!\" \nDialogue 02.\n Poseidon: \n\"As you can see by now, we are a big and clever family, little Hades! My niece Athena here being the cleverest of all. You'd never know that she was childless, the way she looks after and cares for all of us!\" \n Athena: \n\"Surely my cleverness comes from your brother and yourself, Lord Uncle Poseidon. And I would only add, my feeling is we've more than enough children in this family, thus no further need for more of them, for now.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Ares\"&gt;Ares&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\n Ares: \n\"I wished only to speak to you in private once again, my kin, except, you see...\" \n Athena: \n\"...Except you see, dear Cousin, that some members of our family are predisposed toward the unspeakable. I caution you around my half-brother, is all. Now carry on.\" \n Ares: \n\"You interrupt me once again, dear sister. You know I do not care for that. I warn you to stay out of my affairs. I shall aid my kin as I see fit.\" \n Athena: \n\"You only do as you see fit, Lord Ares. Mind that you continue pulling in the same direction as us all.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Demeter\"&gt;Demeter&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"I bring to you the Lady Demeter, Cousin. I've asked that she please rest assured knowing we have your matter well under control. Though, in her infinite compassion, she has taken up your cause, nevertheless!\" \n Demeter: \n\"Oh, you needn't lavish me with your faint praise, Athena dear. In all your boundless intellect, I'd have expected you would know I see through your intentions, plain as day.\" \nDialogue 02.\n Demeter: \n\"To think, young sprout, our strategist Athena, warrior-goddess, sprang from Zeus' head! I would expect that no high intellect could come from there.\" \n Athena: \n\"Please do not mind the Lady Demeter's good-natured sense of humor, Zagreus. She and my father often like to jest with one another, even in the most difficult times.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Dionysus\"&gt;Dionysus&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"Some members of our family do not yet fully understand just how precarious your situation is, Cousin. My Lord Dionysus here, he goes about as though this is a festive matter of some sort!\" \n Dionysus: \n\"Oh, come on, Athena girl, you really mean to tell me that discovering a long-lost relative isn't a cause for celebrating right away, I mean, you can't be telling me a thing like \"that\"? Because if Zag isn't a cause for feasting, I don't know what is!\" \nDialogue 02.\n Dionysus: \n\"Hey, Zag, when you arrive, it's going to be a real scene, I'll tell you now! Even Athena here will cut loose for a bit, let down her hair, you know, put on something more comfy, yeah, it's going to be \"great\"!\" \n Athena: \n\"Perhaps Lord Dionysus here is the true god of strategy, as it appears he is uncannily aware of my next move, Cousin. Although, be that as it may, I shall attempt to remain focused on your situation. Not his feast.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Artemis\"&gt;Artemis&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"If you've a moment, Zagreus? One of my relatives has claimed that I usurp your time. So I invited her to contact you.\" \n Artemis: \n\"Um, hello, Zagreus... Athena here is grandstanding or trying to prove a point, or something. I don't know. Anyway, nice talking to you.\" \n Athena: \n\"Well, I suppose that's settled, then. I am afraid such interactions aren't uncommon here amongst my family; but what's a family without flaws?\" \nBeing Invited to the &lt;a href=\"House%20of%20Hades\"&gt;House of Hades&lt;/a&gt; (Pre-Epilogue).\n Zagreus: \n\"This is it, then. In the name of Hades! Olympus, this is an official message! Lady Athena, I trust you'll quickly figure this one out.\" \n Athena: \n\"Is this some kind of offering for me? No, hold a moment, this appears to be a message! Part of one. Then, can this mean...? I have to notify the others. I trust they also have received something from you, or shortly shall.\" \nPost-Epilogue Dialogue.\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"It was my privilege to have visited your father's House, and briefly had a chance to meet \"you\", Zagreus. Nyx and your mother each are very shrewd; perhaps you've taken after both of them. As for your new responsibilities... exposing weak points in defenses is my specialty.\" \nDialogue 02.\n Athena: \n\"It's fortunate your troubles with your mother were resolved. Persephone, I mean! To think I led all of my family to believe your mother was the goddess Nyx, instead. It seems I was an unwitting accomplice to a bit of a deception, there. But Nyx, I know she merely tried to help.\" \nMiscellaneous Conversations.\n&lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt; Progressing in a Run.\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"It comforts me to see how far you've come, Cousin. And I am confident that you shall make your way, eventually. I shall look forward to our conversations then.\" \nDialogue 02.\n Athena: \n\"You reached the flames of Asphodel, well done! You may have quite a distance still to go, but having crossed through Tartarus is no small step, Cousin.\" \nDialogue 03.\n Athena: \n\"I see you've made it all the way to hallowed Elysium, Cousin? A significant way toward the surface, and if you could get there the one time, surely you have what it takes to do it again, and overcome the dangers that await therein.\" \nDialogue 04.\n Athena: \n\"I understand you nearly reached the surface lately, Zagreus. My confidence remains unshaken that you shall get out of there, eventually. No matter what sorts of unknown horrors lie shrouded beyond the boundary there.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt; Clearing a Run.\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"Were you not close to having reached the surface lately, Cousin? Then, this can only mean some unforeseen impediment prevented your escape.\" \nDialogue 02.\n Athena: \n\"There must be some unconquerable force or foe awaiting you, just at the border of your realm and ours. We cannot even see it through a shroud of darkness, there. I shall make certain that your family knows it may take considerable time to surpass... so fear not, for we are patient, here.\" \nDialogue 03.\n Athena: \n\"Despite whatever difficulties you've encountered, dear Cousin, again and again, you have never yielded. I must admit, your strength of will is quite inspiring. For, even I have doubts, from time to time. It's all the clearer to me why the goddess Nyx spoke so highly of you.\" \nBuying Boon at &lt;a href=\"Charon\"&gt;Charon&lt;/a&gt;'s Shop.\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"It feels unseemly to make contact from that most-unpleasant boatman's stash of ill-gotten wares. Nonetheless, this was an opportunity.\" \nDialogue 02.\n Athena: \n\"You're difficult to track there in the depths, Cousin; though, the boatman Charon thankfully is proving of some help.\" \nDialogue 03.\n Athena: \n\"The river-boatman Charon is beholden to your father's realm, but seems agreeable enough, for a fair price.\" \nDialogue 04.\n Athena: \n\"A shrewd expenditure of wealth is sometimes all that stands between a victory and sore defeat, isn't that right, Cousin?\" \nDialogue 05.\n Athena: \n\"We cannot effectively communicate with Charon from Olympus, but he is amenable to certain trades, and seems unfettered by your father's influence.\" \nHigh Affinity Dialogue.\n Athena: \n\"Supporting you through your ordeal, Cousin? It's reminiscent of the thrill of doing battle by the side of those whom I hold dear. I may be safe upon our mountaintop, though I am with you there, as well... for every well-earned victory, and bitter loss.\"\nAbout Backstory.\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"The one called Nyx... she is your mother, as I understand? We Olympians rarely consort with the chthonic gods. Though Nyx herself reached out to me about your plight, and I was spurred to act.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Athena: \n\"Please send the goddess Nyx my kind regards. That she supports you in your effort to escape her own domain suggests a selflessness I would not have expected.\" \nDialogue 03.\n Athena: \n\"It's such a cruelty that your father hid the knowledge of your birth and life from us, my cousin. It's unacceptable.\" \nDialogue 04.\n Athena: \n\"Your father Hades and my father Zeus have not communicated in some time, and Zeus refuses to explain. Something transpired between the two of them. Perhaps you know better than I.\" \nDialogue 05.\n Athena: \n\"There's something that I've wished to tell you, Zagreus: There is no shame in your upbringing. Many of us on Olympus, we likewise were born and raised under the strangest circumstances. Someday I'll have to tell you about mine.\" \nPost-Flashback Dialogue.\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"You're nothing like your father, Zagreus. I mean that as a compliment. He cut himself off from the rest of us. Many times have we attempted peace, to no avail.\" \nAbout Legendary Boon.\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"You cannot withstand your father's legions, Zagreus. But if you possess one of my greatest blessings, things may unfold differently, I think.\" \nDialogue 02.\n Athena: \n\"Dear Cousin, would that I could give to you everlasting, tireless resolve. Though, come to think of it, this may be suited as a counterpart.\" \nDialogue 03.\n Athena: \n\"For you, my cousin Zagreus, I wish to offer the most potent of the blessings I am able to bestow. Make wise your use of this, and rise toward us!\" \nDialogue 04.\n Athena: \n\"The circumstances spur me now to offer you the greatest of my powers, Cousin. Take my strength, and strike the darkness down!\" \nAbout Hades' &lt;a href=\"Sigil%20of%20the%20Dead\"&gt;Keepsake&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"Zagreus, perhaps it is a fancy of imagination, but it seems almost as though, this time, you bear the blessing of... your own father! If Lord Hades is assisting you in any way in this, then I shall hold out hope that your relationship yet has capacity to heal, to some extent at least.\" \nDialogue 02.\n Athena: \n\"So you've another blessing from Lord Hades, then. Zagreus, I'm under no delusion you and your father shall become the closest friends, from here. Neverthless, I do believe it's possible to move forward even such a relationship as yours. Believe me... I know.\" \nAbout The &lt;a href=\"Fated%20List%20of%20Minor%20Prophecies\"&gt;Fated List of Minor Prophecies&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"The goddess Nyx has indicated you possess a list of prophecies from the Three Fates. I've such a list upon Olympus, here! It seems to be connected to your own, as several prophecies already are fulfilled. Isn't it such an honor to urge Fate along?\" \nAbout Weapons.\nDialogue 01 (&lt;a href=\"Eternal%20Spear\"&gt;Varatha&lt;/a&gt;).\n Athena: \n\"You brandish the Eternal Spear we call Varatha...! So then it wasn't lost during the war. A magnificent weapon, in deserving hands.\" \nDialogue 02 (&lt;a href=\"Heart-Seeking%20Bow\"&gt;Coronacht&lt;/a&gt;).\n Athena: \n\"Why, you wield Coronacht the Heart-Seeker...! I never took you for an archer, though the power of that bow is undeniable. Use it wisely!\" \nDialogue 03 (&lt;a href=\"Shield%20of%20Chaos\"&gt;Aegis&lt;/a&gt;).\n Athena: \n\"You bear Aegis, the original itself...! My own shield was forged much later, in its image. You'll have to tell me someday how you found it.\" \nDialogue 04 (&lt;a href=\"Adamant%20Rail\"&gt;Exagryph&lt;/a&gt;).\n Athena: \n\"The Rail of Adamant, itself, has found its way into your hands, Cousin? A malignant thing, if you were to ask me, and not one I would ever use, myself. Unless, perhaps, I had no other choice. I suppose it must have been that way for you.\" \nDialogue 05 (&lt;a href=\"Twin%20Fists\"&gt;Malphon&lt;/a&gt;).\n Athena: \n\"You got your hands on Malphon, the Twin Fists, I see. No ordinary weapon. Prone to fits of savagery quite unbecoming of a well-trained warrior. Then watch yourself, and throw not caution to the wind.\" \nGifts.\n&lt;a href=\"Nectar\"&gt;Nectar&lt;/a&gt;.\n1st Time.\n Zagreus: \n\"I'm indebted to you, Goddess, for all that you and your side of the family have done for me.\" \n Athena: \n\"Well it simply isn't in my nature to allow such offerings to go unanswered, noble Cousin. In turn, I wish for you to have this, with my compliments.\" \n\"Athena gives &lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt; the &lt;a href=\"Owl%20Pendant\"&gt;Owl Pendant&lt;/a&gt;.\"\n Zagreus: \n\"Lady Athena, thank you.\"\n2nd Time.\n Zagreus: \n\"For you, Lady Athena, without whom I would assuredly be lost.\" \n Athena: \n\"This is an unexpected gesture, Cousin! I do appreciate it, though please do not feel obliged. I offer you my friendship, not a loan to be repaid.\" \n3rd Time.\n Zagreus: \n\"I have a simple token for you, Goddess. Although it's insufficient thanks for all the aid you've given me.\" \n Athena: \n\"You are most gracious, Cousin, to extend this offering. You honor me, yet I would ask you think of your well-being for the time, not mine.\" \n4th Time.\n Zagreus: \n\"Goddess Athena, please accept this gift. Your wisdom ever guides me toward the light.\" \n Athena: \n\"My, how very generous of you, to offer me this gift! I'm very grateful, though I ask that you not go out of your way on my account. Let's please stay focused, here?\" \n5th Time.\nOption A.\n Zagreus: \n\"As I remain committed to my task, Goddess, I'm reminded none of this would have been possible without your aid. And so, I must give thanks, even if through a meager offering.\" \n Athena: \n\"I know there isn't much that you can do to show your gratitude at present, Zagreus. But I would ask that you save it for when your task is complete. You've more important matters to attend to now!\" \nOption B.\n Zagreus: \n\"As I remain committed to my task, Goddess, I'm reminded none of this would have been possible without your aid. And so, I must give thanks, even if through a meager offering.\" \n Athena: \n\"I know there isn't much that you can do to show your gratitude at present, Zagreus. But I would ask that you save it for a better time. You've more important matters to attend to, now!\" \n6th Time.\n Zagreus: \n\"Lady Athena, I know there's more at stake for you in this than just my plight... you care so much about this family. That care and your determination spurs me on. I'm ever grateful.\" \n Athena: \n\"Perhaps there really is no time quite like the present when it comes to showing thanks to one another, my dear Cousin. You've opened my eyes to the possibility, though I remain steadfast in my resolve to fight for you.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Ambrosia\"&gt;Ambrosia&lt;/a&gt;.\n1st Time.\n Zagreus: \n\"I know this Ambrosia originated on Olympus, Lady Athena. Though through its long voyage to these depths, I trust its savor is more worthy of your grace. No one's ever had a greater cousin. And I'll never forget what you've done for me.\" \n Athena: \n\"Zagreus? When Nyx revealed herself to me and I first learned of you, I saw it as an opportunity to bridge the great divide between Olympus and your father's realm. But, having had all these glimpses into who you are, it is an even greater honor to have forged this partnership with you.\" "}
{"id": "5240", "revid": "29110118", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5240", "title": "Athena/Quotes (Hades II)", "text": "\"The following are quotes from &lt;a href=\"Athena\"&gt;Athena&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Hades%20II\"&gt;Hades II&lt;/a&gt;.\"\nFirst Meeting.\n Athena: \n\"The noble Princess of the Dead, at last! I am your cousin Athena, and proud to welcome you to Olympus. Yet I could be prouder, as this wasn't always such a miserable place.\"\n Melino\u00eb: \n\"Hail, Lady Athena and well met! Please call me Melino\u00eb. Now where can I direct my wrath, that we may liberate your mountain stronghold and see its glory all restored?\" \n Athena: \n\"Well met indeed, Melino\u00eb. The wretched Titan's armies have infiltrated our most sacred grounds. On them, your wrath may be well-spent; especially as you rise towards the summit, where most of our family now takes refuge.\" \n Melino\u00eb: \n\"The Palace of Zeus. And what of you, why aren't the others out here fighting by your side?\" \n Athena: \n\"Because that is precisely what our strategy requires, for they aided your arrival, did they not? Now, let us go our separate ways, and may my blessing aid in your ascent.\" \nAbout Characters.\n&lt;a href=\"Arachne\"&gt;Arachne&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Melino\u00eb: \n\"Lady Athena, by your leave ... we have a mutual acquaintance I would ask about, because ... well ... do you recall the weaver Arachne?\"\n Athena: \n\"I seldom forget anything, Cousin. Especially not insolent mortals who see themselves as equal to the gods. Though she is not exactly mortal anymore. What of her?\"\n Melino\u00eb: \n\"Well ... she lives down in Erebus now, near where I reside, and ... she's so wretched about her appearance, which I understand is from a curse you wrought ... doubtless entirely deserved, but ... have mercy on her, Lady Athena. Please.\"\n Athena: \n\"So many mortals grovel to me all the time. But goddesses? And on behalf of mortals far too prideful to grovel for themselves? Cousin, do not waste my time with this.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Athena: \n\"The mortal woman called Arachne. Have you any idea what she did? She fancied herself the greatest weaver in the world; superior even to me, if not the Fates themselves? Is it not our obligation, then, to remind mortals of their place?\"\n Melino\u00eb: \n\"I ... can't say I rightly know the answer to that, Lady Athena. Nor would I ever question your decision about her! I only ask if the term of her punishment could be less than eternal. She's humbled, and she's learned from her mistakes.\"\n Athena: \n\"Has she, now? In my experience mortals can be \"very\" slow to learn. And she was not punished as a lesson to \"her\", but as a lesson to \"everyone else\". I do not go back on my decisions, Melino\u00eb. For I don't make them lightly.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Dionysus\"&gt;Dionysus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Athena: \n\"I must say, Cousin ... I've not seen such unity from our family in some time. Almost everybody stands together now against our foes. Though Dionysus, probably he's lying somewhere in a stupor.\"\n Melino\u00eb: \n\"If Lord Dionysus hasn't taken up arms against the forces of Chronos, surely he has his reasons ...\"\n Athena: \n\"Oh, he does. Why should he callus his hands, when he could laze about feasting? He's fortunate I've more important matters to consider than locating him.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Heracles\"&gt;Heracles&lt;/a&gt;.\n Athena: \n\"You have perhaps encountered mighty Heracles along your route. He has surpassing strength and capability, but do report to me any suspicious actions on his part.\"\n Melino\u00eb: \n\"I have encountered him, and seen him lay waste droves of our foes, though he's not been keen on conversation. Which sorts of suspicious activities do you mean?\"\n Athena: \n\"Consorting with our foes, defying our will, anything of that sort. I have no real reason not to trust him, yet ... I've come to trust you more.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Persephone\"&gt;Persephone&lt;/a&gt;.\n Athena: \n\"After we settled certain troubles with your brother's situation at home, your mother Persephone, she would regularly return to Olympus for part of each year. I should have trusted my instincts when one day she failed to show ...\"\n Melino\u00eb: \n\"Presumably when Chronos struck. Wouldn't her sudden disappearance have been cause for considerable alarm?\"\n Athena: \n\"You'd think. However, we knew your mother was with child, and our conclusion was that your new family wanted privacy. So we waited patiently, not realizing it as Chronos gained his foothold. A grave miscalculation on my part ...\"\n Melino\u00eb: \n\"Your father and mine first fought and vanquished Chronos long before either of us was born. You couldn't have expected the Titan Lord to suddenly return.\"\n Athena: \n\"Yet if I'm to be the strategist upon Olympus then I have to consider each possibility, however unlikely, that can threaten our peace. At any rate, a lesson harshly learned ...\"\n&lt;a href=\"Prometheus\"&gt;Prometheus&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"Beware ahead. The Titan Prometheus is able to elude me, knowing that I'm focused on his vanguard forces. But he'll have no choice but to confront you if you press on.\"\n Melino\u00eb: \n\"He's the Titan of Foresight. He knows exactly what we're planning, doesn't he? And can retaliate accordingly.\"\n Athena: \n\"He knows what is to come to some extent, yes. But he can only see outcomes, not read minds. And just because he knows you're coming doesn't mean he can stop you.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Melino\u00eb: \n\"Have you confronted Prometheus before? You mentioned he's been able to elude you. Perhaps he knows he'd stand no chance against you if you fought.\"\n Athena: \n\"I knew Prometheus prior to all this. I suppose our tendencies towards matters of the mind connected us. You know that he stole the gift of fire for mortalkind. Well ... he also gave them reason, from me. Some of them, anyway.\"\n Melino\u00eb: \n\"I shudder to think what mortals must have been like before they had any reason. Although perhaps Prometheus ought to have kept some reason for himself.\"\n Athena: \n\"Perhaps he thinks he did, or has as much as he requires. Unfortunately, reason tends to be in lesser abundance than most would dare to admit.\"\nDialogue 03.\n Athena: \n\"Even if you're thwarted by the Titan Prometheus, it is a benefit to our war effort. For if he's having to confront you, then he's unable to cause his mayhem elsewhere.\"\n Melino\u00eb: \n\"That is of little consolation to me, Lady Athena. This is not his first crime against Olympus and our family; thus his punishment is to be even more severe.\"\n Athena: \n\"Do not concern yourself with that. His prior punishment inspired this still-greater transgression, rather than remorse for his past deeds. For the moment, our strategy merely requires that he no stand in our way.\" \n&lt;a href=\"Selene\"&gt;Selene&lt;/a&gt;.\n Athena: \n\"The Moon herself assists you, that I know. We often underestimate her here, believing all she does is faintly light the sky. But I know there is more to her than that.\"\n Melino\u00eb: \n\"Selene may be a Titaness but she's an ally to us through and through. She upholds Night's will, as do I.\"\n Athena: \n\"Nyx's will is none of my concern, Cousin. But apparently it's yours, and Nyx has likewise been an ally to Olympus in the past. If you trust Selene's involvement, that is enough.\"\nGifts.\n&lt;a href=\"Nectar\"&gt;Nectar&lt;/a&gt;.\n1st Time.\n Melino\u00eb: \n\"Lady Athena, while we have a moment, I wish to offer you this Nectar as a token of my gratitude. If I'd only known that we would meet here, perhaps I'd have arrived even sooner.\"\n Athena: \n\"Nonsense, for I'm certain that you made your journey here as quickly as you could. Well, I of course accept your offering, though shall be saving it for when our victory's achieved. This, however, you may be able to use sooner ...\"\n\"Athena gives &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; the &lt;a href=\"Keepsakes/Hades%20II\"&gt;Gorgon Amulet&lt;/a&gt;.\"\n Melino\u00eb: \n\"You honor me with such a gift, Goddess.\"\n2nd Time.\n Athena: \n\"\"Huh.\" Try as I might to consider each possibility, partaking of Nectar in the midst of conflict that we're in is quite unthinkable. Still, it's something to look forward to.\" \n Melino\u00eb: \n\"If it's something to look forward to, then it's a greater gift than I thought. The idea of a sip of Nectar while at peace ... it does sound good.\"\n3rd Time.\n Athena: \n\"Your gesture in unnecessary. Warring mortals often make me offerings in hopes that I might guide them to victory. But you and I have a shared purpose, so I require no such incentives in our case.\" \n Melino\u00eb: \n\"This is no incentive, merely a way of saying thank you. For accepting me, and recognizing what potential I may have to aid our family in a time of need.\"\n4th Time.\n Athena: \n\"You honor me, and have my thanks. This Nectar, it's been to the Underworld and back ... along with you. It'll take on a particularly complex flavor, I should think.\"\n Melino\u00eb: \n\"If this bottle indeed traveled to the ends of the earth before returning home, then it's all the more suited to someone of your wisdom and experience. May you enjoy it once you lay down your arms.\""}
{"id": "2506", "revid": "47838920", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2506", "title": "Athena/Relationships", "text": "Family.\n&lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt;: Athena's father.&lt;br&gt;Athena is possibly his favorite daughter. Athena knows how to address her father appropriately, much more so than any of his other descendants on Mount Olympus. Athena praises him elaborately and shows respect to the great king of Olympus. Although she probably disapproves of some of his imprudent actions, which often lead her to intervene.\nWhile Zeus enjoys boasting, according to Athena, she herself would prefer to handle things more \"discreetly,\" in contrast to the occasional sensationalism her father causes. However, she is grateful for him having intervened and wielded his power over the lightning bolts.\nAlthough Athena says she is very different from her father and bears no resemblance to him beyond being a family member, she is equally willing to act imperiously and punish Zagreus should he choose another offering, showing that they are much more alike than she cares to admit.\n&lt;a href=\"Ares\"&gt;Ares&lt;/a&gt;: Athena's half-brother.&lt;br&gt;Alongside Ares, her half-brother, Athena represents military strategy, while Ares represents bloodshed. The two are war gods with opposing perspectives and temperaments. Athena disapproves of Ares' style, and he warns her to stay out of his own business. Despite their sibling quarrels, Ares considers Athena a worthy adversary and praises her battle strategy to Zagreus. Athena is quite cordial and respectful towards her fellow Olympians, including Ares, despite how much they butt heads. She also comments that despite their differences, \"[they] both share a fondness for the night herself\". \n&lt;a href=\"Hephaestus\"&gt;Hephaestus&lt;/a&gt;: Athena's half-brother. \nTheir relationship is currently unknown. \n&lt;a href=\"Artemis\"&gt;Artemis&lt;/a&gt;: Athena's half-sister.&lt;br&gt;Athena isn't a fan of her familial withdrawals, antisocial attitudes, or her younger half-sister's prolonged monologues. Artemis comments to Zagreus that she's never sure if Athena is showing off or trying to prove something. Athena retorts, commenting that such interactions between the two are not uncommon for sisters; \"and what is a perfect family without routine fights?\"\n&lt;a href=\"Apollo\"&gt;Apollo&lt;/a&gt;: Athena's half-brother.&lt;br&gt;Their relationship is currently unknown.\n&lt;a href=\"Hermes\"&gt;Hermes&lt;/a&gt;: Athena's half-brother.&lt;br&gt;Athena finds fault with her brother's secrecy and tendency to withhold information. He believes his stepsister is overly curious and overly problem-solving. Athena is worried that her brother's meddling could do more harm than good.\n&lt;a href=\"Dionysus\"&gt;Dionysus&lt;/a&gt;: Athena's half-brother.&lt;br&gt;She indirectly criticizes him, suggesting that some of his relatives are participating only because they consider all of this a festival. However, it can be suggested that, unlike Athena, who may be acting, he genuinely thinks discovering a long-lost relative is cause for celebration.\n&lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt;: Athena's uncle.&lt;br&gt;Poseidon and Athena incredibly seem to have a positive relationship between them. She comments that, when she enlisted her family's help to help Zagreus, her uncle Poseidon was the first who jumped in and pledged his power over sea and land. Poseidon says that his niece Athena is the smartest of the family, and by the way she takes care of everyone, no one would know that she doesn't have children.\nDespite this, even with his amiable demeanor, he easily becomes irritating, and she prefers to stay cautious around him.\n&lt;a href=\"Demeter\"&gt;Demeter&lt;/a&gt;: Athena's foster aunt.&lt;br&gt;Athena greets her foster aunt with reverence, addressing her as \"Lady Demeter,\" a gesture that underscores her respect for the Olympian authority figure she is. Athena didn't anticipate Demeter to be involved in the cause, presuming that Demeter might not have much interest in Zagreus' cause and that she should be immersed in her ongoing acts of infinite boundless benevolence these days.\nAlthough grateful for any assistance, Athena finds Demeter's cold and capricious temperament unpleasant. She advises exercising caution and discretion in her presence, recognizing the need for care and tact when engaging with this particular goddess.\n&lt;a href=\"Hestia\"&gt;Hestia&lt;/a&gt;: Athena's foster aunt.\nTheir relationship is currently unknown.\n&lt;a href=\"Aphrodite\"&gt;Aphrodite&lt;/a&gt;: The Goddess of Love and Beauty.&lt;br&gt;Athena and Aphrodite are like oil and water, Athena tries to maintain composure in front of her Olympic and cousin companions, with Aphrodite being the only exception; the two will openly insult each other in front of Zagreus and make no attempt to hide it. If she and Aphrodite are together, she will immediately express her disdain but puts it aside to help Zagreus. Even by Olympic standards, the two simply do not like each other, and their double-edged benefits often result in Zagreus being thrown in the middle of their feud.\nChthonic Gods.\nAthena reaches out to them for assistance in aiding Zagreus, as part of a grander scheme to reconcile relations between the Chthonic and Olympian deities.\nZagreus.\n&lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt;: Athena's cousin.&lt;br&gt;Athena, compared to the other Olympians, tends to be impersonal and is the only one who doesn't give Zagreus an affectionate nickname as she is busy coming up with a strategy. Athena will always try to dissuade Zagreus whenever he gives her a bottle of nectar because she doesn't want to be rewarded for helping him. Despite her aloofness, the goddess of wisdom is also probably the most benevolent Olympian, helping Zagreus partially because it's the right thing to do and not just because he's family...but mostly because they're family.\nHades.\n&lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;: Athena's uncle.&lt;br&gt; \nAs a god from a previous generation, Athena shows a lot of respect for her uncle, and despite being a goddess with argumentative abilities, not even she is able to convince him to change his mind when he puts something into his thick head.\nNyx.\n&lt;a href=\"Nyx\"&gt;Nyx&lt;/a&gt;: Night Incarnate.&lt;br&gt;Athena seems to be on good terms with Nyx, whom she considers to be shrewd. She is one of the first Olympians to respond to Nyx's plea to help Zagreus. At one point, she confesses that she sometimes envies Zagreus' relationship with his (foster) mother, having never had one herself.\nHouse of Hades.\nAchilles.\n&lt;a href=\"Achilles\"&gt;Achilles&lt;/a&gt;: former prot\u00e9g\u00e9.&lt;br&gt;Athena was once the patron of a young Achilles during tumultuous times in his past, during the \"Trojan War\".\nDusa.\n&lt;a href=\"Dusa\"&gt;Dusa&lt;/a&gt;: Duty-Bound Gorgon.&lt;br&gt;Although the nature of her relationship with Athena remains undisclosed, it is noteworthy that whenever Athena makes an appearance on screen, she noticeably displays terror and seeks to conceal herself in order to avoid being seen by the goddess."}
