{"id": "326", "revid": "45030189", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=326", "title": "Boons", "text": "Boons are upgrades given by the &lt;a href=\"Characters%23Gods\"&gt;gods&lt;/a&gt; to help &lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt; in his attempts to escape the underworld. They can be obtained as rewards for clearing a room marked with the respective god's symbol or purchased for 150 from &lt;a href=\"Charon\"&gt;Charon's&lt;/a&gt; shop. Boons only last for the duration of a run; they disappear when Zagreus dies and is sent back to the &lt;a href=\"House%20of%20Hades\"&gt;House of Hades&lt;/a&gt;. \nGods.\nEquipping a &lt;a href=\"keepsake\"&gt;keepsake&lt;/a&gt; given by one of the gods (except Hermes or Chaos) ensures that the next time a boon is offered, it will be from that specific god. It does \"not\" guarantee that the very next reward will be a god boon - only that, the first time one appears, it will be from that god. Chaos and Hermes boons can appear before any other god boon regardless of the keepsake you are using.\nSlots.\nZagreus' Attack, Special, Cast, Dash, and Call abilities have one boon slot, and cannot hold multiple ability boons.\nFor example, you cannot have both Cast from &lt;a href=\"Aphrodite\"&gt;Aphrodite&lt;/a&gt; (Crush Shot) and &lt;a href=\"Dionysus\"&gt;Dionysus&lt;/a&gt; (Trippy Shot). However, a god may offer to replace another god's exclusive Boon slot with their own. Exchanges increase rarity of the slot by one, keeping the level the same. In the above example, Dionysus may offer to replace your Crush Shot (Rank 2) with Trippy Shot (Rank 2).\nThis core ability slots follow the same nomenclature:\nHere follow the Boons design for all gods that offer Attack, Special, Cast, Dash, and Call Boons.\nBoon Rarity.\nThere are four 'standard' rarities of boon available, each more powerful than the last:\n\"More powerful\" has a similar meaning as leveling the boon up (i.e. the same numbers get bigger), but +1 rarity and +1 level will have different results. The exact formula is currently unsolved.\n rarity is available through exchanging an -rarity boon, choosing Ambrosia Delight from &lt;a href=\"Eurydice\"&gt;Eurydice&lt;/a&gt;, or from cultivating boons with Rare Crop from &lt;a href=\"Demeter\"&gt;Demeter&lt;/a&gt;. Note that the Yarn of Ariadne from the &lt;a href=\"Well%20of%20Charon\"&gt;Well of Charon&lt;/a&gt;, and the Refreshing Nectar from Eurydice, \"cannot\" offer a heroic boon, even with the Exclusive Access duo boon from &lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Dionysus\"&gt;Dionysus&lt;/a&gt;, which makes every future boon to be at least an -rarity boon.\nBoons that are rewarded from &lt;a href=\"Infernal%20Gate\"&gt;Erebus&lt;/a&gt; encounters, mini-boss encounters (both types are denoted with a small skull on the chamber preview) or bought at a higher price from Charon in the Temple of Styx are more likely to have higher rarities.\nSpecial Boons.\nThere are four types of special boons that are only offered after meeting certain requirements: \nSpecial boon requirements include clearing a curse or acquiring specific standard boons. Special boons cannot be upgraded with &lt;a href=\"Pom%20of%20Power\"&gt;Pom of Power&lt;/a&gt;. "}
{"id": "3560", "revid": "4008728", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3560", "title": "Boons/Hades II", "text": "Boons are upgrades given by the &lt;a href=\"Hades_II%23The_Olympians\"&gt;gods&lt;/a&gt; to help &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; in her attempts to kill &lt;a href=\"Chronos\"&gt;Chronos&lt;/a&gt;. They can be obtained as rewards for clearing a room marked with the respective god's symbol or purchased for 150 from &lt;a href=\"Charon\"&gt;Charon's&lt;/a&gt; shop. Boons only last for the duration of a run; they disappear when Melino\u00eb retreats to &lt;a href=\"The%20Crossroads\"&gt;The Crossroads&lt;/a&gt;.\nGods.\nEquipping a &lt;a href=\"keepsake\"&gt;keepsake&lt;/a&gt; given by one of the gods (except Hermes or Chaos) ensures that the next time a boon is offered, it will be from that specific god. It does \"not\" guarantee that the very next reward will be a god boon - only that, the first time one appears, it will be from that god. Chaos and Hermes boons can appear before any other god boon regardless of the keepsake you are using.\nSlots.\nMelino\u00eb's Attack, Special, Cast, Sprint, and Magick slots are exclusive, and cannot hold multiple ability boons. \nFor example, you cannot have both Cast from &lt;a href=\"Aphrodite\"&gt;Aphrodite&lt;/a&gt; (Rapture Ring) and &lt;a href=\"Apollo\"&gt;Apollo&lt;/a&gt; (Solar Ring). However, a god may offer to replace another god's exclusive Boon slot with their own. Exchanges increase rarity of the slot by one, keeping the level the same. In the above example, Apollo may offer to replace your Rapture Ring (Rank 2) with Solar Ring (Rank 2).\nThis core ability slots follow the same nomenclature:\nHere follow the Boons design for all gods that offer Attack, Special, Cast, Sprint, and Magick Boons.\nBoon Rarity.\nThere are four 'standard' rarities of boon available, each more powerful than the last:\nCurrently bugged: While a rarity of 'normal' boon exists as a sacrifice option for a boon, choosing it will cause the replaced boon\u2019s rarity to revert to Common.\n\"More powerful\" has a similar meaning as leveling the boon up (i.e. the same numbers get bigger), but +1 rarity and +1 level can vary depending on the type of boon.\nAbilities Description.\nMelino\u00eb's Attack, Special, and Cast each have unique \u03a9 versions. Since certain boons apply exclusively to specific moves, the descriptions use precise terminology\u2014singular, plural, or individual terms\u2014to minimize confusion.\nFor example,\nTo clarify these terms, the following nomenclature is used across ability descriptions:\nSpecial Boons.\nThere are six types of special boons that are only offered after meeting certain requirements: \nSpecial boon requirements include clearing a curse or acquiring specific standard boons. Special boons cannot be upgraded with &lt;a href=\"Pom%20of%20Power\"&gt;Pom of Power&lt;/a&gt;. "}
{"id": "4376", "revid": "54583845", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4376", "title": "Boozer", "text": "Boozers are undead sailors hopping around the ghost ships of &lt;a href=\"Rift%20of%20Thessaly\"&gt;Thessaly&lt;/a&gt; from within rum casks.\nBoozers will hop back a short ways and then lurch forward, slashing their sword in an arc in front of them. They will quickly repeat this attack, which can reach similar distances to Melino\u00eb's Dash. They also utilize a short-range stab. "}
{"id": "1032", "revid": "54583845", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=1032", "title": "Bother", "text": "Bothers are spirits made up of the ashes of multiple deceased mortals. These spirits take up residence in burial urns to combine their strength in an attempt to escape the Underworld. They can be found crawling about in the highest reaches of the Underworld, the &lt;a href=\"Temple%20of%20Styx\"&gt;Temple of Styx&lt;/a&gt;. \nThey resemble and attack similarly to &lt;a href=\"Wretched%20Pest\"&gt;Wretched Pests&lt;/a&gt;, but are much stronger.\nWhen a Bother spots &lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt;, it will move away from him in an attempt to find a safe position to fire from. Shortly after, it will launch a bright purple projectile into the air which falls in an arc, causing a large AoE explosion when they come into contact with the ground. The damage done by these will only affect Zagreus, unlike the traps created by Wretched Pests. Also unlike Pests, Bothers will move continuously, rather than try to hide and blend in. \nA large red indicator showing the landing spot of the projectile and the entire area affected appears as soon as they are fired. \nThe projectiles can be deflected, but only when they are close to the ground, which happens when they have either just been fired or about to land.\nA larger, tougher Bother will serve as a possible encounter at the end of one of the Satyr Tunnels. This Bother will send several blasts out at once, surrounding itself in a wide radius to discourage players from getting close enough to attack."}
{"id": "583", "revid": "47838920", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=583", "title": "Bouldy", "text": "Bouldy is &lt;a href=\"Sisyphus\"&gt;Sisyphus&lt;/a&gt;' boulder and constant companion. As his punishment for cheating death, Sisyphus is forced to push Bouldy up a hill constantly, only to have him roll back to the bottom, repeating this process for eternity. Over time, however, Bouldy has become something of a confidante for Sisyphus rather than merely a source of unending torment.\nBouldy returns in &lt;a href=\"Hades%20II\"&gt;Hades II&lt;/a&gt;, having been left to keep &lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt; company by Sisyphus.\nCharacteristics and Personality.\nBouldy does not seem to like talking very much, but &lt;a href=\"Sisyphus\"&gt;Sisyphus&lt;/a&gt; considers him a good friend and confidant.\nAlthough Bouldy is claimed to be a living being, he is never heard or seen moving on screen, but Sisyphus seems to be able to understand what he is saying; however, this is likely just Sisyphus's imagination.\nIt is massively questioned whether Bouldy really is alive or not. If &lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt; offers Bouldy &lt;a href=\"Nectar\"&gt;Nectar&lt;/a&gt;, Bouldy will apparently happily accept the gift and somehow gives Zagreus the Heart of Stone boon implying that he does seem to possess some form of sapience. Furthermore, &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; mentions feeling some sort of energy coming from him. \nPhysical description.\nBouldy is a large, spherical, moss-green anthropomorphic stone with a happy expression, chained to its companion, &lt;a href=\"Sisyphus\"&gt;Sisyphus&lt;/a&gt;, with metal links. Bouldy's facial features are quite stony.\nIn Hades II, Bouldy is now covered in moss in some areas. The moss forms a sort of hairline, beard and eyebrows on Bouldy.\nHades.\nAs Zagreus goes on his escape attempts, Bouldy is seen with Sisyphus in &lt;a href=\"Tartarus\"&gt;Tartarus&lt;/a&gt;. He isn't up for talk at first, but after some encouragement from his companion, the prince will finally start talking with him and build a friendship. From then on, Bouldy is willing to lend a little help to Zagreus at the price of one Nectar.\nOnce Sisyphus's contract is revised and he's no longer bound to his previous torment, he still decides to stay in Tartarus, mostly to stay with Bouldy, among other reasons.\nHades II.\nHades was sent to Sisyphus' chamber after &lt;a href=\"Chronos\"&gt;Chronos&lt;/a&gt; took control of the Underworld. Before he left, Sisyphus told Bouldy to keep &lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt; company until more arrived.\nBouldy cannot be interacted until the chamber is reached without &lt;a href=\"Cerberus\"&gt;Cerberus&lt;/a&gt; in it.\nAmbrosia.\nAlthough Bouldy cannot be gifted &lt;a href=\"Ambrosia\"&gt;Ambrosia&lt;/a&gt;, he can be gifted &lt;a href=\"Nectar\"&gt;Nectar&lt;/a&gt; once per escape attempt. However, he lacks an Affinity level.\nCodex Entry.\n\"Bouldy does not have a Codex entry.\"\nGallery.\n&lt;tabber&gt;\nConcept=\nIllustration=\n&lt;/tabber&gt;"}
