{"id": "4353", "revid": "55184635", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4353", "title": "Chrab", "text": ""}
{"id": "2288", "revid": "44872912", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2288", "title": "Chronos", "text": "Chronos is the &lt;a href=\"Titan\"&gt;Titan&lt;/a&gt; of Time, the father of &lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt; and the main antagonist of \"&lt;a href=\"Hades%20II\"&gt;Hades II&lt;/a&gt;\". \nHe has escaped from his prison in the depths of &lt;a href=\"Tartarus\"&gt;Tartarus&lt;/a&gt; and taken control of the &lt;a href=\"Underworld\"&gt;Underworld&lt;/a&gt; imprisoning Hades, &lt;a href=\"Persephone\"&gt;Persephone&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt; and the other members of the &lt;a href=\"House%20of%20Hades\"&gt;House of Hades&lt;/a&gt;. Now, he launches a war against the &lt;a href=\"Olympians\"&gt;Olympian Gods&lt;/a&gt;, besieging &lt;a href=\"Mount%20Olympus\"&gt;Mount Olympus&lt;/a&gt; itself with the intent of restoring his old rule upon the world. \nCharacteristics and Personality.\nChronos is a Titan of the golden age, the great evil of the game. A tyrannical and composed king, a bad father to Hades and his brothers, and a force that cannot be contained. Chronos looks down upon his granddaughter's attempts with underestimation, serving as the ultimate obstacle. \nChronos behaves with an elegant and superficial affability; he is arrogant, cold, and calculating, showing apathy towards Melino\u00eb's attempts to challenge his dominion to free the Underworld, and, ultimately, his son Hades and his enslaved family, compelling him to witness his loved ones frozen in time as his dominion is conquered. \nThough initially coming off as apathetic to anything that does not involve his domain, he is not completely devoid of curiosity about the &lt;a href=\"Surface\"&gt;outside world&lt;/a&gt; sometimes taking the time to go out and observe the state of the world that his children have left his former kingdom in. He is also often insulting and mocking towards Melino\u00eb throughout her journeys, and when they finally meet officially at the House of Hades, he often criticizes her and the other &lt;a href=\"The%20Unseen\"&gt;freedom fighters&lt;/a&gt; in the Crossroads as being an uncivilized bunch. During their fight, while he does not hesitate to wield his weapons against her, Chronos still maintains a diplomatic stance, preferring conversation over combat. \nHe is apparently an abusive and hated father, feared by all of his children for being cruel and terrible to them, although Hades readily admits that he was least a better father to them than &lt;a href=\"Hyperion\"&gt;Hyperion&lt;/a&gt; ever was to his own daughters. Chronos has a strong desire for control and is a supreme egotist, seeing himself as the victim of the story. He was hurt by his own children going against him and views them as adversaries. His approach is less that of a traditional dictator and more that of a disappointed father who always believes he knows what is best for everyone, disciplining and punishing his offspring as he sees fit from which they will only learn \"over time\". \nHe also has a comedic side, joking that his son let his beard grow before him; he can't help but let out a sinister laugh if the player backs down from a confrontation. \nHe is also very cunning, being a master of deception, he manages to locate and banish the Fates far away where they could no longer interfere in his plans. It is revealed that he deliberately deceived Chaos into telling him where they lived simply because he had wanted to test the magnitude of their power out of curiosity. \nAlthough one might assume he was as chaotic and destructive as the rest of the Titans, Aphrodite mentions that she found his reign to be \"overall boring\", ironically implying that his reign over the universe was in fact very similar to Hades' benevolent yet tyrannical approach to ruling over the Underworld and the dead, and he seems to have garnered a legion of loyal subjects as they all rallied to him when they summoned him, showing that he was at least a good king to them.\nPhysical description.\nAs a Titan, Chronos towers over mortals, being roughly twice Melino\u00eb's height, although his frame is far leaner than his sons' bulky frame. He has dark grey skin with a number of golden scars, combed back white hair, and glowing white eyes. When fighting, he has a set of large dark wings.\nHis attire has a curiously Egyptian aesthetic, consisting of a white tunic with a golden hourglass, a collection of bangles along his arms, and a golden necklace decorated with the Roman numerals I-XII.\nHistory.\nPast.\nChronos ruled the earth in ancient times but was overthrown by his three children &lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt;, and their three allies &lt;a href=\"Hestia\"&gt;Hestia&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Demeter\"&gt;Demeter&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Hera\"&gt;Hera&lt;/a&gt;, the founding Olympians. They cut him into innumerable pieces with his own scythe and scattered them throughout the darkest depths of &lt;a href=\"Tartarus\"&gt;Tartarus&lt;/a&gt;.\nBefore Hades II.\nChronos appeared suddenly in the &lt;a href=\"House%20of%20Hades\"&gt;House of Hades&lt;/a&gt;, using his control over time to imprison the majority of its inhabitants in a moment that would never pass. After ensuring his daughter &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb's&lt;/a&gt; safety, Hades confronted his father, who explained that he sought vengeance against the gods for stealing his throne and killing him. He ordered Hades to tell him the location of the &lt;a href=\"Fates\"&gt;Three Fates&lt;/a&gt;, but Hades didn't know it. Rather than freezing his son in time, Chronos imprisoned him in &lt;a href=\"Sisyphus\"&gt;Sisyphus&lt;/a&gt;' chamber of Tartarus so that he could send his minions to torment Hades for his amusement. He then visited &lt;a href=\"Chaos\"&gt;Chaos&lt;/a&gt;, who, unaware of his scheme, used their omniscience to find the location of the Fates. Chronos used this knowledge to capture the Fates, imprisoning them somewhere in the Underworld.\nHades II.\nWith the leadership of the Underworld destabilized, Chronos put his plan into action. He deliberately disrupted the workings of the Underworld, creating a situation where the lost souls of dead mortals would stagnate in &lt;a href=\"Erebus\"&gt;Erebus&lt;/a&gt; and their bodies would remain animated on the mortal plane. With his army of faithful cultists, he organized these dead into an army that would march on &lt;a href=\"Mount%20Olympus\"&gt;Mount Olympus&lt;/a&gt; to dethrone the gods. They were able to successfully hold back the undead forces for years, but the attacks only grew in intensity, as the dead could not permanently die without being processed through Erebus.\nUnbeknownst to the Titan, forces loyal to Hades had gathered under the banner of &lt;a href=\"Hecate\"&gt;Hecate&lt;/a&gt; and plotted to kill him once more. One such soldier was Melino\u00eb, daughter of Hades, who was able to repeatedly infiltrate the House of Hades and kill Chronos. However, she could not inflict damage to his body nearly as thoroughly as the Olympians had, and he regenerated much more quickly to continue his assault on the gods."}
{"id": "2800", "revid": "48934972", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2800", "title": "Chronos/Combat", "text": "Chronos has two phases, each with their own set of attacks. During the first phase, his attacks are as follows:\nFirst Phase.\nAfter his health reaches 75%, he will perform the following attacks:\nWhen his health reaches 50%, he will begin to combo multiple dashes and slashes into each other, forcing Melino\u00eb to evade a more complex pattern of attacks before getting an opening to retaliate. Chronos will never chain more than 3 of these moves.\nAfter his health reaches 0%, the second phase begins.\nSecond Phase.\nIn this phase, Chronos will regain all of his health and transport Melino\u00eb and himself to a new area shaped like a clock face. He reuses some of his attacks from the earlier phase but also includes new attacks, as follows:\nChronos will stop chaining scythe attacks into each other when transitioning into this phase, but be warned that he will resume this behaviour once he hits 50% health again.\nPassive Abilities.\nCritically, this immunity only affects Chronos himself; none of his reinforcements benefit from this ability. Additionally, his trails will also be slowed like normal, meaning that they can be desynced from their usual timing (this is especially obvious when using the \"Phase Shift\" Hex).\nAmusingly, this immunity also extends to the players ability to pause the game, causing Chronos to taunt the player before unpausing the game again. At the Crossroads, the player can concoct the \"Power to Pause and Reflect\" incantation for 3 &lt;a href=\"Zodiac%20Sand\"&gt;Zodiac Sand&lt;/a&gt; and 3 &lt;a href=\"Moly\"&gt;Moly&lt;/a&gt;, which will restore the ability to pause during the fight.\nChronos' time immunity does not apply to the exaggerated hitstop triggered by blast effects from &lt;a href=\"Hephaestus\"&gt;Hephaestus&lt;/a&gt;' Boons.\nReward.\nDefeating Chronos will grant 1 (repeatable)."}
{"id": "2407", "revid": "46051891", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2407", "title": "Chronos/Quotes", "text": "Erebus Conversations.\nFirst Meeting.\n Chronos : \"Pray, who might you be my girl? And what compelled you to wander in and out of &lt;a href=\"Erebus\"&gt;Erebus&lt;/a&gt;?\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"I'm not your girl, old man. My name and business are not your concern.\"\n Chronos : \"So it seems. You appear to be quite pressed for time. Forgive this \"old man\" his transgressions...\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"...Couldn't have been...\"\nSecond Meeting.\n Chronos : \"You have returned. Or lost your way, perhaps in those interminable passageways beyond.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"I know where I'm going. Whom do I address? And what are you doing here yourself, in such a place?\"\n Chronos : \"\"My name and business are not your concern\", is that not what you said? \"Ahh\", the impertinence of the youth of this age...\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"Wait...\"\nThird Meeting.\n Chronos : \"You, my girl, are meddling in matters you do not understand. Your father made certain choices; he was bound by them, but you are not. You need not follow in his ruinous path.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"\"Ruinous?! You\" brought ruin to the Underworld and the surface! I'll never accept what you've done. Now, enough talk!\"\n Chronos : \"How \"very\" spirited! You truly think you can stop Time. Well, then... I would like to see you try.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"Then watch this!\"\nFourth Meeting.\n Chronos : \"Which rock did you crawl out from under, \"hm?\" My forces, they are terribly confused! They have no idea where you live! So I thought I would \"attempt\" asking you nicely here.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"I live in your nightmares, Titan. I thrive on them! I'll see you dead, and then destroyed. However long it takes.\"\n Chronos : \"\"However long it takes?\" You speak of inevitability, little one. A subject on which I happen to be the expert. As to whomever sent you after me... I shall find them.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"We'll see!\"\nFifth Meeting.\n Chronos : \"You yet persist, despite my generous attempts to dissuade you. Then, very well! You carry on as the distraction which you are, whilst I turn my attention to matters of greater import...\"\n(Post Surface Run) First Meeting.\n Chronos : \"I was beginning to think I had successfully dissuaded you, when it came to my attention you were trespassing some other place instead. You dared venture above?\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"I've seen your work up there firsthand. To have unsealed the very gates of hell! And brought disaster to mortals who've nothing to do with your petty vendetta.\"\n Chronos : \"You speak of the bedraggled city of Ephyra, which once stood in sycophantic tribute to your upstart father. Perhaps what mortals yet remain there shall think twice next time before they put their faith in \"gods.\"\"\n(Post Surface Run) Second Meeting.\n Chronos : \"You cannot help the gods above, you know. My legions are vast, and death means little to them anymore. Not that your efforts here shall be of much consequence, either.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"Your surface legions fight and die for you, yet you hide behind them here. If you're so certain of your victory, you'd be leading them.\"\n Chronos : \"Leadership, my girl, is not about having to do everything oneself. It is about ensuring others share your same ideals and methodology. Wherever you may go, you shall encounter many who embrace my point of view, I think.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"No shortage of fools...\"\n(Post Surface Run) Third Meeting.\n Chronos : \"No victories upon the surface as of yet? It appears you have \"two\" hopeless goals, rather than one.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"I've only one, and hope has nothing to do with it. I may not be able to stop you yet, but neither can you stop me. You've tried.\"\n Chronos : \"You \"have\" been more resistant than \"some\" members of your family, I admit. Well then, see where your scattered ventures to the surface, or these depths, shall ultimately lead!\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"We'll both see.\"\n(Post Surface Run) Fourth Meeting.\n Chronos : \"At last you have returned to more-familiar environs, girl. Neither the gods nor the Fates want you upon the surface of this world! Yet you insist on fighting there, for them.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"I suppose I'll be more welcome in my father's home later this eve? As you can see I'm willing to fight there as well.\"\n Chronos : \"\"Ah\", but you have such a long way to go! Confined to making the journey by foot, like a pathetic mortal. Do be sure to conserve some of your strength for the \"final stretch.\"\"\n(Post Battle) First Meeting.\n Chronos : \"I thought that I might find you here, my girl. Such fire in your eyes! How obstinate the members of our family can be. Have you learned nothing from our previous exchange?\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"Oh, I learned plenty, and I'm eager to learn more. So why don't you get out of my way, since there's nothing you can do within these woods but try to slow me down?\"\n Chronos : \"Past the point of reason, and so very self-assured. Then, very well! Come find me if you must, and learn some more. You know where I reside. I do not hide from {#Emph}gods!\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"See you soon...\"\n(Post Battle) Second Meeting.\n Chronos : \"Little one, do not presume to think your movements are invisible to me! I see you plainly where you stand. A trespass for which you shall suffer, although, regrettably, not by my hand right now. Not yet.\"\n(Post Battle) Third Meeting.\n Chronos : \"I am Time itself. What are you? A thrall of those calling themselves gods, mindlessly serving at their whim. My children are crafty... to them, you are nothing but a common tool! And not an especially sharp one, it appears to me.\"\n(Post Battle) Fourth Meeting.\n Chronos : \"If there is one thing on which the accursed Fates and I agree, it is that all eventually shall decay. All sprang from nothingness, and back into that Chaos we shall all return. You merely hurry it along.\"\n(Post Battle) Post Melino\u00eb's Winning Streak.\n Chronos : \"Why, here comes our shadowy assassin on her nightly escapade to try and do me harm! Although perhaps the outcome shall not be so fortunate, this time.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"We'll soon find out, won't we? I promise not to keep you waiting long. I'm well on my way already, as you can see.\"\n Chronos : \"Oh, that I \"can\". Then, I had best return and make ready! We have to tidy up for your arrival, after all. Until later tonight.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"...Until then.\"\nTalking about The Gods.\n&lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Chronos : \"My dear son Zeus is already abetting you this night? I fear not his famous thunderbolt, young fool that he is.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt;.\n Chronos : \"\"Ah\", so Poseidon gave to you his blessing, has he now? What are you going to do... pour water on me?\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hestia\"&gt;Hestia&lt;/a&gt;.\n Chronos : \"The goddess of the hearth has blessed you now? There is no flame which \"Time\" cannot extinguish soon enough.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Demeter\"&gt;Demeter&lt;/a&gt;.\n Chronos : \"The frosty goddess Demeter is urging you along this eve? Alas, there are no \"seasons\" in the Underworld.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hera\"&gt;Hera&lt;/a&gt;.\n Chronos : \"The self-made Queen of the Gods, bestowing you her Boon? Is there not some mortal wedding she ought to officiate?\"\n&lt;a href=\"Olympians\"&gt;Olympians&lt;/a&gt; as a Whole.\n Chronos : \"Try all you like, my girl; but the outcome of this night shall be no different from the last.\"\nAnomaly Dialogue (&lt;a href=\"Oceanus\"&gt;Oceanus&lt;/a&gt;).\nFirst Anomaly Greeting.\n Chronos : \"I know who you are. I know where you go. You shall not get there.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"This magick... Chronos! I'll carve you limb from limb for this. For everything!\"\n Chronos : \"How frightening. Unfortunately, we shall never know if yours was a mere-empty threat, for you are going on a little \"time out\". At least until some other matters are resolved...\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"No!\"\nAfter the First Anomaly Greeting.\n Chronos : \"I am afraid I must ask you to cease this at once...\"\nAsphodel?\n Chronos : \"You wish to traipse through this realm, then here! Bask in it.\"\nRevealing the Golden Ring.\n Chronos : \"What witchery is this...?\"\"\nLeaving Time Out.\n Chronos : \"You knew how to resist my little spell...\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt; Flashback in Tartarus.\n Chronos : \"Hello, Hades...\"\n Chronos : \"\"Ah\", there you are, my son. Grown a full beard and a broad frame, I see. And now you have a family of your own! How full of life they are, despite the dour environs.\"\n Hades : \"Greetings, Father. I... was not expecting your arrival. You... must forgive us that the House was unprepared for guests. To what do we owe the pleasure of your company?\"\n Chronos : \"Oh, you know, for one thing I was in the area! You might recall the time you, &lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt; and the rest of you little brats cut me to ribbons? Sprinkled all my bits, all throught Tartarus?\"\n Hades : \"Father... that was a war \"you\" started and you know it! We took no joy in what we had to do! But how can this be? I thought that you were gone...!\"\n Chronos : \"Do not sound so disappointed! It is \"I\" who should be disappointed here, not \"you\". You thought I was gone? I was! But it turns out spite is a powerful motivator. Blood sacrifices also helped.\"\n Hades : \"What do you intend to do? And... what have you done to the others? To my family?!\"\n Chronos : \"Your cries fall on deaf ears. Fear not, my son. I have not eaten them or anything. I have merely... set them aside. They stand imprisoned in a moment that shall never pass. My qualm is not with \"them\".\"\n Hades : \"...Olympus shall have your head. You can take \"mine\", for all I care, \"blast you\"! But don't you \"dare\" harm anybody in my House!\"\n Chronos : \"Tsk! You have grown so accustomed to issuing commands that you forget yourself. Though, I do have such a command for \"you\": Tell me, exactly, where the Fates reside.\"\n Hades : \"The \"Fates\"? How should \"I\" know? Not even &lt;a href=\"Nyx\"&gt;Nyx&lt;/a&gt; herself knows where her daughters are! Why are you... asking me...?\"\nPre-Fight Conversations.\nFirst Meeting.\nA Version.\n Chronos : \"Let yourself in, I see. Through the gutter? This family never had any class! Though I am working on alleviating that within this House, if you would pardon all the \"dust\". We have been \"renovating\" around here.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"Get up. You get up off that stolen throne! You know who I am, and you know why I'm here.\"\n Chronos : \"A family with no class, and no civility, either. Have I not made clear to you that your attempt to do me harm shall be in vain? I am a deathless \"Titan\". You merely are a poor, misguided \"girl\".\"\nB Version (First Run &amp; No Deaths ).\n Chronos : \"Pray, who might you be, my girl? It is not often that I entertain of late. Perhaps after this House becomes a little more presentable... though for the moment, you must pardon all the dust. We have been \"renovating\" around here.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"Get up. You get up off that stolen throne! You know who I am, and you know why I'm here.\"\n Chronos : \"\"Ahh\", what a surprise. My granddaughter! The one loose end I failed to tie up, now fully grown, almost. I have so many questions, if you please. How have you been? And how, exactly, did you find me here?\"\nC Version.\n Chronos : \"A guest, arrived so soon! It is not often that I entertain of late. Perhaps after this House becomes a little more presentable... though for the moment, you must pardon all the dust. We have been \"renovating\" around here.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"Get up. You get up off that stolen throne! You know who I am, and you know why I'm here.\"\n Chronos : \"Come, now, Granddaughter. There is no need to rush! You have come all this way. And I have so many questions. How have you been? And how, exactly, did you find me here?\"\nRest (All Versions).\n Melino\u00eb : \"Hear me, you enemy of Night and Darkness, now;&lt;br&gt;For your transgressions, you shall imminently die;&lt;br&gt;Under chthonic doctrine, this I vow!&lt;br&gt;For there is no escape from Fate beneath the sky.\"\n Chronos : \"\"Manners!\" Cursing is forbidden in this House. By that token, \"fighting\" is forbidden as well. But for you, my girl? We shall have to make an exception. \"Time\" for you to \"go\".\"\nAbout Characters.\nAbout &lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Chronos : \"You saw your father out there, I presume? He required a special arrangement. For aeons, he incarcerated countless souls within this place; not to mention \"me.\" Seemed only fitting he should have to waste away accordingly.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"You couch it in morality, when vengeance is reason enough. Though, since you've reasoned it all out, by what right did you take the other members of my family? And Nyx and all the rest?\"\n Chronos : \"Why, because they opposed me. Except you have this rather vexing knack for resisting some of my time-honored techniques... a recessive family trait, perhaps. Although, your brother... he was not so fortunate. You, too, shall break, however... soon enough.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Chronos : \"Hades used some of his failing strength to spur you on! Even whilst bound in chains no god can break, your father yet proves to be a pest.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"You've tortured and humiliated him. All this talk of how you plan to bring about a bygone age, yet petty vengeance seems to be your chief concern.\"\n Chronos : \"The thing is, my girl, I can have \"both.\" You should have seen the cruel, inventive ways your father tortured mortal souls! Thus I dispense a form of justice to \"him\", and to \"you.\"\"\nAbout &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt;.\n Chronos : \"You are \"quite\" dangerous, I must admit. You have repeatedly breached into Tartarus, and this House; impossibilities, if not for your tainted bloodline! And you are able to withstand my conjuring. Might I again politely ask you \"how?\"\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"You call that \"politely?\" You didn't even say the magick word. But since you really want to know... I'm from the future. You'll later come to realize the error of your ways, and teach me to stop you before you can cause more harm.\"\n Chronos : \"\"Ha ha ha!\" Oh, quite an imaginative tale. A comedy, for the utterly outrageous premise beggars belief! My girl, one cannot travel \"back\" in Time! Time marches ever forward; and I alone determine at which rate.\"\nAbout &lt;a href=\"Cerberus\"&gt;Cerberus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Chronos : \"You are proving to be quite a nuisance, if only because you insist on continually setting loose your father's wretched old three-headed cur! To think how such a beast used to be kept within these walls.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"So you keep casting out poor Cerberus into the Mourning Fields, where he rages alone. Of all your unforgivable offenses...\"\n Chronos : \"What would you have me do? I do not require him to guard the gates to this realm, for they are open wide. And I certainly do not require him to shed everywhere. Though \"blood\"shed, I accept.\"\nAbout &lt;a href=\"Polyphemus\"&gt;Polyphemus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Chronos : \"My work is made much easier for all the enemies Olympus has accrued. From the Satyrs, to the Harpies, to the Cyclops Polyphemus and much more! It is not I alone who seeks the downfall of the gods.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"So you gathered up the dregs lusting for power or revenge! Such company you keep. I know that Polyphemus well enough by now... his loyalty can almost certainly be bought.\"\n Chronos : \"\"Oh\", that it \"can. Loyalty\" is either earned or bought, and it makes very little difference either way. Polyphemus has his limitations, to be sure. But he is not a \"lost cause.\"\"\nAbout &lt;a href=\"Chaos\"&gt;Chaos&lt;/a&gt;.\n Melino\u00eb : \"You know, I'm almost impressed. Not only have you ransacked my father's domain and made war on Olympus, you had the audacity to deceive Primordial Chaos! That takes a spine.\"\n Chronos : \"Why thank you, my girl! I must admit, I thought that Chaos would be something of a bargainer, for I was willing to exchange their daughter Nyx for the Three Fates. But now, I have them all!\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"You played the chthonic gods for a pack of fools... these eldest, most powerful forces in existence. Such choices may come back to haunt you.\"\n Chronos : \"Yes, \"you\" have come back to haunt me here repeatedly. You, the best that the gods of the Underworld and Olympus have to offer. \"Bah!\"\"\nAbout &lt;a href=\"Fates\"&gt;The Fates&lt;/a&gt;.\n Melino\u00eb : \"So what have you done with the Three Fates? You would incur the wrath of all chthonic gods, as though the wrath of all Olympus weren't enough...\"\n Chronos : \"Oh, I banished them! Where, I cannot say, or {#Emph}when. {#Prev}In any event, they trouble us no longer, with their manipulative weavings. No, what happens now... is entirely up to {#Emph}us.\"\nAbout &lt;a href=\"Charon\"&gt;Charon&lt;/a&gt;.\n Chronos : \"I am quite flummoxed with that \"Boatman\" fellow just outside, who has the gall to scull his little boat right to my very doorstep! The Satyrs have more fear of him than you.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"You ought fear him yourself. Lord Charon knows every stone in the Underworld... every drop in the five rivers. You say you can't be stopped? Neither can he.\"\n Chronos : \"...That trinket-peddler, crudely hawking his ill-gotten wares to his very limited base of customers! And hoarding so much Gold I generously wrought. A noble ally that you have!\"\nAbout &lt;a href=\"Eris\"&gt;Eris&lt;/a&gt;.\n Melino\u00eb : I thought all the chthonic gods opposed you openly. But you persuaded \"Eris\", of all creatures, to your side! A laughable alliance, though not bad for sowing more destruction and dissent.\"\n Chronos : \"I am owed credit for a great many things, my girl; but not for any such alliances with Strife! What use have I for Nyx's youngest whelp? Although perhaps she is no fool, if she has rallied to my banners as you say.\"\nAbout Weapons.\nAs a Whole.\n Chronos : \"What \"are\" those \"garish\" instruments with which you try to do harm? Like as not some gadgets that the Fates themselves had vainly hoped would put an end to me.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"Whether they \"vainly\" hoped is yet to be determined. These may not be the arms the gods once used to bring you down, but they'll get the job done just the same. You watch.\"\n Chronos : \"Oh, we are eager to learn more, Hrodreptus and I. This scythe is not merely for cutting short the wheat whilst I put Cerberus away; it is for cutting short just about anything, you see.\"\nAspect of &lt;a href=\"Thanatos\"&gt;Thanatos&lt;/a&gt;.\n Chronos : \"I recognize that blade you bear: The scythe of Death himself! Alas that he was momentarily without it when I caught him in my snare, along with this House's other former residents.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"You may have taken Death, yet death is here for you. It would be fitting if you met your end by Zorephet.\"\n Chronos : \"It would be most unlikely, I should think. Then let us match now, scythe to scythe! Your Zorephet against my Hrodreptus. And we shall imminently see who reaps, and who sows.\"\nAbout the Scenery.\nAbout The Fallen &lt;a href=\"House%20of%20Hades/Hades%20II\"&gt;House of Hades&lt;/a&gt;.\n Chronos : \"You should have seen the hideous appearance of this place when I arrived! Or, I suppose you {#Emph}did{#Prev}, but were too little to recall. I daresay now it is a little more presentable. Yet you barge in, tracking blood and filth across the floor.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"My apologies to your custodial staff. Next time, I'll have to try to be a little more presentable when I arrive.\"\n Chronos : \"You seethe with bitter irony; but look at yourself! Come to confront me whilst more dead than alive. Well, the sooner I cast you out, the sooner my \"custodial staff\" can start to tidy up.\"\nAbout The Fallen &lt;a href=\"River%20Styx\"&gt;River Styx&lt;/a&gt;.\n Chronos : \"Did you enjoy your swim? The River Styx once flowed through here like blood. Foul traces of it yet remain in the Fields above, but now in my vicinity, it is all grains of gold.\"\n Melino\u00eb : You would transform the River Styx itself to suit your fancy? Or perhaps I heard you incorrectly. I may still have too many of your grains of gold stuck in my ears.\"\n Chronos : \"No wonder you have had such difficulty listening to me. Nevertheless, I trust the point I am about to make shall come through loud and clear.\"\nAbout The &lt;a href=\"Rift%20of%20Thessaly\"&gt;Rift of Thessaly&lt;/a&gt;.\n Chronos : \"You have been busy on the surface, have you not? Paid witness to indomitable fleets that sail toward inevitable victory, and the destruction of the mountain of the gods.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"The only fleet I saw up there was a ramshackle mess whose crew could barely stand, much less put up a fight. No wonder you have failed to take Olympus yet.\"\n Chronos : \"My fleets may not be to your standards, girl; but they have one important characteristic, which the gods all sorely lack: They are loyal to \"me\" to the end. Whichever end I \"deem!\"\"\nAbout the Enemies.\nAbout the Satyrs.\n Chronos : \"My legions know you well by now; the trouble you have caused. Yet only my most ardent followers may spill their blood within my halls.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"These Satyr worshipers of yours must be very honored to be the first to die here. Not the wisest creatures, though, are they?\"\n Chronos : \"The wise do not follow; the wise \"lead.\" These Satyrs lack a mortal fear of death, believing that their sacrifice shall bring me strength, and that they shall live on. Let us \"grant their desire.\"\"\nAbout Wretches.\n Melino\u00eb : \"Pardon my lateness, I had some wretches to contend with. I thought you let everyone go, regardless of past transgressions.\"\n Chronos : \"I let just about everyone go, yes. You may be surprised, however, to learn that some of those so-called \"wretches\" do not care for Hades very much. They were quite eager to serve me instead, when nicely asked. With you, I shall not even bother.\"\nMiscellaneous Conversations.\nAbout &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt;'s Loss.\n Chronos : \"You slipped through my fingers before, only to return and give to me another opportunity to add you to my collection? Did Athena truly get all the wisdom in our family?\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"Your \"collection...\" you speak of your kin as objects to be put on display. The gods ought have put \"you\" on display after cutting you to pieces, instead of discarding you like common filth.\"\n Chronos : \"You know, I am still rather sore about all that. I truly thought my children would be different; that they would show their elders some respect. But they did not. And my tolerance... has its limits.\"\nAbout &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt;'s Success.\n Chronos : \"Your eyes do not deceive; I am as hale and hearty as can be! That sinking sense you must have felt after our previous exchange? The fear of the utter senselessness of your entire enterprise? You now know it to be true.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"I was never going to destroy you in a single clash. You more than anybody ought to know results of any worth take time.\"\n Chronos : \"\"Ahh\", so then you wish to make a habit of such unceremonious appearances as this. As though they might amount to something, in the end. Fine. For my part, I occasionally need to stretch my limbs.\"\nAbout History.\n Chronos : \"The course of history is mine to shape. Yet you continue vexing me, as though you wish to do so in my stead. Fine, what shall it be? Shall I just go ahead and cede my rightful throne?\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"You don't set the course of history... you're Time. You're just the paving stones we cross along our way. More than getting back at the gods, you're getting back at the Fates, who know your rightful place in all of this.\"\n Chronos : \"I do, in fact, take issue with the Fates. Though they ought to be none of {#Emph}your {#Prev}concern, or anyone's. Imagine being free to make your own decisions now, only to long for the weight of their yoke upon your back! How {#Emph}pathetic.\"\nAbout the Golden Age.\nDialogue 01.\n Chronos : \"You are too young to know what it was like. Before the gods re-shaped the world to be like this. Mortals did not have to die in agony, and waste away within this \"pit\". A simpler age, and all the better for it.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"All the better, because you controlled every detail, is that it? You couldn't stand that others had a different outlook than your own. You went to war with your own children! After eating them whole, so they say.\"\n Chronos : \"They say a lot of things! \"They\" went to war with \"me.\" My offspring and my other charges did not always take to discipline; I had too many to look after to take cheek from any one. And \"you\", my girl, are not entitled to anything more.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Chronos : \"You have by now seen something of this world. Consider what the gods have wrought: war, famine, betrayal! During my Golden Age, there were no such concerns. It was a tranquil time... until the gods decided to wrest control forcibly!\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"Perhaps your rule was not as perfect as you claim. Perhaps you were a stifling presence on your children and their generation, leaving them with little choice but to rid themselves of you.\"\n Chronos : Well, they \"failed!\" And thus presents itself this golden opportunity to teach my \"children and their generation\" a most-valuable lesson about having to live with the consequences of their actions!\"\nAbout the Future.\n Chronos : \"The future is unwoven; uncertain. Not even the Fates themselves can anticipate how all of this shall end, or \"when.\" Yet you press on.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"I thought you were all about the inevitable. Whether the outcome of all this has been foretold or not, I'll see it through. Call it a morbid curiosity.\"\n Chronos : \"I call it reckless abandon, nothing more. You fail to consider the many possibilities in which you prove unable to enjoy the fruits of your labors...\"\nAbout Time.\n Chronos : \"A moment passes... then another, and another. I have names for them in every measure, you know? The very brief ones. The ones that linger...\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"If you're quite finished, I'll try to not to take up more than a few of the very brief ones you mentioned.\"\n Chronos : \"I understand the need to cut \"Time \" down to smaller bits, I do. Hours, cut down to minutes. Minutes, cut down to seconds. Because the whole of it, my girl... is \"too much to fathom.\"\"\nAbout &lt;a href=\"Titans\"&gt;Titans&lt;/a&gt;.\n Melino\u00eb : \"You're so indignant of my father's generation. What came of yours? I don't see many of your contemporaries rallied to your cause, or any other for that matter.\"\n Chronos : \"Well, you see, most of the other Titans met their end, just as did I! The doing of your father and his \"generation.\" Perhaps when all of this is settled, I shall see to bringing my \"contemporaries\" back. A few of them.\"\nAbout Origin.\n Melino\u00eb : \"Get up, wretch. Titan. \"Lord Master Chronos.\" Whatever they call you now. It's \"time\", as you might say.\"\n Chronos : \"It is, indeed. And they have called me many things; many names, in aeons past. There are those who think me nothing more than the offspring of Heaven and Earth, of all the \"nerve.\" And you are even less cordial than \"they.\"\"\nAbout Clockwork.\n Chronos : \"Have you once marveled at the ever-turning gears in Tartarus? My little contribution to the Underworld's design; a steady means of moving things along. I call it \"clockwork.\" A cycle without end! Akin to the turning of the seasons.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"I'm not here for a tour. That \"clockwork\" could have only come from \"you.\" An eyesore, going nowhere, groaning all along.\"\n Chronos : \"Going \"nowhere?\" One with capacity for magick ought espouse a deeper understanding of this world! We are always going \"somewhere;\" the \"future\", my girl! Into the \"future.\"\"\nAbout The Gameplay Timer.\nDialogue 01.\n Chronos : \"So you are keeping careful track of Time; such things of course are plain for me to see. But your reasons for it, I hardly can surmise. To gauge, perhaps, how quickly you shall fall?\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"Either me or you. So how much time shall we require here tonight? In all your wisdom, surely you must know.\"\n Chronos : \"Oh, this shall take but a \"trifle\", I expect! Not yet a formal measurement, although perhaps that too shall change...\"\nDialogue 02.\n Chronos : \"You ceased to track the measurement of just how quickly we may settle our disputes. Was it too much for you? To be so self-aware of your inexorable flight toward uncertainty?\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"I am an immortal goddess of the Underworld. Time means nothing to me. I can do this forever.\"\n Chronos : \"Is that so? \"Forever\" is a very long while. We shall have to make this slow and excruciating, to sate your gluttonous desire for more...\"\nAbout Pausing the Game.\n Chronos : \"You have considerable power over Time, that you can turn some of my innate power against \"me!\" Perhaps your knack for this is merely a recessive family trait.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"Don't insult me, and don't fool yourself. When you took my family, you created in me a lifelong desire to see you destroyed. So I simply prepared.\"\n Chronos : \"A lifelong desire. Your \"life\", girl, is but a blink of an eye to \"me!\" No one achieves abilities as yours through force of will alone. Though you are no mere \"god\"; you are a \"witch.\"\"\nDefeat.\nFirst Loss Against Melino\u00eb.\n Chronos : \"\"&lt;Gasp&gt;\" I thought... \"none\" could resist the ravages of Time... but, \"you\"? \"How\"...?\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"You'll get no answers from me, and no mercy, either. Now \"die\", already. And I'll collect the ichor from your veins. Or whatever flows through them.\"\n Chronos : \"\"Hah\", hah, hah! What is death to the deathless? A mere nuisance! This House is \"mine\". Once I am gone... you shall be cast away.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"I expect so. And you'll be re-made and back on the throne before I can return. But I \"shall\" return. And I'll slay you again, and again, and \"again\", if I must.\"\n Chronos : \"Even if, in so doing, it meant that you would never see your dear old family again? Because the mercy I have shown to them thus far is something I may have to re-evaluate.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \"\"Our\" family. And what do I care? I don't even know them. But I \"do\" know you ought be dead here in another moment; any last words?\"\n Chronos : \"...For you, my girl...? No... none, for now...\""}
{"id": "2522", "revid": "31007", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2522", "title": "Chronos/Relationships", "text": "Chthonic Gods.\nThe Gods of the Underworld.\nHades.\n&lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;: Chronos's son.&lt;br&gt;Hades fought and overthrew Chronos and the other Titans, and imprisoned them in Tartarus. In various dialogues with Zagreus, Hades has described the Titans as exceedingly cruel and terrible parents, far worse than he ever was. The only good thing Hades has said about his father, was that he was less of a terrible father than the Titan Hyperion (Demeter's father), who was considered to be the worst of them all. By the time of &lt;a href=\"Hades%20II\"&gt;Hades II&lt;/a&gt;, Chronos has escaped the pits of Tartarus, and captured Hades.\nMelino\u00eb.\n&lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt;: Chronos' granddaughter.&lt;br&gt;Chronos' granddaughter, Melino\u00eb considers him an enemy and has swore to slay the Titan.\nDespite openly despising Melino\u00eb, he develops affection for her after she discovers a loophole to evade his control, and he endeavors to persuade her to support him.\nOlympian Gods.\nAfter the Titan War, the &lt;a href=\"Mount%20Olympus\"&gt;Olympians&lt;/a&gt; imprisoned the Titans in the depths of &lt;a href=\"Tartarus\"&gt;Tartarus&lt;/a&gt;.\nZeus.\n&lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt;: Chronos's son.&lt;br&gt;Zeus fought and overthrew Chronos and the other Titans. By the time of Hades II, Chronos has launched a war against Olympus.\nPoseidon.\n&lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt;: Chronos's son.&lt;br&gt;Poseidon fought and overthrew Chronos and the other Titans. By the time of Hades II, Chronos has launched a war against Olympus."}
