{"id": "4395", "revid": "4008728", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4395", "title": "Demeter/Boons (Hades II)", "text": "Demeter boons revolve around in applying her &lt;a href=\"Hades_II%23Status_Curses\"&gt;Status Curse&lt;/a&gt; Freeze which causes afflicted enemies to stop for 2 seconds. Additionally, Demeter can also apply a second Status Curse called Cyclone that makes enemies 20% slower and their ranged shots 60% slower. Demeter's elemental affinity is &lt;a href=\"Earth\"&gt;Earth&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Water\"&gt;Water&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Aether\"&gt;Aether&lt;/a&gt; for her Duo Boons."}
{"id": "1674", "revid": "29110118", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=1674", "title": "Demeter/Quotes (Hades)", "text": "\"The following are quotes from &lt;a href=\"Demeter\"&gt;Demeter&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Hades%20%28game%29\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;.\"\nFirst Meeting.\n Zagreus: \n\"Brr. That is cold...\"\n\"Last time I felt a chill like this was...on the surface, but, who...? Well, one way to find out, then, in the name of Hades! Olympus! I accept this message!\"\n Demeter : \n\"I understand, young Zagreus, that you would seek to leave that bitter darkness for this bitter cold? Quite honestly I fail to see why. But I'll aid your plight, why not? For I can offer plenty of assistance, and you soon shall grow fond of it, I think.\"\n Zagreus: \n\"I've the power of the freezing surface, now.\"\nKeepsake Dialogue (&lt;a href=\"Keepsakes\"&gt;Frostbitten Horn&lt;/a&gt;).\n Demeter : \n\"The Frostbitten Horn which you bear once overflowed. It holds a certain power still, of course. But never again shall mortalkind take it for granted.\"\nReactions.\nBoon Bought From Charon.\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"Be thankful that the rivers to your realm have not yet frozen over, Zagreus.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"I trust your ferry-boatman Charon has no qualms about the freezing temperatures up here?\"\nDialogue 03.\n Demeter : \n\"My message comes to you by river-boat this time, young Zagreus. At least that Charon is amenable to our attempts to contact you.\"\nLow Health.\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"Why, you've the look of one who has endured a terribly long winter, Zagreus! I trust you'll cling to life a little longer, now.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"I sense your grip on life is coming loose, young Zagreus. Now turn that cold you feel against your enemies.\"\nDialogue 03.\n Demeter : \n\"You seem to be in dire need of some assistance, Zagreus. I think perhaps I have a bit to spare.\"\nDialogue 04.\n Demeter : \n\"You're in the winter of your current stretch of life, aren't you, Zagreus? Do try and live a little longer for me, hm?\"\nDialogue 05.\n Demeter : \n\"You waste away just like a common mortal, Zagreus. How rather unbecoming of a god.\"\nDialogue 06.\n Demeter : \n\"The flame of life is easily extinguished by the cold, young Zagreus. Surely you feel the warmth within you giving way?\"\nDialogue 07.\n Demeter : \n\"Cold comfort for your terrible predicament, young Zagreus, but I am here.\"\nWeapons.\nWielding Exagryph.\n Demeter : \n\"Why isn't that there Sister Hestia's oddly constructed armament you bear? She always was so predisposed to flame; I thought she'd never give it up! If it's to be in any hands, then may as well be yours.\"\nWielding Coronacht.\n Demeter : \n\"That's Sister Hera's Heart-Seeker you have! The very weapon which she used to put our predecessors down. It hasn't lost its potency I see. Fear not, I shall not mention this to her, if I see her.\"\nWith Other Characters.\n&lt;a href=\"Ares\"&gt;Ares&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\n Ares: \n\"The cold of death is quite becoming of the Goddess Demeter, do you not think so, my death-dealing kin? She is becoming well accustomed to it, too.\"\n Demeter : \n\"I think that you forget yourself, Lord Ares, sir. For I am much your elder; my famines had already slain the mortals by the tens of thousands by the time such thoughts of doing so first crossed your mind.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Athena\"&gt;Athena&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Athena: \n\"I bring to you the Lady Demeter, Cousin. I've asked that she please rest assured knowing that have your matter well under control. Though, in her infinite compassion, she has taken up your cause, nevertheless!\"\n Demeter : \n\"Oh, you needn't lavish me with your faint praise, Athena dear. In all your boundless intellect, I'd have expected you would know I see through your intentions, plain as day.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"To think, young sprout, our strategist Athena, warrior-goddess, sprang from Zeus's head!! I would expect that no high intellect could come from there.\"\n Athena: \n\"Please do not mind the Lady Demeter's good-natured sense of humor, Zagreus. She and my father often like to jest with one another, even in the most difficult times.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Dionysus\"&gt;Dionysus&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Dionysus: \n\"Hey Zag, got a favor here I mean to ask, could you maybe persuade the Lady Demeter to ease up on the whole 'not let anything grow' thing she's been going on about?\"\n Demeter : \n\"I dare say, my lord Dionysus, that partaking of less wine for some amount of time might do you good. Regardless, you'll not coax a better crop from me.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"The crops shall wither and decay so long as I may please, young Zagreus. Although we do have those upon Olympus who take issue with my reasoning...\"\n Dionysus: \n\"Um, yeah, milady, I take issue here! I mean how are the grapes supposed to grow and wine supposed to flow when you are so uptight, now, just ease up a little there, let's see what we can do!\"\n&lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Poseidon : \n\"My foster-sister Goddess Demeter, despite her stern approach, she often likes to make good sport of me, Nephew! Why, here she is right now!\"\n Demeter : \n\"If you're quite finished blathering, Poseidon, our young Zagreus has more important things to do. He needs your blessings, not your point of view. Don't you, young sprout?\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"Ah, little sprout. I was just notifying Lord Poseidon here that all of his domain exists because it pleases me; remember, my good foster-brother, I could freeze your oceans solid if I chose.\"\n Poseidon : \n\"Ah, hahahah! Excellently stated, venerable Goddess Demeter! I'm reminded once more of your vast experience, though, I think we all prefer our oceans liquidy, isn't that right, Nephew?!\"\n&lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Zeus : \n\"Now, now, young man, whatever you heard about good Demeter, I'm here to clear the air. She's like a sister to me, yes, but only thus. Although her Titan parents and my one met the same fate.\"\n Demeter : \n\"Why, Foster-Brother Zeus! Such an unlikely bit of candor there, from you! Almost as though you felt compelled to speak the truth only whilst I'm directly within earshot.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"Well now, young sprout, you met the so-called King of the Olympians and I. Whom do you now suppose is genuinely the ruler of this snow encrusted mountaintop of ours?\"\n Zeus : \n\"Oh, hahaha, Lady Demeter, your wit is just as dry as the earth flying quite fallow in your care, perhaps you should go tend to that again though unless we go ahead and help our young man first.\"\nGifts.\n&lt;a href=\"Nectar\"&gt;Nectar&lt;/a&gt;.\n1st Time.\n Zagreus: \n\"Good Lady Demeter, you've shown me warmth and generosity, and I am very grateful for it. Please, accept this as a small token of my appreciation.\"\n Demeter : \n\"An offering well suited for the season, there, young Zagreus! In turn, as you are honorable and obedient, you'll have from me what the mortals have not.\"\n\"Demeter gives Zagreus the &lt;a href=\"Keepsakes\"&gt;Frostbitten Horn&lt;/a&gt;\"\n Zagreus: \n\"I'm in your debt, great Goddess Demeter.\"\n2nd Time.\n Zagreus: \n\"A little offering for you, good Lady Demeter. I'm deeply grateful for your willingness to aid me in all this.\"\n Demeter : \n\"I must acknowledge and accept your thoughtful gift of nectar, Zagreus; would that the mortals showed deference thus.\"\n3rd Time.\n Zagreus: \n\"May this small offering bring you some joy there on Olympus, Lady Demeter. Thank you for all your help.\"\n Demeter : \n\"A conscientious gift, my little sprout; and I am grateful for your generosity. A bit of nectar cuts straight through the cold, I say.\"\n4th Time.\n Zagreus: \n\"Your power and your wisdom has been of such help, good Lady Demeter. I'm honored, and this is the least I can do in exchange.\"\n Demeter : \n\"I was quite certain that the youth today was lacking any sort of tactfulness, young Zagreus. For once I'm thankful to be proven wrong.\"\nAbout Characters.\n&lt;a href=\"Aphrodite\"&gt;Aphrodite&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"All of the love and beauty in the world can wither in a season, Zagreus. Remember that when next the goddess Aphrodite makes her promises.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Ares\"&gt;Ares&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"Lord Ares already got hold of you, has he? He's good at making mortals kill each other, yes. But he has utterly no knack for subtlety.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Artemis\"&gt;Artemis&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"The gentle Artemis already found you, Zagreus? She takes my orders well; one cannot blame her, for she'd have nothing to hunt if not for me.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Athena\"&gt;Athena&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"Athena has imparted you her wisdom, Zagreus? A simulacrum of the real thing, at any rate. True wisdom only comes with age, I think.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Dionysus\"&gt;Dionysus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"You stumbled into Dionysus, Zagreus? One of these days I shall prevent his vineyards all from ripening; put to the test his carefree attitude.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Minor%20Characters\"&gt;Helios&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"I have a brother, Helios, the Sun. A nonsense-talker with a flaming chariot. Why, he once told me that my Kore,that she went into that Underworld of yours! Preposterous. The clouds now blot him out entirely.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Minor%20Characters\"&gt;Hyperion&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"We all are willful children, are we not? I'm daughter to Hyperion, you know; a Titan so obscure and hated that Lord Zeus, he started calling me his birth-sister, so much did he dislike this bit of truth! And to get a rise out of me, too.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"You bear the blessing of Poseidon, Zagreus? Someday I shall remind him of his place, and freeze his watery domain entirely.\"\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"I see the noble King of the Olympians has reached you prior to me, Zagreus. I wonder which of all his many lies he's told you last.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"I ought to warn you that my foster-brother Zeus, he has just a disgusting sense of humor, little sprout. He'd have you think he sired half the countryside! I have to shudder at the very thought.\"\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"You are entirely too young to have had meaningful experience with loss, young Zagreus. Pray to me that you never have to learn.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"My foster-brother's wayward son appears! I, too, once lost a child, Zagreus. I was quite foolish with her from the start. Her father was a baseborn farm-boy; worshipped me! He's gone as well, of course. Only the cold remains.\"\nBeing Invited to the &lt;a href=\"House%20of%20Hades\"&gt;House of Hades&lt;/a&gt; (Pre-Epilogue).\n Zagreus: \n\"Hope Mother knows what she's doing, in the name of Hades! Olympus, this is an official message! Lady Demeter, this is for you.\"\n Demeter : \n\"What's all of this, young Zagreus, a message of some sort, for me, indeed? I... can't decipher it, although... it bears the marks of my two foster-brothers here, and... well! It seems we'd better compare notes!\"\nPost-Epilogue.\n Demeter : \n\"Why, little sprout, young Zagreus... my grandson! I can scarce believe it, still! To think that, Kore, or... Persephone, my daughter... she had been with Foster-Brother Hades, all this time! A match I wouldn't have expected...or approved. That's why she left! Our blasted hearts do what they want.\""}
{"id": "4396", "revid": "55184635", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4396", "title": "Demeter/Quotes (Hades II)", "text": "The following are quotes from &lt;a href=\"Demeter\"&gt;Demeter&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Hades%20II\"&gt;Hades II&lt;/a&gt;\".\nFirst Meeting.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Headmistress told me so much about you, and now at last we meet. \"In the name of Hades! Olympus, I accept this message!\"\n Demeter : \n\"...You look just like your mother. I'll not lose her again. I shall freeze hell in its entirety if that is what it takes to get her back. You'll help me, won't you, Granddaughter?\"\nKeepsake Dialogue (&lt;a href=\"Barley%20Sheaf\"&gt;Barley Sheaf&lt;/a&gt;).\n Demeter : \n\"We are connected not unlike that Sheaf of Barley which you have. Each stem is broken easily, and yet the bunch is strong! Each different, and yet all very much alike.\"\nReactions.\nSeeing &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; at Low Health.\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"\"Ah\", you're hurt! Your partly-mortal blood's to blame. And so am I, for having fallen into love with a mere farm-boy once...\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"What happened, Granddaughter? May those wretches that hurt you thus suffer a thousandfold for what they have done.\"\nDialogue 03.\n Demeter : \n\"Injured already...! Know that the pains we suffer are the means by which we grow. And our enemies are about to grow a \"great deal.\"\nDialogue 04.\n Demeter : \n\"You spill your blood each night for our mistakes. I cannot cure your ailments from here, but I \"can \"make your enemies shatter to \"pieces\", if that is of any comfort.\"\nAbout Characters.\n&lt;a href=\"Chronos\"&gt;Chronos&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"I \"detested \"Chronos even in my youth. Almost as much as my own Titan father. We took our vengeance, though; on Chronos, Hyperion, and the rest. But I was a fool to think we'd never see any of them again...\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"We've been locked in conflict with Chronos for so long that we've begun to doubt that anything can meaningfully change. I wonder, flower... can you truly rid us of this blight?\"\nDialogue 03.\n Demeter : \n\"I take it Chronos still goes everywhere with that old gaudy-looking golden scythe of his? He fancies himself a reaper, speaks of harvest and decay; but he merely speaks in riddles, whilst \"I \"work directly in the trade.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"Melino\u00eb... I was certain you were gone. Scarce born, only to be taken by Chronos, along with my daughter and those nearest her. But the Witch of the Crossroads got you out of there, did she? How could she not send word...?\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"When bright Apollo gathered us and announced that his twin sister, whilst out hunting for our enemies, stumbled upon a long-lost relative with the Witch of the Crossroads, why... I was overjoyed and furious at once...\"\nDialogue 03.\n Demeter : \n\"You could have informed us; informed \"me\", whilst you grew supple and strong in the Witch's care. Yet knowing Hecate... she must have deemed the risk too great. I understand. I'll try to understand...\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"Your father was sullen and difficult even whilst young, quite honestly. What my daughter saw in him, I could not. Yet my Kore as I called her... she would brighten around him...\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"Word reaches us that you located Hades, flower! How he must seethe, incarcerated in that pit of despair, although at least he's whole. What of your mother, nothing still...?\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hecate\"&gt;Hecate&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"The first time your mother was lost to me... the Witch of the Crossroads emerged from the shadows to light my way, as I searched to the ends of the earth. We found not a thing; but at least I was not alone...\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"You know I always felt a kinship with Hecate, seldom though we saw each other. She never seemed to want for children of her own. But the Fates delivered you to her anyhow.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Circe\"&gt;Circe&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"The witch Circe, whom you know. She's distant daughter to my Titan-brother Helios the Sun, who dares not show his face. Her enthusiasm for soil and grain is almost cloying... though I appreciate the underlying sentiment.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Artemis\"&gt;Artemis&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"Perhaps I misjudged your woodsy cousin Artemis. To think that she found you! I was certain she was merely gallivanting with her Nymph-friends rather than being of use.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"I miss your mother terribly, and your brother as well. He was my little sprout. Chronos must have ensnared him with the others in your father's House, the unforgivable wretch...\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hephaestus\"&gt;Hephaestus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"Why, you even got the elusive god of the forge to crawl out of his cave. To think that all it took was this terrible in-fighting with our forebear to bring our family closer together.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Persephone\"&gt;Persephone&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"You inherited your mother's flaxen hair, and seemingly her force of will. Greenery would burst to life for her... the dead would too, if but they could. Within the reaches of my heart not yet grown cold, I know she still is safe.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Minor%20Characters%23Unnamed\"&gt;Farm Boy&lt;/a&gt; (&lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt;'s Human Grandfather).\n Demeter : \n\"You have one grandfather in the cruel Titan, Chronos... and another who was nothing but a mortal farm-boy worshiper of mine. Whether I loved or pitied him, I cannot say. At least your mother was born deathless...\"\n&lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"The great and crafty Zeus is aiding you directly, now? Then you truly must be one of our best remaining chances to thwart the Titan's plans... for Zeus is loath to ask for help, or offer it.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hera\"&gt;Hera&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"Well it seems you've earned the good graces of my sister Hera! And you didn't even have to commit yourself to a mate or bear any children, I suppose. She must be growing soft!\"\n&lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"\"Ahh\", you bear the blessing of Poseidon! Surely such a loud and blustering god must have more than sufficient might to back it up?\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"So Poseidon has again availed himself to you! Well, good, and may he prove of use. I'll hold my threat to freeze his oceans then, for now.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Apollo\"&gt;Apollo&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"Your fair cousin Apollo wields the light that mortals so cherish, for it brings them warmth, melting away my snow. With my permission, of course! His power shall only help you so much.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hestia\"&gt;Hestia&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"So Hestia gave you her gift of flame? Normally the old miser wants nothing to do with any of us, not even her sisters. But extraordinary times do call for extraordinary measures.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Aphrodite\"&gt;Aphrodite&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"Normally, sweet Aphrodite's power over beauty provides no shortage of entertainment I'm sure, though I fail to see how her blessing can be of much benefit in such a predicament as ours.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hermes\"&gt;Hermes&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"You're making haste, flower! I'd swear that you were graced by swift Hermes himself, except he must be too busy keeping watch over our enemies to be of much benefit to you.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Selene\"&gt;Selene&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"There's a touch of moonlight about you, flower, as though Selene lights your way. Would that the Moon concerned herself with more than her path across the sky...\"\nWith Other Characters.\n&lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"When my sisters and my foster-brothers and I overthrew Chronos long ago, we were much closer to \"your \"age, flower. Now we are older, and one should think wiser... although our frequent bickering and inaction suggest otherwise.\"\n Zeus : \n\"We are a strong-willed family, as you know perfectly well, Lady Demeter. We must move forward in unison! Building that sort of consensus is not always quick; though we each could do our part to hasten it along.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Zeus : \n\"Our upstart enemies shall scatter to the Four Winds once we're through with them! Our challenge is to purge them whilst minimizing unspeakable devastation. And Lady Demeter could always make the Earth re-grow.\"\n Demeter : \n\"Well, Lord Zeus... it is much harder to re-grow where not a trace of life remains. But that's of little consequence right now. Let all who oppose us \"wither! \"And we shall salt the Earth beneath their feet.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hera\"&gt;Hera&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"Of late, even my radiant young sister must sully her delicate hands in all the field work that must be done. She is even beginning to take to it... aren't you, Hera our Queen?\"\n Hera : \n\"\"Oh\", Demeter. These hands have seen more than you know! I simply do not flaunt the hardships I've endured. One \"can \"be as strong as a rock, without taking on its texture.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hera : \n\"Much as your father was custodian of all the dead, so are we responsible for the rest of the world! The hour has grown dark, yes, but... we have the power to \"restore. \"Thanks be to my good sister Demeter...\"\n Demeter : \n\"The time for restoration always comes as does the spring. But we're amidst a long winter, without an end in sight. We need concern ourselves with naught else, O Queen.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"Granddaughter, Poseidon here has been regaling me about the time his seas drank half the land! \"Ahh\", such a flood that was! Perhaps our strengths can be combined again...\"\n Poseidon : \n\"Oh, there's no \"perhaps \"about it, Demeter! We'll weather this storm yet! I'd just as soon whip up another great big flood for old \"Time\"'s sake, it's just... too many mortals these days!\"\nDialogue 02.\n Poseidon : \n\"\"Ah\", my niece, you ought to know that Elder Goddess Demeter and I, we may jeer and jest at one another, but it's never out of spite! Isn't that right, dear foster-sister?\"\n Demeter : \n\"Oh, Poseidon! You needn't lie to young Melino\u00eb like that. It sends a terrible impression, and may make her hold you in as much contempt as do I! But let's cooperate for now, why not?\"\n&lt;a href=\"Apollo\"&gt;Apollo&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"You know, flower, how mortals seek to be like us? Yet in so doing, they take on our ignoble qualities. Perhaps it's Lord Apollo's fault, as the standard to which they aspire!\"\n Apollo : \n\"Did I offend somehow, good Lady Demeter? I know the times have been quite cruel, though why don't we direct that cruelty at our enemies, instead of heaping it upon each other here?\"\nDialogue 02.\n Apollo : \n\"All of us here want you to succeed, Cousin, though none so much as Lady Demeter... I'm reminded that you are her grandchild, after all. \"Erm\", wait, she wants to speak to you herself!\"\n Demeter : \n\"Thank you for your advocacy services, Apollo. Should I have need of them again, I shall apprise you. For now, my granddaughter requires our abilities, not honeyed words.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Aphrodite\"&gt;Aphrodite&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"Aid from Olympus can take many different forms... as not all of us are suitably prepared or even \"built \"to face significant ordeals. Take, for instance, fairest Aphrodite over here...\"\n Aphrodite : \n\"Oh, Lady Demeter, you know that's \"patently \"untrue! I may be more a lover than a fighter, but that doesn't mean I won't mangle the faces of our foes, if that is what it takes to get them to \"back off! \"Now why don't we show your granddaughter how well we get along?\"\nDialogue 02.\n Aphrodite : \n\"You and your Granny Demeter, you must have \"so \"much catching up to do! Perhaps you even have the power to un-freeze that disapproving scowl I oft fear is \"permanently \"set, though... I can see she wishes to address you now herself!\"\n Demeter : \n\"Please pay no heed to Aphrodite, flower. She's more concerned about the contours of my face than doing anything of use. But on the count that we've much catching up to do, she's right...\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hephaestus\"&gt;Hephaestus&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"Even \"I \"could use a bit of heat on some occasions, flower, which the forge of Hephaestus here provides. Perhaps as compensation for the utter lack of \"warmth \"between most members of our family.\"\n Hephaestus : \n\"\"Ah\", just \"listen \"to the Lady Demeter! Everybody on our mountaintop thinks they're \"so sharp\", but \"this \"one? She is blunt like my hammer. And some jobs call for a blunt instrument, don't they?\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hephaestus : \n\"Your grandnan and I, we don't usually get talking very much. But now we got something in common, witchie: \"you! \"I say you've got things well under control, but I... can't fool the likes of Lady Demeter!\"\n Demeter : \n\"Not one of us has \"got things well under control\", Granddaughter. So pay what Hephaestus said no heed! Instead use our strength combined... and Fates willing, restore for us some sense of normalcy.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hestia\"&gt;Hestia&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"Your Great Aunt Hestia is not exactly as she \"seems. \"In olden times, she was content merely to let her flames keep sputtering within the hearths of mortal homes. Admit to it, Sister: You've changed.\"\n Hestia : \n\"And you, Demeter, you've not changed at \"all! None \"of you have! It's why you're in a heap of \"trouble \"now, or \"we \"I ought to say. Good thing your grandkid's coming to our rescue!\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hestia : \n\"Would you believe it, hot stuff? I have on good authority that \"somebody \"around here's laid a claim to being \"Eldest of Olympus. \"Oh, Demeter? Care to explain \"that \"one?\"\n Demeter : \n\"Hestia, you had \"abandoned \"us! To be an Olympian is not merely a birthright, but a \"pledge; \"both to this family, and this mountain. Restore your rightful status, and join me now to aid my granddaughter!\"\nAbouth the Scenery.\n&lt;a href=\"Oceanus\"&gt;Oceanus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"What are you doing in those brackish depths, flower? Even Poseidon has turned his back on what lurks in that corner of the sea. Does such a path truly lead deeper into hell?\"\n&lt;a href=\"Fields%20of%20Mourning\"&gt;Fields of Mourning&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"Your journey sends you through the Mourning Fields. I've seen that place... just \"dreadful\", utterly! All of the wheat there, it... I thought perhaps it would provide a bit of cheer...\"\n&lt;a href=\"The%20Surface\"&gt;The Surface&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"My understanding was your line could scarce survive beyond the reaches of the Underworld. Yet there you are, traipsing about as though not bound by your father's fate. How can this be...?\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"You sprang forth from underneath that gloom unto our world's surface, have you, flower? If you mean to visit our mountain, merely follow the path of desolation leading straight to us...\"\nDialogue 03.\n Demeter : \n\"Fear not for this mountaintop, nor for the Earth; for she is far more resilient than us all. Our foes could scour \"every trace \"of our existence, yet Mother Gaia would remain, and recover.\"\n&lt;a href=\"City%20of%20Ephyra\"&gt;City of Ephyra&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"Nothing lives in the city of Ephyra. And I shall keep it that way until its infestation of shambling wretches is brought to heel! Though, you need not concern yourself with the details; we have someone already on the case.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"Are you on your way here to us, flower? A journey that your mother made many a spring... but at a different time, whilst not beset by thuggish followers of a despicable Titan.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Rift%20of%20Thessaly\"&gt;Rift of Thessaly&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"Your uncle Poseidon created that watery chasm you see before you. I've half a mind to freeze it shut, though I fear our enemies shall cross it anyhow, and your voyage would only be more fraught.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"That Rift of Thessaly could easily be turned to ice, you know. I'd like to see the enemy's fleet sail across it \"then! \"But I am told we have to cool it with the cataclysms for a while... mortals and their \"begging.\"\nMiscellaneous Conversations.\nOffering Boon at The Start of a Run (Any).\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"As you begin your next attempt at the seemingly impossible, know that I shall be with you to the bitter end. In blessing form, at least.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"Go forth on this next ordeal with my blessing, Granddaughter. I've a feeling it shall be a very cold night for our enemies...\"\nDialogue 03.\n Demeter : \n\"Should this night take you all the way to hell and back, I still would gladly come along. But, this is the best that I can do from here.\"\nDialogue 04.\n Demeter : \n\"The forecast for this evening calls for a sharp decline in temperature. Though you are well-accustomed to the cold by now, aren't you?\"\n&lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; Clearing A Run (Underworld).\n Demeter : \n\"Granddaughter, where have you been? In the deepest reaches of your father's realm, perhaps! Striking at the very heart of our enemy. One can but hope.\"\nBuying Boon at &lt;a href=\"Charon\"&gt;Charon&lt;/a&gt;'s Shop.\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"How shameful that we now resort to common subterfuge, having our correspondence smuggled to and fro by the erstwhile Boatman of the Dead.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"The Titan's coin that you exchanged for this message... we shall find all of it, melt it down, and return the Gold whence it came.\"\nDialogue 03.\n Demeter : \n\"If only you could see my fields in the morning sun... shining brighter than any gold you shall ever find. Such metals ought remain within the earth.\"\nDialogue 04.\n Demeter : \n\"To be reduced to picking through such meager offerings! You ought have lived here in the glory of Olympus, where everything that you desire is at hand... for the most part.\"\nAbout The &lt;a href=\"Chaos%20Trials\"&gt;Chaos Trials&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"Something about this night is troubling... as though some force of will yawned forth from the very depths of Chaos. But \"you \"wouldn't know anything of this, would you?\"\nAbout The &lt;a href=\"Oath%20of%20the%20Unseen\"&gt;Oath of the Unseen&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"Such a foreboding night this is! The air is thick with the death and decay of your father's realm, and the desolation I have wrought. The pale Moon can scarce cut through...\"\nAbout The &lt;a href=\"Pom%20of%20Power\"&gt;Pom of Power&lt;/a&gt;.\n Demeter : \n\"I wonder if the vile pomegranate fruit yet grows in your Underworld. It holds a power there that I do not abide; a mere taste of its blood-like seeds can be very dangerous, indeed.\"\nAbout The Moon.\n Demeter : \n\"Even in the dark of a new moon, when Selene herself dares not ride across the cold night sky, I found you there... and I shall give you all the power that I have to spare.\"\nAbout The Rain.\n Demeter : \n\"That rainfall there may be of benefit to you; washing all the filth away, revealing new growth. Think you that Zeus himself brings the rain, or Poseidon? Take one more guess...\"\nAbout Resources.\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"The bounties of the earth... life flourishes even there where you reside, amid all that death. Flowers, roots, herbs, and seeds; you know their hidden strength. I let them grow for you.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"You've picked an abundance of Moly flowers... unassuming little things, aren't they? Not unlike \"you\", for they too hold power far beyond that suggested by their form.\"\nAbout Legendary Boon.\nDialogue 01.\n Demeter : \n\"As the sapling struggles to grow, so too must we push ourselves to discover our truest potential. Behold my power over life and death; may you find yours.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"The seasons are a never-ending cycle of decay and renewal... though there are such times when the seasons assert themselves much more fiercely than usual; times such as \"now.\"\nGifts.\n&lt;a href=\"Nectar\"&gt;Nectar&lt;/a&gt;.\n1st Time.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"To think the goddess of seasons herself is my grandmother. I am honored to have made your acquaintance.\"\n Demeter : \n\"I see the Witch of the Crossroads taught you not just strength but grace! I hereby accept your offering, and have something for you as well.\"\n\"Demeter gives &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; the &lt;a href=\"Barley%20Sheaf\"&gt;Barley Sheaf&lt;/a&gt;.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"A gift from Grandmother...\"\n2nd Time.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Lady Demeter! I'm grateful for your strength. This is hardly fitting in exchange, but please accept it.\"\n Demeter : \n\"It seems there are such youth today as still can show my generation due respect. I am pleased my own granddaughter is such an example.\"\n3rd Time.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"To the goddess whose power truly is the lifeblood of our world! It's by your grace that such an offering of Nectar may exist at all.\"\n Demeter : \n\"Why, flower, surely there are other matters weighing heavily upon you now, more so than honoring your elders in the customary way? Nevertheless, I'm grateful for this, truly.\"\n4th Time.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Grandmother, we've so much making up to do for all the time we could have spent getting to know each other. I trust we'll do just that soon enough, though for right now, there's this.\"\n Demeter : \n\"It's strange... as much as I loved your mother, she never honored me thus. Perhaps I was too lenient with her, or perhaps your generation is merely more considerate of their predecessors.\""}
{"id": "2515", "revid": "30972", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2515", "title": "Demeter/Relationships", "text": "Family.\nPersephone.\n&lt;a href=\"Persephone\"&gt;Persephone&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's daughter.&lt;br&gt;Demeter loves her daughter, adoring her and calling her Kore (the name Demeter gives her) instead of Persephone, which she prefers to be called. She was extremely protective of her because Demeter believed her daughter was fragile due to being half mortal. When Persephone disappeared, it affected Demeter, turning the once gentle and generous goddess into a cold and vengeful one.\nShe blamed Mortalkind for her daughter's disappearance and unleashed her wrath upon them by casting an endless winter upon the world. It is repeatedly suggested that if Demeter were to uncover the truth about Persephone's abduction, it could lead to a war between the Olympian gods and the chthonic gods, or even among the Olympian gods themselves, due to Zeus's involvement. Once Persephone reveals herself to the Olympians (with a slightly altered retelling of the events to suggest that Persephone simply fled), Demeter is simply relieved to know that her daughter is alive, even if she does not approve of her husband's choice.\nFrom then on, Persephone and Demeter come to an agreement where Persephone must spend 6 months of the year on Olympus and the rest of the time with her husband and son. Humiliated by having lost her daughter before due to harsh treatment, Demeter seems to have significantly softened towards Persephone, and whenever Persephone is in the underworld, she regularly asks Zagreus to send her regards.\nIn the second game, after Chronos kidnaps Persephone, she vows not to lose her again, even if it means freezing the flames of hell to have her back.\nZagreus.\n&lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's grandson.&lt;br&gt;Initially, she presents herself as a cold and distant leader in Zagreus' presence and doesn't understand why he would exchange the underworld where she lives for the frozen surface, always cold and grumpy. But gradually she begins to accept him and reciprocate the kindness he offers her so he can escape. Upon discovering that Zagreus is actually her grandson, she becomes more drawn to him and starts to act more sensibly and lovingly in his presence. \nDemeter starts to soften simply out of relief, but soon she begins to look upon Zagreus more kindly. He gives her a reason to smile, gradually warming the heart that was once cold and hopeless.\nMelino\u00eb.\n&lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's granddaughter.&lt;br&gt;After the first game, Persephone gave birth to her second grandchild. Demeter acts much more warmly towards her granddaughter, lending her strength so she can achieve her goal of saving Persephone and Zagreus. However, due to the war against Chronos, she has no time to spare, and any closeness between them must wait. Demeter did not meet Melino\u00eb; she assumed she had met the same fate. During their eventual encounter, Demeter finds Melino\u00eb remarkably similar to Persephone and uses the same endearing nickname with Zagreus, \"little sprout.\" She is determined to retrieve Persephone again, even if it means freezing hell itself to do so, and believes her granddaughter will help her with that.\nHestia.\n&lt;a href=\"Hestia\"&gt;Hestia&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's older sister.&lt;br&gt;She mentions her sister in the dialogue about Exagryph. She says that there is no strangely armament more elaborate than that of Sister Hestia and that she has always been so predisposed to flames.\nHera.\n&lt;a href=\"Hera\"&gt;Hera&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's younger sister.&lt;br&gt;She mentions her sister in the dialogue about Coronacht, referring to it as the same weapon that Hera used to defeat their predecessors. She acknowledges that the weapon has not lost its power and assures Zagreus not to be afraid and promises not to mention it to Hera if she happens to encounter her.\nHelios.\n&lt;a href=\"Helios\"&gt;Helios&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's brother.&lt;br&gt;When Helios from his chariot across the sky informed her of what had happened to Persephone, she not only didn't believe him but also blocked out the sun.\nSelene.\n&lt;a href=\"Selene\"&gt;Selene&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's sister.\nEos.\n&lt;a href=\"Eos\"&gt;Eos&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's sister.\nHyperion.\nHyperion: Demeter's father.&lt;br&gt;Hyperion was said to be a terrible father, even more than the Titan &lt;a href=\"Chronos\"&gt;Chronos&lt;/a&gt;. Demeter hated Hyperion and personally slew him with the &lt;a href=\"Twin%20Fists\"&gt;Twin Fists of Malphon&lt;/a&gt; by pummeling him so much that his immortal body was thoroughly pulverized and even his legacy was erased.\nTheia.\nTheia: Demeter's mother.&lt;br&gt;She refers to Theia as \"whoever she is\" implying that she was not part of Demeter's life.\nOlympian Gods.\nThe Olympians are Demeter's adoptive family. She has a long-standing enmity with them, stemming from the abduction of her daughter, Persephone, which resulted in the infamous \"Endless Winter.\"\nZeus.\n&lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's foster brother.&lt;br&gt;Demeter regards Zeus as an adopted brother, but blames him for mortals mistaking their real relationship as true brother-sister. She despises his deceitful nature, cynically questioning which ideas he's implanting in young Zagreus's mind, highlighting his deceptive nature and disgusting humor, speaking for her part the deities are her relatives . He is the Olympian who seems least to fear her, and remains calm in her presence, but deep down, shamelessly showing her false condolences for Persephone's disappearance, without even a hint of remorse, even though he knows he's primarily responsible. \nDuring the epilogue, Zeus is superficially forgiven easily, as for now, she seemed to ease the situation at her daughter's request. But it's only superficial. Demeter still has many things to discuss with him, as she still left a part of Olympus frozen, showing that she hasn't forgotten the occasion.\nPoseidon.\n&lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's foster brother.&lt;br&gt;Demeter does not have a pious relationship with Poseidon. He tells Zagreus that despite his subtle approach, she enjoys mocking him. Demeter will continue to speak ill of him indirectly, telling Zagreus that she has more important things to do than listen to Poseidon. They do not share the same opinion about the weather, and Demeter probably has a long and complicated history of struggle with him.\nIn the Duo - Poseidon and Demeter, she says that his domain only exists because it pleases her; she could completely freeze it if she wanted to.\nAthena.\n&lt;a href=\"Athena\"&gt;Athena&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's foster niece.&lt;br&gt;She praises her foster niece Athena for her 'wisdom', and is amazed that she emerged from the head of Zeus!! Since she wouldn't expect any high intellect to emerge from there. Although Demeter thinks Athena has the best of intentions, Demeter notices her weak praise and considers her adopted niece to be a bit sycophantic and condescending and sees through her intentions like daylight. \nShe doesn't appreciate the way she omniscient knows everything, and thinks that true wisdom comes with age, and not that it is innate.\nAres.\n&lt;a href=\"Ares\"&gt;Ares&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's nephew.&lt;br&gt;Ares is the nephew of Demeter through her sister Hera, yet she does not accord him differential treatment in relation to her other adopted nieces and nephews. He mentions her as a companion of death, which has claimed many mortal lives, Demeter is displeased. She responds, reminding Ares that her famines had taken tens of thousands of mortal lives long before Ares gave it a second thought.\nHephaestus.\n&lt;a href=\"Hephaestus\"&gt;Hephaestus&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's nephew.&lt;br&gt;\nArtemis.\n&lt;a href=\"Artemis\"&gt;Artemis&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's foster niece.&lt;br&gt;Though they share similar views of Athena, Demeter and Artemis differ in their opinions about mortals. While Artemis complains about the challenging snowy weather hindering their hunts, Demeter warns that humans are resourceful and deceitful, suggesting they will adapt and find alternative means, showcasing their differing perspectives on mortals as well.\nApollo.\n&lt;a href=\"Apollo\"&gt;Apollo&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's foster nephew.&lt;br&gt;Their relationship is currently unknown.\nAphrodite.\n&lt;a href=\"Aphrodite\"&gt;Aphrodite&lt;/a&gt;: The Goddess of Love and Beauty.&lt;br&gt;Despite being the goddess of love, Demeter claims that Aphrodite can be particularly venomous towards all the Olympians. Aphrodite will say how Demeter is pitiful for neglecting her appearance or how she has become cold and rigid. Demeter hints at how young Aphrodite is, considering her superficial intentions and interests.\nHermes.\n&lt;a href=\"Hermes\"&gt;Hermes&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's foster nephew.&lt;br&gt;Hermes complains about how much he's been fearing the cold lately, as it has been interfering with his work. He sarcastically remarks, \"We have Demeter to thank for that,\" implying that it's her fault. Hermes doesn't like crossing paths with Demeter, as she doesn't value his services much. He hopes that spending time with Zagreus will lift her spirits and warm her heart.\nDionysus.\n&lt;a href=\"Dionysus\"&gt;Dionysus&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's foster nephew.&lt;br&gt;Dionysus finds Demeter very uptight and disagrees that the plants must die in winter, he considers this a great exaggeration. He thinks his aunt should relax and enjoy some good wine with him. She warns him that drinking less wine for a while might do him good.\nChthonic Gods.\nThe gods of the underworld, most of whom the Olympians seem to despise, including Demeter.\nHades.\n&lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;: Demeter's foster brother and son-in-law.&lt;br&gt;Demeter finds her brother dull and dislikes his dark presence. He is undoubtedly the last suitor she would ever want for her daughter. Hades is terrified of her and is keeping Persephone's existence a secret, partially out of fear of what she would do. Hades, in particular, calls her a \"witch\" who could do terrible things if she was angry. \nWhen Demeter found out the whole truth, she was incredibly willing to accept that her daughter was married to him and loved him. She does so primarily to avoid losing her daughter again, rather than approving of him as a worthy consort for her Kore.\nThe Titans.\nThe previous rulers of the world, defeated in the Titan War and imprisoned in the pits of &lt;a href=\"Tartarus\"&gt;Tartarus&lt;/a&gt;. \nChronos.\n&lt;a href=\"Chronos\"&gt;Chronos&lt;/a&gt;:"}
{"id": "2741", "revid": "47838920", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2741", "title": "Demigod", "text": "The Demigods are a race of beings that are half-god and half-human. They possess mortal souls and are vulnerable to old age and death though they have longer than average human lifespans; however, their divine blood endows them with supernatural abilities that allow them to achieve feats usually not possible by humans.\nMost notably the Olympian God &lt;a href=\"Dionysus\"&gt;Dionysus&lt;/a&gt; was a Demigod before being made a full Olympian as a reward for his feats. "}
