{"id": "4248", "revid": "46051891", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4248", "title": "Hades/Quotes (Hades II)", "text": "First Meeting.\n Hades : \"Pah!\" Another tormentor come to break me, or to try. And such a frail one, at that. Has the Titan Lord a lack for decent help?\n Melino\u00eb : You... are you... the master of this beast?\n Hades : \"The master of this beast? Ha, haha!\" Well, if I'm to be remembered, I could think of far worse ways than that. Though, this \"beast\" has yet to so much as snarl at you...\n Melino\u00eb : \"&lt;Gasp&gt;\" Lord Hades, you're my... Father, I'm... Melino\u00eb. I'm your daughter.\n Hades : ...My daughter. Melino\u00eb? Merciful Fates...! You cannot be here. He shall find you. He'll find you, and...\n Melino\u00eb : ...I'll slay him where he stands. Where is he?\n Hades : He's in my blasted House! Where you were meant to be, and I. Look at me, Daughter. I could not confront him on my own. What do you expect shall happen?\n Melino\u00eb : I expect he'll underestimate me. Father, let me free you from these bonds!\n Hades : \"No!\" No, that would bring greater ruin, nothing more. Now, get out of this place. Though let me lend to you what strength I still possess.\nResponse 01.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"...I'll slay him where he stands. He's in the area, is he not?\"\nResponse 02.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"...I'll slay him where he stands. And not for the first.\"\n Hades : \n\"\"Not for the first\", truly? Then you must know the meaninglessness of the act! Look at me, Daughter. I could do nothing against him on my own. Even though I, too, have fought him before. \"Slain \"him before!\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"I'm sorry, Father. But I shall not be deterred, even by you. Now let me free you from these bonds!\"\nBasic Narrative Dialogue.\nSecond Meeting.\n Hades : \n\"What are you doing here again? I told you, you \"cannot \"be here!\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"And I told \"you \"I'd be back for you. Though my priority is Chronos. You vanquished him before. Can you reveal to me any weaknesses? Anything at all?\"\n Hades : \n\"\"I \"vanquished him with the aid of \"five other gods! \"What hope have you, alone? He has no weakness, save his arrogance. And it appears you have that weakness, too.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Then it seems we are equally matched. Father, how long have you been this way? Is there aught I can do?\"\n Hades : \n\"You think I've any sense of time in such a place? And I've said already what you can do: \"Risk not your everything. \"Go now, and be unseen.\"\nThird Meeting.\n Hades : \n\"I know not how you withstood the Titan, if truly you confronted him. Quickly now, tell me but this: Have you been... are you well?\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Am I... well? All my life I've been preparing for this moment, to bring the usurper of the House of Hades to justice. So, I'll have to get back to you, depending on how it goes.\"\n Hades : \n\"...I'm sorry... I'm sorry. Get back to me if you must. I'd grant your vengeance if I could. But this is all that I can do for now.\"\nSend-offs.\nTBA\nAbouth the Scenery.\n&lt;a href=\"House%20of%20Hades/Hades%20II\"&gt;Fallen House of Hades&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hades : \n\"If you'd indulge a senseless curiosity... how fares my House? Your brother, he was more or less in charge of the decor. I highly doubt the Titan shares his taste.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Well, unless Zagreus was enamored of gold trim and the Titan's sneering likeness everywhere, then it's probably quite different from what you recall...\"\n Hades : \n\"\"Urgh... \"you have your mother's candor to a fault. You ought have told me everything was \"fine! \"The comfort of lies at times is all we have.\"\n&lt;a href=\"The%20Surface\"&gt;The Surface&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hades : \n\"I cannot believe that I am asking but, how fares Olympus in all this? Even trapped within this chamber, it is evident to me that the Titan's legions are at war.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"The surface swarms with the dead, and the armies of Chronos are besieging the mountain. Our family is holding them back. I've been trying to break the stalemate in their favor, but all in all, it's not a pretty sight up there right now.\"\n Hades : \n\"\"Not a pretty sight up there... \"you mean to say you've seen all this firsthand? \"How?\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"You mean our birthright. Would you believe I learned a means by which I could withstand the surface climate for a while? Long enough to make a difference up there... or to try.\"\n Hades : \n\"Impossible... yet seemingly, all these impossibilities continue to occur. So you must vanquish the Titan, as well as come to the rescue of Olympus. How utterly absurd that you are burdened with all that...\"\nMiscellaneous Conversations.\nAbout Pain.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"It hurts my heart to see you like this, Father. But, it brings me peace. And strength. Helps that this chamber isn't crawling with Satyrs...\"\n Hades : \n\"Oh they have sense enough to keep their distance from me... or perhaps Cerberus. Well if seeing me in this pitiable state should spur you to your fullest wrath, then so be it.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"That's not quite it; I don't feel loathing or hatred. Elsewhere in Tartarus, perhaps, but not here. Not anymore. I just hope my presence doesn't cause you further pain.\"\n Hades : \n\"No. The only pain... is that your mother and I, your brother, this dog, that we were not... we could not be there to see you grow. Each time I see you now... it fills an absence that was there.\"\n&lt;a href=\"https%3A//hades.fandom.com/wiki/Chronos/Quotes%23Hades_Flashback_in_Tartarus%3A~%3Atext%3Dmy%2520little%2520spell...-%2CHades%2520Flashback%2520in%2520Tartarus%2C-Collapse\"&gt;About the Nightmare&lt;/a&gt;.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"When Chronos took our family and the House, and you bade the Witch of the Crossroads take me... I remember it somehow, or dreamt of it. Did he... demand you tell him of the Fates?\"\n Hades : \n\"How could you possibly...? He did. Perhaps the Fates themselves permitted you that bit of insight. He did his worst to discover where they hide... though would have failed, even if I did possess the knowledge that he sought.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Wait, you never told Chronos how to find the Fates? Then how did he? Because he's captured them. Not long ago, perhaps, but nonetheless. I'm certain of it.\"\n Hades : \n\"\"Hah! \"If this is true, well then my father's plan for conquest is much closer to fruition than I thought. I do not know how he could find the Fates. But if they can do nothing against him now... Daughter, what chance do you have...?\"\nAbout The &lt;a href=\"Oath%20of%20the%20Unseen\"&gt;Oath of the Unseen&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hades : \n\"The darkness stirs in such a way as I've not felt since very long ago. This cannot be the Titan's work. It must be that of the Witch of the Crossroads, if not you.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Father: \"In shadow, I serve; to shadow, I return. \"Thus have I sworn the Oath of the Unseen, who serve this realm, and execute the will of Night.\"\n Hades : \n\"I know less of the Unseen than you suppose. As it should be, lest the Titan could have learned much more. Then, may you serve the will of Night judiciously...\"\nAbout Characters.\n&lt;a href=\"Hecate\"&gt;Hecate&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hades : \n\"Daughter, tell me what... became of the Witch of the Crossroads, should you know. When all seemed lost... your mother and I, we left you in her care.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"And she has cared for me ever since. Prepared me. Though, we had best not speak of her in these chambers. Suffice it to say, the Unseen remain in shadow.\"\n Hades : \n\"Good. She was... well as you say, we'd best say nothing more. Though if you have the opportunity, extend to her my deepest gratitude.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Nyx\"&gt;Nyx&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hades : \n\"Nyx, herself... even she was powerless against the Titan. Two of Night Incarnate's own sons served in my House along with her... I suppose he has them, too.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"No, Hypnos is with \"us! \"Fast asleep for all this time, perhaps some sort of... defensive response, for we have found no way to wake him. Brave Schelemeus is with us as well!\"\n Hades : \n\"Hypnos, asleep \"again? \"And I've no recollection of that other name... but time has worn on me, perhaps. Regardless, if the Witch yet leads the Unseen... the will of Night is not yet lost.\"\n&lt;a href=\"https%3A//hades.fandom.com/wiki/Hades/Relationships%23Olympian_Gods%3A~%3Atext%3Dthan%2520fearing%2520Hades.-%2COlympian%2520Gods%2C-Hades%2520once%2520fought\"&gt;About Hades' Brothers&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hades : \n\"My brothers each are aiding you, are they? Zeus, doubtless leading from behind the safety of his palace walls... Poseidon, blustering as though his victory is already at hand...\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Father, they're fighting to defend their home... and they're fighting for \"you! \"You're right that neither one is much inclined to show concern, but why should they? Fear spreads.\"\n Hades : \n\"They sat oblivious upon their surface realm for far too long...! But do not listen to my rantings about them. Had you known your own brother, perhaps you'd better understand the impulse for such ill-conceived remarks...\"\n&lt;a href=\"Cerberus\"&gt;Cerberus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hades : \n\"What has that blasted Titan done to Cerberus, that he should storm into this place with such abandon, only to be ushered out again? Takes a small army of Satyrs to drive him back...\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Chronos casts him out into the Mourning Fields above. Then rage and despair congeal about him, and his better senses take leave. My own path leads me through where he resides.\"\n Hades : \n\"So you must face him in that sorry state. Thank you, Daughter, for taking pity on the moody beast. He has seen better, but been through worse. You were too young to form a bond before, but perhaps... it is not too late.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Bouldy\"&gt;Bouldy&lt;/a&gt;.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Where's Cerberus, Father? He's usually right here. I saw him in the Fields as before!\"\n Hades : \n\"He runs amok at my behest. Spreads the attention of the Titan's legions thin. Eventually they drive him back, but can do him no harm.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"So just you and the boulder, then. Looking as though it's not been heaved up any hills in quite a while. Chronos doesn't make you do it?\"\n Hades : \n\"I'd have less difficult a time than a mere Shade. Besides, these shackles cannot be unlocked, save by the Titan's command. But I'd remain here for eternity before I'd grovel at his feet.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"You say this boulder was companion to a mortal king? I... sense something from it. There can be so much energy within a common stone.\"\n Hades : \n\"I'll take you at your word. The boulder and I... we're not as close as was its last relationship. Though perhaps you shall coax something from it; the Witch apparently has taught you everything.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Sisyphus\"&gt;Sisyphus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hades : \n\"This chamber... it once held a prisoner of mine. A mortal king who had attempted to cheat Death! I forced the wretch to heave that boulder up that path forever. He forgave me anyway.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Forget him, Father. What purpose does it serve to dwell on some dead mortal now? Chronos wants you to wallow in your guilt. Don't.\"\n Hades : \n\"You misunderstand. The prisoner, he was called Sisyphus the King. His boulder there was like a friend. He... asked his friend to keep me company. Until more company arrived, he said.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Well then, I'm grateful to that boulder and the king. Chronos must not have accounted for your former prisoners being fond of you.\"\n Hades : \n\"Oh most of them are not. Some chose to join the Titan's legions and remain here in Tartarus. Not anywhere I cast my gaze, of course.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Charon\"&gt;Charon&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hades : \n\"...The scent of blood. You're injured. And you expect to face the Titan still? At least you're in the right place should you die.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"I won't be dying here no matter what. As for my injuries, perhaps Lord Charon has some Life Essence in stock.\"\n Hades : \n\"Even now the Boatman plies his trade? Absurd. Our entire operation was shut down! Although... I ought remember that he serves this realm, not me.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hades : \n\"Daughter. Tell me something of yourself, for I know not a thing. For instance... what is it that you like to do? When you are not... attempting this.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"What do I like to do? Well... I ensure all of my reagents are in order, so when practicing my craft, what I need is always close at hand. And I like to... \"ungh\", Father, this rings false...\"\n Hades : \n\"\"Mm. \"Neither the time nor place for trivialities... perhaps, however, at some point... we may discuss such matters more. But there are scores to settle first.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hades : \n\"You have the Death Defiance. Runs in the family. Your brother Zagreus, he was also rather sturdy for his stature. Hard-headed, as a boy.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Don't speak of him as though he's gone! Chronos has him, and Mother, and the rest. But when all this is over... we'll see each other again.\"\n Hades : \n\"How can you be so certain? To make such guarantees of the unknown! The Titan... my father... he shall not stop. He is the most hard-headed of us all.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Persephone\"&gt;Persephone&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hades : \n\"Your mother was so proud when you were born. We... did not always think that we would have another child. But we decided to try again.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"And you did the most important thing parents can do. You \"protected \"me. As for my mother, I know her beautiful smile. The way she's looking at me in the painting that I have.\"\n Hades : \n\"The painting, it survived?! The Witch, she must have taken it... and such a risk, for such a thing. Know that your mother's radiance... cannot be captured. No matter the artist's skill.\"\n&lt;a href=\"https%3A//hades.fandom.com/wiki/Hades/Relationships%23Family%3A~%3Atext%3DHeracles-%2CFamily%2C-Persephone\"&gt;Family&lt;/a&gt;.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"You saw what happened... what Chronos did to Mother, and my brother, and the rest. Where are they? Where is he holding them?\"\n Hades : \n\"My knowledge of this is not up-to-date. He... made everybody stop, somehow. I saw them, still as stone; not petrified exactly but ensnared, in the Great Hall of the House. He must have stored them someplace else inside...\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Even when I'm able to vanquish Chronos on a given night, most of the House is sealed off, and I'm unable to remain for long. How can we break them out...?\"\n Hades : \n\"Perhaps if you ask the Titan very nicely, he shall comply? Daughter, I know of no way to undo his work, and have no wisdom to impart. But \"this\", I can provide.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Chronos\"&gt;Chronos&lt;/a&gt; (Won Battle).\nDialogue 01.\n Hades : \n\"Such a cacophony occurred, after you last visited. Exactly when I cannot say. All of the Titan's wretched servants flew into a panic. Their cries would not cease. What transpired?\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Perhaps they were concerned for their master. Or busy trying to bring him back to life. Because I slew him, finally. And it won't be the last time.\"\n Hades : \n\"Blood and darkness, \"hah... urgh! \"Then you accomplished... that which once took half the blasted strength of Olympus... all on your own.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Not on my own at all. I had their strength, if not their support; as you've given me yours. Father, we can stop him. And for now... we can kill him.\"\n Hades : \n\"He shall seek vengeance with a renewed zeal. This entire plot of his is driven by the same impulse. Then, kill him if you must. At least... his many deaths ought keep him occupied.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Perhaps they were concerned for their master. Or busy trying to bring him back to life. Because I slew him once again. And it won't be the last time.\"\n Hades : \n\"Blood and darkness, \"hah! Urgh... \"To have achieved such an outcome... which once required half the blasted strength of all Olympus, on your own...\"\nWith Other Characters.\n&lt;a href=\"Hecate\"&gt;Hecate&lt;/a&gt; (Pre-Main Story).\n Hecate : \n\"...But, Lord Hades, I...\"\n Hades : \n\"...You have your orders. Now return to shadow. And, take care of her. For all of us.\"\n Hecate : \n\"No harm shall come to young Melino\u00eb, my lord. In this, at least, I shall not fail you.\"\n Hecate : \n\"Farewell...\"\n Hades : \n\"Goodbye, Daughter...\"\nGifts.\n&lt;a href=\"Nectar\"&gt;Nectar&lt;/a&gt;.\nGift Decline.\n Melino\u00eb : Father, while I know this wasn't necessarily permitted, I thought if maybe it would be of any comfort at all, that I might offer you this Nectar?\n Hades : Exactly like your brother, blast... I fear I'm not in any mood or state for such a thing. Concern yourself not with my comfort, but with the target of your wrath."}
{"id": "2521", "revid": "29110118", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2521", "title": "Hades/Relationships", "text": "Family.\nPersephone.\n&lt;a href=\"Persephone\"&gt;Persephone&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' wife.&lt;br&gt;Their relationship fell apart at some point in the past, partly due to the apparent stillbirth of Zagreus. Persephone left the underworld, while Hades hid the truth about her to Zagreus and forbade all mention of her in the House. Although Persephone had left Olympus willingly, she was technically forced to come to the Underworld by Zeus. Hades was similarly forced into the situation by his scheming brother, although they've been smitten with each other for a while. Hades did his best to give his would-be bride her space. The two would eventually come to love each other genuinely, and she brought a kinder side out of him. However, their relationship eventually faltered, largely due to the death of their newborn son, Zagreus. She left the Underworld, but did not return to Olympus, and Hades left her alone. However, Nyx pulled a favor with the Fates, and had Zagreus revived, but Hades chose to not tell Persephone in a bid to protect them from the Olympians, and concealed Zagreus' true parentage from the boy, even going so to forbid her mention in the House of Hades. When Zagreus brings Persephone back from the surface, she reunites with Hades, and the two slowly patch things up. She encourages her husband to be kinder and more patient with Zagreus, and their subjects. \nHades hasn't seen his wife since the day his father Chronos conquered his House. He mentions to his daughter Melino\u00eb that no artist could capture Persephone's beauty and expresses disappointment that the Argent Skull did not protect her as much as he preferred. \nZagreus.\n&lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' son.&lt;br&gt;Hades has a bitter relationship with his son, viewing him as a disappointment. Prior, he tried various methods to toughen Zagreus up and shape him according to his ideals. He is deeply displeased by Zagreus's attempts to escape. Upon Persephone's return and encouragement, their relationship softens somewhat, resembling mutual respect. However, Zagreus has yet to forgive his father fully, and Hades does not expect forgiveness for his actions. Hades eventually makes Zagreus' escape attempts an official job description to stress-test the Underworld's security. By the time of Persephone's return, Zagreus' relationship with his father has improved significantly, in part due to her presence. However, Zagreus is still not able to forgive his father's rude and bitter treatment over the years, while Hades expects no such grace, and instead recognizes that it is his fault in the first place. During their fights on the surface, after the Epilogue, they will mock each other with trivial matters in a light-hearted manner, while showing mutual respect for their skills and combat abilities.\nHades hasn't seen his son since the day his father Chronos conquered his House. He mentions to his daughter Melino\u00eb that Zagreus was quite headstrong for his stature when he was a boy and that it was he who was in charge of decorating the House.\nMelino\u00eb.\n&lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' daughter.&lt;br&gt;At some point after the events of the first game, Hades and Persephone had a second child, a daughter they named Melino\u00eb. However, shortly after her birth, the House of Hades was overthrown by Chronos. Hades entrusted Melino\u00eb to the Titaness Hecate, who was to keep her safe at the Crossroads.\nHades wouldn't see his daughter again until years later when she begun her task to defeat Chronos. Hades is calm and soft towards her, a clear contrast to how he is with Zagreus. He fears Melino\u00eb's mission and the toll it might take on her, as before it took six gods to overthrow the Titan of Time, and now that task fell to only one. Nonetheless, he stays determined in his own mission and lends her his personal aid against Chronos.\nCerberus.\n&lt;a href=\"Cerberus\"&gt;Cerberus&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' animal companion.&lt;br&gt;Cerberus appears to be Hades' only genuine companion and reprieve from his ongoing work.\nHouse of Hades.\nNyx.\n&lt;a href=\"Nyx\"&gt;Nyx&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' co-manager.&lt;br&gt;Hades and Nyx co-manage the underworld domain. Though they seem to tolerate each other begrudgingly, they hold mutual respect for one another. Before Hades' arrival to the underworld, Nyx held everything together but wasn't quite as scaled up on the parchment work or the details of the daily operations of the underworld. Upon Hades' arrival to the underworld, Nyx found Hades to be resourceful and efficient in keeping the underworld's details and operational aspects in good order. Occasionally, Hades and Nyx may disagree on certain things concerning Zagreus and the Olympians. Still, Nyx has no trouble reminding Hades of his place and shows it by literally shaking the entire house of Hades. Hades may control the maintenance of the underworld and placement and punishment of the shades, Titans, and primordial gods, but Nyx is the Night itself and not under the rule of Hades. Nyx and Hades, therefore, have a mutually beneficial arrangement, but Nyx is not a force to be toyed with by anyone, including Hades.\nHypnos.\n&lt;a href=\"Hypnos\"&gt;Hypnos&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' employee.&lt;br&gt;Supposedly, Hypnos is tasked with overseeing the newly arrived deceased souls. However, he prefers to spend most of his time sleeping, chatting, and only occasionally fulfilling his duties. The reason he hasn't been fired is because Hades finds him highly amusing, and Hypnos often gets a good laugh out of his boss (a rarity for Hades). As a result, Hades keeps him around as an unofficial court jester of sorts.\nDespite Hypnos not being the best employee, at some point, he became more dependable to Hades and more obedient than Thanatos, who often assists Zagreus from the shadows. Hypnos' effort is recognized by Hades, especially in improving his reception duties. This eventually leads to Hypnos having his face on the employee recognition board of Hades.\nIn Achilles' Codex, Hades seems to genuinely appreciate Hypnos' presence, as it brings a softer and more fun side to the House, which is much needed.\nAchilles.\n&lt;a href=\"Achilles\"&gt;Achilles&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' employee.&lt;br&gt;Hades had Achilles sign a contract stating that he would work for Hades; his job involves training and looking after Zagreus, and guarding the &lt;a href=\"https%3A//hades.fandom.com/wiki/House_of_Hades%23West_Wing\"&gt;West Wing&lt;/a&gt;.\nMegaera.\n&lt;a href=\"Megaera\"&gt;Megaera&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' employee.&lt;br&gt;Hades places deep trust in Megaera, selecting her exclusively to punish Zagreus. He does so because he knows she has unresolved matters with Zagreus and will execute the task efficiently. She is also a crucial figure in the administration of the underworld, extremely important as an enforcer in her role to maintain order. Megaera is the Fury sister in whom Hades has the most confidence because she is helpful and worth keeping within the House. She also fulfills her role of disciplining her sisters for him.\nAlthough Megaera is strict in the work environment, Hades likely sees her as similar, although he's not sure if Megaera agrees with this. He understands her sense of duty towards him, and she never breaks an order.\nThanatos.\n&lt;a href=\"Thanatos\"&gt;Thanatos&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' employee.&lt;br&gt;Hades regards him quite highly owing to his unwavering work ethic, to the extent that he becomes the poster child for motivational posters in the administrative office. Nevertheless, within the inner circle, Thanatos doesn't appear to hold Hades' directives as unassailable decrees, unlike the unquestionable authority of his mother, Nyx. He's even open to adjusting or finding loopholes in these directives, a departure from his usual demeanor, all in a bid to aid Hades' offspring, Zagreus.\nThis favor, however, dissipates when Hades uncovers his complicity in Zagreus' actions. The discovery casts a shadow over their once-respected professional relationship.\nCharon.\n&lt;a href=\"Charon\"&gt;Charon&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' employee.&lt;br&gt;Charon is regarded as one of Hades' most valued employees. Hades acknowledges that Charon is present in the underworld before him, diligently performing his duties. It's likely that Charon's role is of utmost importance, and he holds an equal standing with Hades. Hades doesn't take Charon lightly and knows how to show him the respect he deserves. He also understands the significance of Charon's presence, realizing that the underworld would face uncertain outcomes without him.\nUnderworld Residents.\n&lt;a href=\"Alecto\"&gt;Alecto&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Tisiphone\"&gt;Tisiphone&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' employees.&lt;br&gt;The Furies are the main employees that Hades sends after his runaway son to punish him in his place. Even though he doesn't have as much security and confidence in them as he does in Megaera and Thanatos, he will send them in Megaera's place if she fails, despite her protests. This is because they have caused him a lot of headaches, having expelled Tisiphone and Alecto from the house due to previous conflicts they caused within the House. He still chooses them for this task.\n&lt;a href=\"Theseus\"&gt;Theseus&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Asterius\"&gt;Asterius&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' employees.&lt;br&gt;Hades's champions, he recognized Theseus and Asterius as his champions. Hades summoned them to defeat his rebel son in whatever way they desired.\nOrpheus.\n&lt;a href=\"Orpheus\"&gt;Orpheus&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' employee.&lt;br&gt;Hades's Court Musician. In fact, Orpheus does not see his wife, due to his favor to the House. He is too torn over Eurydice to even sing, let alone compose, so Hades puts him in solitary confinement, revealing that Eurydice is more important than fearing Hades.\nOlympian Gods.\nHades once fought alongside his Olympian siblings to defeat the Titans. Nowadays, he has a low opinion of the Olympians, and has cut off communication with them. In particular he seems to resent his brother Zeus due to past quarrels (and, as is later revealed, the reason behind Persephone initially departing Olympus for the Underworld).\nZeus.\n&lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' younger brother.&lt;br&gt;Hades has a complicated relationship with his youngest brother. Although Hades had an interest in the daughter of the goddess Demeter, he never asked for his brother's help in getting her attention, let alone kidnapping her, and he certainly didn't see her as a \"gift\" that could be given as an object. Zagreus will tell Hades is enraged with him, Zeus says that he and Hades had a fight, which he wants to fix, and that the next time Zagreus sees Hades, tells him that he forgives him, this forgiveness only serves to drive him crazy, because their disagreement was entirely Zeus's fault.\nPoseidon.\n&lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' younger brother.&lt;br&gt;Poseidon and Hades were trapped in their father's stomach for part of their lives, indicating they share a drama that Zeus does not share with them.\nHades was the one who taught Poseidon how to fight with his trident, after giving up using the sword. When he gave up using a sword, and much to Hades' dismay, Poseidon became so well known that he is now associated with the weapon. Poseidon is fond of his brother, Hades, however, admits he rarely misses him and wouldn't want his right influence to interfere with the way he handles things.\n-Upon use of Poseidon's Greater Call. Hades remarked, 'Poseidon has the habit of meddling in others' affairs!' He truly dislikes his brother's meddling habit!\nDemeter.\n&lt;a href=\"Demeter\"&gt;Demeter&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' foster sister and mother-in-law.&lt;br&gt;\nDemeter finds Hades dull and dislikes his dark presence. He is undoubtedly the last suitor she would ever want for her daughter. Hades is terrified of her and is keeping Persephone's existence a secret, partially out of fear of what she would do. Hades, in particular, calls her a \"witch\" who could do terrible things if she was angry. When Demeter found out the whole truth, she was incredibly willing to accept that her daughter was married to him and loved him.\nAthena.\n&lt;a href=\"Athena\"&gt;Athena&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' niece.&lt;br&gt;-Upon use of Athena's Greater Call. Hades is too busy and did not directly contact his niece in Hades. He reminds Zagreus that Athena can't always protect him, indicating her subordination to him. This statement shows that, despite being an influential goddess, as part of a younger generation, she is subordinate to Hades and lacks the power to directly interfere with his commands. At least Hades knows that his niece puts herself in her place when addressing him, unlike Zagreus.\nAres.\n&lt;a href=\"Ares\"&gt;Ares&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' nephew.&lt;br&gt;-Upon use of Ares's Greater Call. Hades found it predictable that the god of war would be present! and made it clear that it is best for his nephew Ares to stay out of his affairs, labeling him a busybody.\nAres will express his admiration for his Uncle Hades, as he sees War and Death as going hand in hand. Ares is notably the only Olympian god who will offer praise to Hades without it feeling like a backhanded compliment.\nArtemis.\n&lt;a href=\"Artemis\"&gt;Artemis&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' niece.&lt;br&gt;-Upon use of Artemis's Greater Call. Hades thinks that Artemis should choose smaller prey and that this hunt is out of her reach.\nHades and Artemis are both indifferent, stoic, and preoccupied. Achilles speculates that despite all Hades resents and complains about regarding his \"irresponsible\" Olympian relatives, he could actually get along well with his reliable niece, equally distant and obedient, if he tried.\nIn the Epilogue, her encounter with her uncle fills her with excitement, even though she harbors reservations about his tendency to keep secrets. Still, she's willing to set aside these concerns.\nApollo.\n&lt;a href=\"Apollo\"&gt;Apollo&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' nephew.&lt;br&gt;Hades finds his nephew Apollo too bright for his eyes.\nAphrodite.\n&lt;a href=\"Aphrodite\"&gt;Aphrodite&lt;/a&gt;: The Goddess of Love and Beauty.\n-Upon use of Aphrodite's Greater Call. For Hades, Aphrodite has no jurisdiction in his domain. He calls her \u201cthat meddling goddess of love!\u201d Indicating that she herself interfered a lot in his love life.&lt;br&gt;\nHermes.\n&lt;a href=\"Hermes\"&gt;Hermes&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' nephew.&lt;br&gt;Hermes has met his uncle Hades once before the events of the game, presumably when he got assigned his role as psychopomp. He claims to have been a \"memorable experience\".\nInitially, they don't seem to have much in common in terms of temperament, but both are quite dedicated to their duties. Hermes was present during the making of the Pact of Punishment, and likely gave his own insights, which implies Hades doesn't mind his opinion, a rare occurrence.\nDionysus.\n&lt;a href=\"Dionysus\"&gt;Dionysus&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' nephew.\n-Upon use of Dionysus's Greater Call. \"Hades says that drunk's power means nothing to him!\". \u201cWhy are you staining my clothes with wine?!\u201d. \"This is a battle, not a time for revelry!\" Indicating that his nephew is clueless enough.\nLater, Zagreus suggests that his father enjoyed a good party, but Hades will never agree, especially if Dionysus is in the mix.\nThe Titans.\nThe previous rulers of the world, defeated in the Titan War and imprisoned in the pits of &lt;a href=\"Tartarus\"&gt;Tartarus&lt;/a&gt;.\nChronos.\n&lt;a href=\"Chronos\"&gt;Chronos&lt;/a&gt;: Hades' father.&lt;br&gt; Hades fought and overthrew Chronos and the other Titans, and imprisoned them in Tartarus. In various dialogues with Zagreus, Hades has described the Titans as exceedingly cruel and terrible parents, far worse than he ever was. The only good thing Hades has said about his father, was that he was less of a terrible father than the Titan Hyperion (Demeter's father), who was considered to be the worst of them all. By the time of &lt;a href=\"Hades%20II\"&gt;Hades II&lt;/a&gt;, Chronos has escaped the pits of Tartarus, and captured Hades.\nOthers.\nHeracles.\n&lt;a href=\"Heracles\"&gt;Heracles&lt;/a&gt;: Mightiest of Men.&lt;br&gt; \nHades despises Heracles entirely and still harbors resentment and anger toward him for invading the Underworld and unexpectedly stealing Cerberus in the past to fulfill one of his \"12 Labors\" requirements."}
{"id": "329", "revid": "49442578", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=329", "title": "Hades (game)", "text": "Hades is a roguelike game from &lt;a href=\"Supergiant%20Games\"&gt;Supergiant Games&lt;/a&gt;, creators of , and . You play as &lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt;, immortal son of &lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;, on his quest to escape from the underworld, fighting through many angry lost souls along the way. Death is a mere inconvenience for Zagreus, returning to &lt;a href=\"House%20of%20Hades\"&gt;Hades' palace&lt;/a&gt; each time to reflect in the &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20of%20Night\"&gt;Mirror of Night&lt;/a&gt; and try again. Receive &lt;a href=\"Boons\"&gt;Boons&lt;/a&gt; from the other &lt;a href=\"Characters%23Gods\"&gt;gods&lt;/a&gt; of Olympus and find treasures to aid in each escape attempt.\nOn December 8, 2022, the sequel to Hades, &lt;a href=\"Hades%20II\"&gt;Hades II&lt;/a&gt;, was announced to be in development by Supergiant Games.\nOfficial description.\n\"Hades\" is a rogue-lite dungeon crawler in which you defy the god of the dead as you hack and slash your way out of the Underworld of Greek myth. We think it combines the best aspects of our previous games, including the fast-paced action of \"Bastion\", the rich atmosphere and depth of \"Transistor\", and the character-driven storytelling of \"Pyre\". \nIt\u2019s never the same experience twice: Each time you play, you'll combine the divine might of various Olympian gods with your own in new ways, brave a wide variety of different challenges, and unravel more of the story featuring our award-winning art, audio, and narrative. You may play for not just dozens of hours, but \"hundreds\" of hours, while still discovering new character builds and story events. "}
{"id": "2945", "revid": "15872423", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2945", "title": "Hades 2", "text": ""}
{"id": "2271", "revid": "49442578", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2271", "title": "Hades II", "text": "Hades II is a sequel to \"&lt;a href=\"Hades%20%28game%29\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;\" currently in development by &lt;a href=\"Supergiant%20Games\"&gt;Supergiant Games&lt;/a&gt;. \nYou play as &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt;, immortal daughter of &lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;, on her quest to defeat the &lt;a href=\"Chronos\"&gt;Titan of Time&lt;/a&gt;, battling numerous angry lost souls along the way. Death is a mere inconvenience for Melino\u00eb, who returns each time to &lt;a href=\"The%20Crossroads\"&gt;the crossroads&lt;/a&gt; to make incantations in Hecate's magical cauldron and try again. Receive &lt;a href=\"Boons\"&gt;Boons&lt;/a&gt; from the &lt;a href=\"Olympians\"&gt;Gods&lt;/a&gt; of Olympus and find treasures to aid in stopping Time itself.\nOfficial description.\n\"Hades II\" is a rogue-like dungeon crawler in which you'll battle beyond the Underworld of Greek myth using dark sorcery to take on the sinister Titan of Time. Our studio's first-ever sequel builds on the best aspects of the award-winning original in an all-new, action-packed, endlessly replayable experience rooted in the Underworld of Greek myth and its deep connections to the dawn of witchcraft. \nAs the immortal Princess of the Underworld, you'll explore a bigger, deeper mythic world, vanquishing the forces of the Titan of Time with the full might of Olympus behind you, in a sweeping story that continually unfolds through your every setback and accomplishment. New locations, challenges, upgrade systems, and surprises await as you delve into the ever-shifting Underworld again and again."}
