 linger there for long.\"\n Hecate : \n\"Truly? And, you retrieved something from him, I see. We were never going to destroy him with brute force alone, but soon enough, he may yet be undone entirely. Until then, study him. And I shall study what you found...\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"By \"study him\", you mean find him again, and fight him... weaken him... distract him?\"\n Hecate : \n\"Precisely that.\"\n Hecate : \n\"Oh, by the way... something awaits you in the training grounds. You proved beyond a doubt that you're prepared.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Moros\"&gt;Moros&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hecate : \n\"One more of Nyx's kin is here for us to mind. Your incantation tracked him after all! \"Doom \"typically arrives \"un\"invited, of course.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Lord Moros is to be our guest. I know his presence must seem an ill portent, but if the Fates wanted him here, who are we to fight it?\"\n Hecate : \n\"Who, indeed.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"I found him, Headmistress! My father! Chronos has him locked away in Tartarus. But, I couldn't save him... he asked I leave him be...\"\n Hecate : \n\"Truly? How utterly predictable of Chronos to gloat in such a way. I regret that your reunion with Lord Hades thus transpired... though, I am gladdened you discovered him. How does he fare?\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"He... \"ungh. \"I really wouldn't know. He seemed sound of mind and body, and he knew me soon enough. Gave me what blessing he could still bestow. What can we do?\"\n Hecate : \n\"If he asked you leave him be, then 'tis evidence he wishes to remain unseen. Use full discretion and be brief, should you encounter him again; and \"I \"shall see about ensuring Chronos remains ignorant of your newfound connection.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Headmistress, I've a message from my father that he asked me to relay: He sends his deepest gratitude...\"\n Hecate : \n\"Lord Hades told you this? \"Whyever for? \"He \"rots \"in his own prison whilst the Titan ransacks his domain! My charge was to safeguard the realm and I did not.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Father spoke of when he left me in your care, when Chronos struck. He must have feared the worst. Now he knows I'm well... all thanks to you.\"\n Hecate : \n\"No, Melino\u00eb, all this is thanks to \"Chronos. \"Your father would do well to save his gratitude ere we settle certain scores. Though... speak not to him of this... undignified response. I merely was taken aback.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Of course. I understand.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Cerberus\"&gt;Cerberus&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"At the edge of the Mourning Fields... I faced some sort of dark, infernal beast. Three monstrous canine maws, bellowing with fury and sorrow. It was my father's... my \"family's \"old dog... wasn't it?\"\n Hecate : \n\"Through Odysseus we have a few reports about a creature fitting that description, more or less, but... Cerberus was \"red \"in hue, as blood. Nevertheless, a stay within the Fields could have transformative effects. \"Tsk\", wretched thing. Torn from its home.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"He doesn't seem to know who I am. Whether because it's been too long, or there's too much on his mind. Minds? But I felt a flash of recognition. He isn't too far gone, is he...?\"\n Hecate : \n\"The nature of a beast can never change. Like us, however, they at times must fight the daemons that torment them... a battle in which you can assist! Trust your training, and perhaps he can yet shake the spell that's overtaken him.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"I'm certain that he can.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hecate : \n\"You've not escaped the Mourning Fields as yet. The beast guarding the entrance into Tartarus seems insurmountable. 'Tis the effect of the Fields themselves.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"What hope I have begins to drain from me as soon as I set foot in there. I know it's just a trick of the mind, but...\"\n Hecate : \n\"...but an effective trick it is, I know.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Headmistress, Lord Zeus requested \"prompt reports\", his words, from you about the situation in the Underworld. He seemed a little frustrated. Asked me to let you know.\"\n Hecate : \n\"And you're as dutiful as ever, aren't you? Exactly as Lord Zeus wants us to be. Think you he truly cherishes these Underworld reports?\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"I... hadn't considered that he might not. He seems the sort to want to know about all goings-on, especially ones dangerous to him.\"\n Hecate : \n\"Correct! He grows uneasy when the silence thickens. He'll get his prompt reports; though, just remember, he already \"has \"a messenger.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Artemis\"&gt;Artemis&lt;/a&gt;.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Headmistress, I found Artemis out there. I'd not expected her so soon, but then, she's quick. Speaking of which, what of Hermes, any word?\"\n Hecate : \n\"Alas, not yet. However, those two are resourceful and discreet... and Olympus remains none the wiser to our long-standing connection with them, if that is your concern.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"My concern is their safety. May Hermes soon discover what exactly Chronos is scheming and return, though I know we can ill afford to wait.\"\n Hecate : \n\"No, we cannot. Hermes convinced me of that.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hermes\"&gt;Hermes&lt;/a&gt;.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Hermes is back, Headmistress. He was able to lend some of his swiftness, and... also asked that I come to the aid of Olympus. Has the hour grown so desperate up there?\"\n Hecate : \n\"He would not ask otherwise. To be sure, this complicates the task. My view, however, is that you are not yet prepared for the surface. I'll not lift the wards barring that path.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"And if I were to lift them myself? I've seen you do it.\"\n Hecate : \n\"Then you'll be more prepared than you are now.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Arachne\"&gt;Arachne&lt;/a&gt;.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Headmistress, there must be something we can do for Arac