m more the sort that likes to freely move about. Always a trade-off to be made!\"\nAbout Legendary Boon.\nDialogue 01.\n Hephaestus : \n\"...You wouldn't know it, witchie, but I'm mad this evening. Nothing you did, mind! Fortunately, when I'm mad, I do good work. My \"best \"damn work if I say so myself...\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hephaestus : \n\"Can't guarantee a weapon worthy of the gods is going to be enough for you to see this through. But I \"can \"guarantee you're getting the very best.\"\nAbout Relationships.\n Hephaestus : \n\"Got off on the wrong foot from the first, me and my mum. Can you blame her? Imagine seeing splendorous Apollo and Athena and so on, thinking, \"oi, I want to make me one of those! \"But instead, \"heheheh\", you make me.\"\nAbout Parents.\n Hephaestus : \n\"No telling how many cousins I got, but you're another, \"eh? \"You're getting special treatment only 'cause my mum and dad, they asked me real nice. Don't mind the extra work!\"\nAbout Mortals.\nDialogue 01.\n Hephaestus : \n\"Those mortals, they sure got it rough of late. Sometimes I think there's just so blasted many of them now. More suffering and such! \"Eh\", reckon that's life! Don't get any say in being born, then do what we can.\nDialogue 02.\n Hephaestus : \n\"Oi what I said before, 'bout more mortals begetting more suffering and the like? Aphrodite, she reminded me there's more to it than that. And maybe she's right. It's just, I reckon the bad in things is easier to spot...\"\nAbout Volcanoes.\n Hephaestus : \n\"Feel any tremors, they are probably Uncle Poseidon shaking up the place. Though there \"are \"times it's me! When Earth herself gets angry with the state of things, I give 'er a good outlet to let off a little steam.\"\nAbout Practice.\n Hephaestus : \n\"This lot up here act like they all was born with all the talent in the world! Mayhap Apollo and Athena, sure, and Artemis, and Hermes... Aphrodite definitely, too, but, \"erm... point is! \"Most of us, we got to \"work \"at things before \"we're \"any good.\"\nAbout Legs.\n Hephaestus : \n\"Must like to run about don't you? Me, at this point I would rather sit. And so I do! Won't find a better set of legs than this anyplace besides on Aphrodite herself! Yet even still.\"\nAbout Backstory.\n Hephaestus : \n\"Must think I got it all up here, don't you? Well you'd be right! But let's just say you're not the only one who had to learn things the hard way, witchie. I needed to do what I do.\"\nAbout Automatons.\n Hephaestus : \n\"All this warring, bit concerned I'll end up typecast as a weaponsmith! I make a lot of things, you know! Jewelry, fancy chairs, walking automatons even! Though lately, it's all weapons, all the time...\"\nAbout &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; Cleating A Run (Underworld).\nDialogue 01.\n Hephaestus : \n\"\"Ohh, there \"you are! We'd lost you for a bit! Must have gone so deep, we couldn't spy on you no more. Well, you've still got your arms and legs! Must have turned out all right.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hephaestus : \n\"Am I to understand you gave a certain \"Titan \"a right thorough walloping of late? Mayhap I helped in my own way? Not like you took down Chronos with your bare hands, \"eh? \"Point is, \"good job\", witchie! \"\nGifts.\n&lt;a href=\"Nectar\"&gt;Nectar&lt;/a&gt;.\n1st Time.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Lord Hephaestus! Your services must be in very high demand. I'm grateful, and doubtless so are the Nocturnal Arms.\"\n Hephaestus : \n\"Look I don't work for tips. Though ours ain't an ordinary arrangement, and ain't often lately I get new regular clients! So, here. Call it a trade.\"\n\"Hephaestus gives &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; the &lt;a href=\"Adamant%20Shard\"&gt;Adamant Shard&lt;/a&gt;.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"I'm in your debt for this, Hephaestus sir.\"\n2nd Time.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"For you, mighty Hephaestus! Though, you may not have occasion for such offerings, working a hot forge every night and day...\"\n Hephaestus : \n\"Oi, this is just a service job, no need to get all cordial and the like. Nice gesture from you, though. So cheers and all.\"\n3rd Time.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Great Hephaestus! Your work is beyond compare, and I'm grateful for your candor with me as well. Please, take this offering.\"\n Hephaestus : \n\"Anytime I get an offering it's 'cause somebody wants something from me. You're already getting premium service, but hey, it's your Nectar! Well, mine now I reckon.\"\n4th Time.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Lord Hephaestus, you're so much more than your ingenious craft. I never could have expected you to be so generous to me, and I'm most grateful for it.\"\n Hephaestus : \n\"Oi witchie, is it hot in here, or are you embarrassing me to no end? Just let me work the blasted forge, no need to make a big deal.\""}
{"id": "2587", "revid": "31005", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2587", "title": "Hephaestus/Relationships", "text": "Family.\nAphrodite.\n&lt;a href=\"Aphrodite\"&gt;Aphrodite&lt;/a&gt;: Hephaestus's wife.&lt;br&gt;Hephaestus is married to Aphrodite. She laments to Zagreus that they spend little time together due to his work, though the way she says it makes it sound more like an excuse created on the spot than the actual truth, which is most likely her cheating nature.\nHera.\n&lt;a href=\"Hera\"&gt;Hera&lt;/a&gt;: Hephaestus's mother.&lt;br&gt;\nZeus.\n&lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt;: Hephaestus's father.&lt;br&gt;\nAres.\n&lt;a href=\"Ares\"&gt;Ares&lt;/a&gt;: Hephaestus's brother.&lt;br&gt;\nAthena.\n&lt;a href=\"Athena\"&gt;Athena&lt;/a&gt;: Hephaestus's half-sister.&lt;br&gt;\nArtemis.\n&lt;a href=\"Artemis\"&gt;Artemis&lt;/a&gt;: Hephaestus's half-sister.&lt;br&gt;\nApollo.\n&lt;a href=\"Apollo\"&gt;Apollo&lt;/a&gt;: AHephaestus's half-brother.&lt;br&gt;Hephaestus perceives Apollo as embodying the qualities Hera had hoped for in a son \u2013 socially adept and fitting for society. Despite Apollo's persistent attempts to draw him out of his cave, Hephaestus remains resolute in his seclusion. He views Apollo as insincere and overly intrusive in his life, lacking authenticity in their interactions.\nHermes.\n&lt;a href=\"Hermes\"&gt;Hermes&lt;/a&gt;: Hephaestus's half-brother.&lt;br&gt;\nDionysus.\n&lt;a href=\"Dionysus\"&gt;Dionysus&lt;/a&gt;: Hephaestus's half-brother.&lt;br&gt;In the second game, Hephaestus doesn't appear to have such a strained relationship with him. He comments that his brother doesn't seem to be in the right place, probably intoxicated somewhere. Not everyone is passionate about what they are fighting for.\nHestia.\n&lt;a href=\"Hestia\"&gt;Hestia&lt;/a&gt;: Hephaestus's maternal aunt.&lt;br&gt;\nDemeter.\n&lt;a href=\"Demeter\"&gt;Demeter&lt;/a&gt;: Hephaestus's maternal aunt.&lt;br&gt;\nPoseidon.\n&lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt;: Hephaestus's paternal uncle.&lt;br&gt;\nChthonic Gods.\nThe gods of the underworld.\nMelino\u00eb.\n&lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt;: Hephaestus's cousin.&lt;br&gt;Hephaestus arrives, extending his offer to assist Melino\u00eb, inquiring if she requires any repairs on her weapons. Known for his critical eye, he often scrutinizes the weaponry Melinoe wields, pointing out flaws and commenting on their imperfect craftsmanship. Initially reserved, Hephaestus keeps his distance; he harbors a disdain for magic, favoring manual craftsmanship, which occasionally earns Melino\u00eb the nickname \"little witch.\"\nOver time, Hephaestus begins to realize that she isn't like her other relatives. He sees Melino\u00eb's unique qualities, recognizing her genuine desire to help others without prying too much into their lives. Gradually, he opens up to her, sharing his insecurities about his artistry and family. When Melino\u00eb's brother, Zagreus, sought his aid, Hephaestus hesitated, unwilling to entangle himself in another family dispute. Yet, he later regrets his decision and chooses to assist Melinoe, seeking personal redemption for his past actions concerning Zagreus.\nZagreus.\n&lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt;: Hephaestus's cousin.&lt;br&gt;Hephaestus didn't come to his aid in the first game, but it's implied that they met later. He seems to find Zagreus naive for thinking that the problems of their families would vanish overnight. Hephaestus recalls when Zagreus sought help from his family; at that time, he didn't assist as he was tired of family dramas and intrusions. Later, he felt guilty for staying out of it, indicating that perhaps Zagreus was worth considering, just like Melino\u00eb.\nThe Titans.\nChronos.\n&lt;a href=\"Chronos\"&gt;Chronos&lt;/a&gt;: Hephaestus's paternal grandfather.&lt;br&gt;"}
{"id": "2120", "revid": "54283153", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2120", "title": "Hera", "text": "Hera is the &lt;a href=\"Olympian\"&gt;Olympian&lt;/a&gt; Goddess of Marriage and Queen of the Olympians.\nIn \"&lt;a href=\"Hades%20%28game%29\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;\", she is only mentioned as one of the previous bearers of &lt;a href=\"Coronacht\"&gt;Coronacht&lt;/a&gt;.\nShe appears in \"&lt;a href=\"Hades%20II\"&gt;Hades II&lt;/a&gt;\" and offers her boons to &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt;. Her &lt;a href=\"Status%20Curse\"&gt;Status Curse&lt;/a&gt; is Hitch which makes foes take damage when other afflicted foes are attacked.\nHera will only appear once Melino\u00eb has reached the surface.\nCharacteristics and Personality.\nThe feared and elegant queen of the gods, Hera assists &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; in overthrowing &lt;a href=\"Chronos\"&gt;Chronos&lt;/a&gt; primarily to act of good deeds and uphold her impeccable queenly image.\nA woman who bathes in extravagance, she is a socialite and vain, wanting to maintain her social status. Hera seems to despise those beneath her, she looks with little animosity, and only helps Melinoe because she doesn't have many options.\nParticularly discontent with her tiresome married life due to her &lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;husband&lt;/a&gt;'s constant escapades, Hera maintains a cynical view. Despite her pride and irony, she never admits her dissatisfaction. She sarcastically refers to herself and her husband as \"ideal models.\"\nKnown for her vengeful nature, Hera is not a loving stepmother, evident in her pursuit of Zeus's illegitimate children, like &lt;a href=\"Heracles\"&gt;Heracles&lt;/a&gt; and his enduring trials. Her displays of wrath are flashy.\nDespite her tumultuous marriage, Hera remains a faithful wife, committed to her husband. Their synchronized efforts, evident in mutual benefits, reflect their duo boon.\nLiving by appearances, Hera clearly favors &lt;a href=\"Ares\"&gt;Ares&lt;/a&gt; over &lt;a href=\"Hephaestus\"&gt;Hephaestus&lt;/a&gt;. However, her sighs and interactions suggest regret, especially regarding the strained relationship with her son. She gradually develops affection for Melino\u00eb, seeing her as the daughter she never had.\nPhysical description.\nHera appears as an imposing and beautiful woman with a dark complexion. She has light bluish hair framing her face and part of it is held high by a golden helmet. A feathery mantle falls from her head, with tons of greens and blues. Her eyes are violet, she wears golden hoop earrings and her nails are dark blue. She wears a teal dress with green peacock feathers for a pattern with an opening that leaves her leg exposed, on top of it a golden breastplate, and around the breasts it resembles feathers. Her neck is covered in dark green fabric with a golden infinite loop on the centre, also resembling wedding rings; it's further held together and decorated with golden plates shaped like feathers on the side. Her shoulders are covered in the same material as her dress, however resembling a plummage even more. She wears golden bracelets on both her wrists and an armband on her right forearm. Finally, she carries a scepter, one of her symbols, itself shaped like two intercepted wedding rings, further decoarted with loose bluish green fabric on the top and a floating green orb on the bottom circle.\nHistory.\nPast.\nHera is the daughter of the &lt;a href=\"The%20Titans\"&gt;titans&lt;/a&gt; Hyperion and Theia, and sister of &lt;a href=\"Hestia\"&gt;Hestia&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Demeter\"&gt;Demeter&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Helios\"&gt;Helios&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Selene\"&gt;Selene&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Eos\"&gt;Eos&lt;/a&gt;. Together with her older sisters, Hestia and Demeter, Hera joined &lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt;' side and helped him defeat the Titans. During the war she wielded &lt;a href=\"Coronacht\"&gt;Coronacht&lt;/a&gt;. After the war, Hera married Zeus and together they became the rulers of Olympus and its residents. At some point, presumably after she married Zeus, she would discard her weapon as she had other more important things to focus on.\nHades.\n&lt;a href=\"Coronacht\"&gt;Coronacht&lt;/a&gt; ended up in the possession of &lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt;, who could unlock her Aspect.\nHades II.\nHera appears to &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; after she reaches the surface and lends Melino\u00eb her boons.\nAffinity.\nIf given &lt;a href=\"Nectar\"&gt;Nectar&lt;/a&gt;, Hera will give you the &lt;a href=\"Iridescent%20Fan\"&gt;Iridescent Fan&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn Early Access, Hera's affinity gauge is maxed out at 3 hearts, requiring the gifting of 3 Nectar.\nGallery.\n&lt;tabber&gt;\nConcept=\nIllustration=\nMerchandise=\n&lt;/tabber&gt;"}
{"id": "2803", "revid": "4008728", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2803", "title": "Hera/Boons", "text": "Hera boons revolve around in applying her &lt;a href=\"Hades_II%23Status_Curses\"&gt;Status Curse&lt;/a&gt; Hitch which causes afflicted enemies to take 30% of the damage dealt to other afflicted enemies. Additionally, Hera can upgrade a boon's rarity. Hera's elemental affinity is &lt;a href=\"Earth\"&gt;Earth&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Aether\"&gt;Aether&lt;/a&gt; for her Duo Boons."}
{"id": "2752", "revid": "46051891", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2752", "title": "Hera/Quotes", "text": "The following are quotes from &lt;a href=\"Hera\"&gt;Hera&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Hades%20II\"&gt;Hades II&lt;/a&gt;\".\nFirst Meeting.\nDialogue 01 (Boon Dialogue).\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"The family stands united in our cause... \"In the name of Hades! Olympus, I accept this message!\"\"\n Hera : \n\"Pleased to make your acquaintance finally, my dear! Already had enough of the surface, yes? \"Heh\", well I promised the family that once you demonstrated your resolve to us, I'd take you under my wing. And I \"always \"keep my vows.\"\nDialogue 02 (Boon Dialogue).\n Hera : \n\"Pleased to make your acquaintance finally, my dear! Welcome to our world's surface, such as it is. I promised the family that once you demonstrated your resolve to us, then I'd take you under my wing... and, I \"always \"keep my vows.\"\nReactions.\nSeeing &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; at Low Health.\nDialogue 01.\n Hera : \n\"\"Oh! \"You're a frightful mess, if you'll forgive my saying, girl! I can't help you when you're practically dead! At least, not very much.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hera : \n\"What happened to all your lifeblood? That's precious stuff! Yet you've gone spilling it about, then have the \"nerve \"to thus present yourself to me.\"\nDialogue 03.\n Hera : \n\"However much you've trained, it evidently was not \"nearly \"enough, if you've \"already \"taken such a \"beating \"before I can even begin to protect you!\"\nDialogue 04.\n Hera : \n\"Not having a good night...? Your injuries will heal eventually, my dear. But, I can't make any promises about your pride.\"\nAbout Characters.\n&lt;a href=\"Chronos\"&gt;Chronos&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Hera : \n\"Remember, girl, this world is ours by right. The Fates themselves decided it! Now Chronos seeks to overthrow our reign? He already had his opportunity to rule. There is no going back to how things were.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hera : \n\"The Titan Chronos is no father of mine. But \"your \"father sprang from him, as did my husband, and Poseidon as well. So, now we're all tied up in this little family affair!\"\nDialogue 03.\n Hera : \n\"Would that I could put another arrow in between the eyes of Chronos again myself, but alas, you're closer and I'm stuck. Kill him for me, would you?\"\nDialogue 04.\n Hera : \n\"This matter with Chronos, it may seem unconscionable that a parent could resent their own children. But let me tell you, girl, there are moments when I \"almost \"sympathize.\"\nDialogue 05.\n Hera : \n\"I always knew Chronos would return. Zeus kept saying I was fearful over nothing! We buried the old wretch in the depths of Tartarus, after all. But he's a deathless Titan. \"Time\", it seems, slipped through our fingers...\"\n&lt;a href=\"Fates\"&gt;The Fates&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hera : \n\"The Fates are gone, then, yes? According to Hermes? Quite the unfortunate turn of events if true. Well, if Chronos is bent on vengeance, it only makes sense that he would take it out on \"them\", not just on \"us.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hera : \n\"\"Ah\", your poor father. You must have been the jewel in his eye, only to have been ripped away! He would have been so very proud. Well, perhaps not \"proud\", as such. He was never big on taking pride in anything, now that I think on it. \"I'm \"proud of you, at least!\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hecate\"&gt;Hecate&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hera : \n\"The Witch of the Crossroads evidently raised you well! The younger generation here, they lack in character, and their manners oft leave \"much \"to be desired. Almost as though \"my \"generation did not set the best example!\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hephaestus\"&gt;Hephaestus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hera : \n\"\"Augh\", at least Hephaestus is \"attempting \"to be of use! You'll have to excuse my sheltered son, girl. He'd much prefer to clang ceaselessly upon his forge than to be a part of polite society.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Aphrodite\"&gt;Aphrodite&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hera : \n\"The goddess of love, always one step ahead of me. How many mortals do you suppose would seek me out to bless their wedding vows, had Aphrodite not already worked her \"charms \"on them? It seems our strengths go hand in hand.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hyperion\"&gt;Hyperion&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hera : \n\"My sisters Demeter and Hestia and I, our father was the Titan called Hyperion. \"Father \"by technicality at least. You don't hear much about \"him \"anymore! We should have dealt with Chronos just the same back when we had the chance.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Eris\"&gt;Eris&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hera : \n\"No surprise that Strife Incarnate recently decided to show up, as she is wont to do. Eris made good sport of us before! Must think we're fools and easy prey. You'll correct her, yes?\"\n&lt;a href=\"Heracles\"&gt;Heracles&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Hera : \n\"Word reached me you've encountered mighty Heracles! Big, thick-headed fellow? You're not to aid him in his labors, do you understand? He's in the middle of what we Olympians like to call a \"journey of self-discovery.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hera : \n\"That Heracles is Zeus' lad, you know. \"Glory of Hera! \"I should be honored. He's just another mouth for me to feed, and one with quite an appetite, at that. But, I'll keep him busy, sure! We need all the help we can get.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Hera : \n\"For all his foibles, my husband makes a dangerous adversary. Why else do you think we've ruled for however many aeons it's been? Zeus doubtless has his enemies, but few are brave or misguided enough to let on.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hera : \n\"Lord Zeus and I, we've known each other for a time. A regular old married couple we are! And yet such awful things are often said of us. I try to brush it off! No couple is beyond reproach; certainly, not one that's survived as long as we.\"\nDialogue 03.\n Hera : \n\"\"Ah! \"I see that my distinguished husband has already been in touch. Well, just in case he doesn't make the sparks fly in \"quite \"the manner you expect, I have something for you of my own.\"\nDialogue 04.\n Hera : \n\"Again, Lord Zeus has reached you first, has he? \"Heh. \"The noble Son of Chronos and his lightning speed! You can't imagine just how quickly he flees from \"me\", sometimes.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Polyphemus\"&gt;Polyphemus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hera : \n\"Confronted one-eyed Polyphemus, have you, then? That is the sort of \"help \"Chronos employs. A hollow fool! But strong, admittedly. No sneaking past \"him\", I'm afraid. We've tried...\"\n&lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hera : \n\"Had I but known that stout Poseidon went out of his way for you earlier, I would have got here even sooner. The sea is unreliable, whilst my bond is forever. Figuratively, at least!\"\n&lt;a href=\"Apollo\"&gt;Apollo&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hera : \n\"Golden Apollo already offered you his aid, has he now? Always so eager to please. I find his constant doting bothersome... but doubtless you're more tolerant than I.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hestia\"&gt;Hestia&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hera : \n\"I'm pleased to see that you're agreeable with Hestia, my dear. Her temper and my own don't often mesh, but I respect her wisdom, and her power to simply burn everything down if and when necessary.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Demeter\"&gt;Demeter&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hera : \n\"Cold vengeance... I can feel it from afar. I suppose my sister Demeter has more at stake in this than anybody on this mountaintop. Our enemies shall rue having crossed her.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hermes\"&gt;Hermes&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hera : \n\"Where is that \"Hermes \"when you need him, have you seen him lately, girl? Always \"flitting \"about, impossible to pin down. \"Eugh. \"What news could there be to deliver at a time like \"this?\n&lt;a href=\"Selene\"&gt;Selene&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hera : \n\"You know, I saw a flicker in the sky before, as though the moonlight shifted for a moment. But now it's almost as though that light is shining from \"you. \"You drew Selene down? She would not answer such a call from most.\"\nWith Other Characters.\n&lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n\"\"Ah! \"Look, my dear! It's my beloved husband. The distinguished \"King of the Olympians\", who shall lead us all out of this mess. How goes it, Son of Chronos, any news?\"\n Zeus : \n\"Oh, \"hahaha! \"Come now, Hera dear, for all your jesting with me, it can send the wrong impression to one unaccustomed to your dry and clever wit! You see that, Melino\u00eb? Humor is the bond that makes a marriage strong!\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hera : \n\"Our family's unity does not come cheap. We all must work together to ensure the bonds connecting us don't fray, or split entirely as was the case with Chronos. My Lord Husband knows this better than anyone, don't you, Zeus?\"\n Zeus : \n\"You're quite right, Dear, that marriage can most certainly begin to feel like work! It was so easy for us in the early days, but our responsibilities have grown since, haven't they?\"\nDialogue 03.\n Zeus : \n\"My command of the heavens is nothing compared to the strength of our family bond! The Queen and I have stood together through worse times than \"this. \"Haven't we, Dear?\"\n Hera : \n\"\"Oh \"why, we've stood together now through more hard times than I can count! I daresay we're well past due for a break. Perhaps after our present difficulties finally subside?\"\n&lt;a href=\"Aphrodite\"&gt;Aphrodite&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Hera : \n\"Even Titans and gods are quite vulnerable creatures, deep down. For we are all driven by a most-delicate instrument, as liable to stir our spirits or drive us to despair, as my dear Aphrodite knows full well.\"\n Aphrodite : \n\"Come now, my Queen! The heart's the strongest part we've got and tougher than it seems! We've withstood a bit upon this mountaintop, but we can take much more. Especially when our hearts \"all \"beat as one!\"\nDialogue 02.\n Aphrodite : \n\"Be on your \"best \"behavior now, gorgeous! For I present to you our most resplendent Queen. No stranger to the ways of war, or to extinguishing the wretchedness that festers in the hearts of the wicked! Behold, \"our Lady Hera!\"\n Hera : \n\"I think we're past the need for such pomp, Aphrodite. But then, more goddesses ought better understand the need to keep appearances even in troubled times... \"especially \"in troubled times.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Hera : \n\"A shame you never knew your father, girl... but at least now you know his good brother Poseidon, here! Imagine this one, but without the foolish grin, nor the inappropriate remarks, with frankly better hair, in finer physical form.\"\n Poseidon : \n\"\"Ah, hahaha! \"See how strong a family we are, my niece?! For even in the face of such catastrophe as we have all endured, the Queen herself is able to make such humorous remarks! At my expense. But \"still!\"\nDialogue 02.\n Poseidon : \n\"\"Ahoy\", my little niece, I'm here with the spectacular Queen Hera, fairest wife of my distinguished brother, and all that! Shame I have never found myself a perfect mate as she! \"You\"'d bless us if I did, wouldn't you, Hera?\"\n Hera : \n\"\"Oh\", I'll assuredly bless you \"and \"your beloved mate whomever they may be, Poseidon. Perhaps when all of this is over, you may resume your search in earnest! But until such time, get your mind out of the gutter.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Apollo\"&gt;Apollo&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Hera : \n\"I fear for the younger generation. What can you possibly achieve when you're born with our worst qualities and not merely our best? Take good Apollo here... just like his father.\"\n Apollo : \n\"Now, Stepmother, don't all we gods aspire to your husband's excellence? I do appreciate the kind comparison! My fair cousin likewise surely has her father's finest traits!\"\nDialogue 02.\n Apollo : \n\"I know you were expecting me, sunshine, but my \"glorious \"stepmother the Queen would like a word! This instant... so I'd better step aside, all right?\"\n Hera : \n\"You see, my dear? There are yet those upon Olympus who show their Queen the proper deference. Seek not to earn the love of your subjects; make them a bit afraid, instead.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Demeter\"&gt;Demeter&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Hera : \n\"Much as your father was custodian of all the dead, so are we responsible for the rest of the world! The hour has grown dark, yes, but... we have the power to \"restore. \"Thanks be to my good sister Demeter...\"\n Demeter : \n\"The time for restoration always comes as does the spring. But we're amidst a long winter, without an end in sight. We need concern ourselves with naught else, O Queen.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Demeter : \n\"Of late, even my radiant young sister must sully her delicate hands in all the field work that must be done. She is even beginning to take to it... aren't you, Hera our Queen?\"\n Hera : \n\"\"Oh\", Demeter. These hands have seen more than you know! I simply do not flaunt the hardships I've endured. One \"can \"be as strong as a rock, without taking on its texture.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hephaestus\"&gt;Hephaestus&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Hera : \n\"I know full well we cannot stand on ceremony whilst our entire way of life is under threat! Yet surely my dear son Hephaestus here need not be so \"uncouth \"at every opportunity?\"\n Hephaestus : \n\"Not like you ever taught me proper manners, Mum. Fortunately, I did learn a couple things even without having a role model like you or Dad around to set me straight! Just \"watch\". And witchie, too!\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hephaestus : \n\"My Mum the Queen could not believe that you and I had been conversing lately, witchie. So I had to prove it to her here, you understand. Though seems she wants to be conversing in my stead...\"\n Hera : \n\"My son Hephaestus need only prove he can exude the \"confidence \"befitting a god, rather than whatever it is that he exudes instead. He's made himself useful at least, yes?\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hestia\"&gt;Hestia&lt;/a&gt; (Duo Boon).\nDialogue 01.\n Hera : \n\"We goddesses can be too proud to beg for aid! I'd never stoop to it myself. Why bother, when my hard-headed sister Hestia shall insist on intervening, anyway? And at this very moment \"whilst I speak!\"\n Hestia : \n\"Because, respectfully, you just don't know what's \"good \"for you, O Queen! Sometimes it's ones can't bring themselves to ask for help that need it \"most! \"Now why don't we set a \"proper \"example for the latest unceremonious addition to our family?\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hestia : \n\"Not always big on family business, though I take exception for my little sis. She of all goddesses has to put up with the most around here, and that's not even counting all this Chronos stuff. How do you manage it, \"O Queen?\"\n Hera : \n\"I manage it one evening at a time is how, Sister! Perhaps we shall have to burn the old world down and start anew, but... I can think of \"none \"more suited, should the need arise.\"\nAbouth the Scenery.\n&lt;a href=\"Oceanus\"&gt;Oceanus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hera : \n\"\"Eugh\", I can barely reach you as it is within that murk, and you seem even farther away now. The very outskirts of your father's realm, is it? That's... not the customary path into the Underworld...\"\n&lt;a href=\"Fields%20of%20Mourning\"&gt;Fields of Mourning&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hera : \n\"You've seen the Mourning Fields within your Underworld, yes? A solid portion of the residents are there due to failed marriages, most typically their own. I bless each matrimony that I can, but it can only do so much.\"\n&lt;a href=\"The%20Surface\"&gt;The Surface&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Hera : \n\"Welcome, my dear, to our world's surface! First time? It's a vast place! All sorts of different climates, mortal cultures, and the like. So don't let your first impression shake your faith; it isn't always such a disaster!\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hera : \n\"Mortals complained their city of Ephyra was forsaken by the gods, yet here we are! Ungrateful wretches. Not had many weddings of late. Not many funerals either... though, lots of death, destruction, and the like!\"\nDialogue 03.\n Hera : \n\"There are many potent reagents growing on the surface here, if you know where to look! Mere roots and flowers to the untrained eye, but in your hands, or better, in your cauldron? They'll have you working magick like never before.\"\nMiscellaneous Conversations.\nOffering Boon at The Start of a Run (Any).\n Hera : \n\"Each night presents to us a new beginning, isn't that so, my dear? And on \"this \"night, \"I \"shall accompany you from the very start... until the bitter end.\"\nOffering Boon at The Start of a Run (Underworld).\n Hera : \n\"Your descent into the Underworld has only begun, but I would join you from the very first steps. I'd far prefer it to all my other obligations put together, let me tell you!\"\nOffering Boon at The Start of a Run (&lt;a href=\"The%20Surface\"&gt;The Surface&lt;/a&gt;).\nDialogue 01.\n Hera : \n\"Your Underworld has long since fallen, but our Olympus yet stands; you're wise to head this way, where you can make a \"real \"difference, here and now. As \"I \"shall momentarily!\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hera : \n\"A single, capable combatant striking our enemies from their exposed flanks may be \"just \"what we require to drive them back. Looks like \"you're \"up for the job tonight!\"\nBuying Boon at &lt;a href=\"Charon\"&gt;Charon&lt;/a&gt;'s Shop.\nDialogue 01.\n Hera : \n\"We've a long-standing partnership with your good boatman there. I bring mortals into being and marry them off after a bit, he takes them yonder to your realm! Or used to, anyway.\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hera : \n\"Wealth cannot be measured in mere coin! The very idea is absurd; yet, there you are, paying for goods and services as though Chronos has already prevailed!\"\nDialogue 03.\n Hera : \n\"We cannot always reach you in those depths, though your boatman seems to have no trouble at all. Keeps to himself, fends for himself... I quite like him!\"\nDialogue 04.\n Hera : \n\"At least this was a shorter delivery for your trusted boatman, compared with having to drag our Boons all the way into the Underworld. Although, he probably prefers it there...\"\nAbout Route Choice.\n Hera : \n\"My husband Zeus and I have \"spirited \"debates regarding how you may ensure our victory. He is too proud to seek your help here on our mountaintop, whilst I would welcome it with open arms, so... come along!\"\nAbout Meeting.\n Hera : \n\"\"Ah! \"There you are \"again\", my dear! Pity to have only met in circumstances such as these. Yet families all go through their ups and downs, yes? Let me help you help us all.\"\nAbout Mission.\n Hera : \n\"To level with you, girl, I don't know that you've got what it takes to thwart the Titan. But, what choice do we have at this point? I'm willing to give you the benefit of the doubt.\"\nAbout Family.\n Hera : \n\"This is hardly the first time I've been pressed to intervene on \"your \"side of the family's behalf. I've stood my ground! We cannot keep getting involved in each other's affairs. Yet, if you've come to our defense, you're owed an exception...\"\nAbout Children.\nDialogue 01.\n Hera : \n\"Oh, the blessings that my kin and I bestow, why... they're a bit like children, I suppose. You don't always get the kind you want, but if you're clever, you can make them work!\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hera : \n\"I always wanted a little girl, you know? But I got Ares. Hephaestus. \"Eugh! \"Zeus' girls Athena and Artemis stay well afield of me, and Aphrodite, oh, she does what she wants. Some family we are.\"\nDialogue 03.\n Hera : \n\"Our great big family, why, we would have been just a small fraction of the size, if not for my husband's escapades! So many delightful children in my life as a result.\"\nAbout Eternity.\n Hera : \n\"One thing I've learned, my dear, is that \"forever \"is a very long time. It seems to me that nothing \"truly \"lasts forever anymore. Perhaps that is why we find ourselves in this particular predicament.\"\nAbout Mortals.\nDialogue 01.\n Hera : \n\"We had an obligation to your father here. Each mortal death adds to the population of the Underworld, after all! I tried to do my blasted part to curb the flow a bit. Have you any idea how onerous it is for mortals to give birth?\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hera : \n\"If ever you wondered whence came all the \"wretches \"in your Underworld, there are such mortals who see it as \"our \"responsibility to protect \"them! \"Can you believe it?\"\nDialogue 03.\n Hera : \n\"I hardly blame them but \"some \"mortals have grown skeptical about our governance. They have this newfangled idea of \"luck... \"strokes of fortune from thin air! Sheer \"mindless \"happenstance, not the work of gods or the Three Fates.\"\nAbout Witchcraft.\n Hera : \n\"I know something of witchcraft myself, girl. A subtle art, and therein lies its strength. Easy to disbelieve, or to dismiss as mere coincidence. But true power need not assert itself.\"\nAbout Reputation.\n Hera : \n\"We might not care for it but there's a certain power to being underestimated constantly. Right, girl? Let them think what they want; my blessings aren't merely for couples about to tie the knot. \"\nAbout Survival on &lt;a href=\"The%20Surface\"&gt;The Surface&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hera : \n\"They said you weren't cut out for being aboveground! Some Underworld curse holding you back... I'd not believed the hearsay for a moment, and sure enough. Perhaps they merely fear your potential.\"\nAbout Relationships.\n Hera : \n\"Aphrodite has quite gleefully informed me that \"you \"and certain friends of yours have grown quite close. Well if one thing leads to another and you decide to make a serious commitment, I should be \"only \"too pleased to oblige!\"\nAbout Marriage.\n Hera : \n\"I realize this may seem odd coming from me, my dear, but from one goddess to another: Do not rush into marriage! As much as it may seem a wondrous idea. Consider my example; and I'm the blasted goddess of marriage, herself!\"\nAbout &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; Completing A Run (&lt;a href=\"The%20Underworld\"&gt;The Underworld&lt;/a&gt;).\n Hera : \n\"We saw reports suggesting that you made it to the lowest depths! I thought perhaps you had prevailed... though, not yet, it seems. A sign of progress, nonetheless! Press on.\"\nAbout &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; Completing A Run (&lt;a href=\"The%20Surface\"&gt;The Surface&lt;/a&gt;).\n Hera : \n\"You came closer than ever to our mountaintop! I hoped, perhaps, that we could meet at last, but... we've more pressing matters to attend to now, the both of us.\"\nAbout &lt;a href=\"Trial%20of%20the%20Gods\"&gt;Trial of the Gods&lt;/a&gt; (Previous Rejection).\n Hera : \n\"The other night, given the opportunity, you sided with my kin, forgoing my Boon when I first generously offered it. Whilst that little scuffle is behind us, I do \"not \"appreciate any such slights. I trust I've made myself quite clear?\"\nPost-Gift Lines.\nDialogue 01.\n Hera : \n\"How fare you in your task of late, my dear? Much better than we fare up here, I hope. Oh, all of us are fine, except... being besieged does mean we're stuck in closer quarters than I'd like. There's not a moment's peace!\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hera : \n\"Take it from me, my dear, don't listen to your heart. I know it's difficult, seeing as the blasted thing tends to be very loud. But if you heed it, it'll lead you straight to your mistakes more often than not.\"\nAbout Polymorph.\n Hera : \n\"You know the Twilight Curse, oh I can tell. The power to change a form into another! A favorite of mine, and one small step removed from shapeshifting oneself. The possibilities are limitless, really.\"\nAbout Bows.\n Hera : \n\"You seem adept at keeping distance from your foes. I once excelled at this myself, although I favored an arrow through the heart over magick, which I found rather unreliable! But, whatever works for you.\"\nGifts.\n&lt;a href=\"Nectar\"&gt;Nectar&lt;/a&gt;.\n1st Time.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Queen Hera, out of all the matters you could be attending to, you've chosen to aid me. I am honored, and would honor you in kind.\"\n Hera : \n\"Is there a wedding date that I should know about or are you merely being generous with me? In any case, when I am offered to, there's always a catch. So, here!\"\n\"Hera gives &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; the &lt;a href=\"Iridescent%20Fan\"&gt;Iridescent Fan&lt;/a&gt;.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"You truly needn't have, Your Majesty.\"\n2nd Time.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Great Queen of Olympus! I am humbled to have earned your favor, and will do everything I can to honor you!\"\n Hera : \n\"Unbound by wedlock yet you praise me thus? I must say you are full of surprises, my dear. Or potentially just very ignorant. Or both!\"\n3rd Time.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"This golden Nectar is nothing in comparison to your splendor, Queen Hera; but it's the very best we have where I am from. To your eternal beauty, grace, and wisdom!\"\n Hera : \n\"You needn't be a flatterer, you know? I aid you not from love but from necessity. If there's a lesson I can impart, it's that you ought to keep your guard up at all times.\"\n4th Time.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"To the Queen of Olympus! Long may you reign, and may that reign be one of great prosperity and peace, both for your devoted family and subjects, and for you!\"\n Hera : \n\"Go on, girl. We each know I'm not really your Queen. You're not even an Olympian, so why don't you drop the act? Or if it's not an act, wise up. This is a complicated world.\""}
{"id": "2717", "revid": "29110118", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2717", "title": "Hera/Relationships", "text": "Olympian Gods.\nThe Olympians, including Hera, are part of the Olympians and hold high status. She is the queen, and they constitute a dysfunctional family.\nZeus.\n&lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's husband.&lt;br&gt;Hera and Zeus united to defeat Cronos together, and from there, a spark ignited between them. They fell in love and married, with Hera assuming the role of queen of the gods. Despite her status as a goddess of marriage, her wedded life is far from idyllic due to her husband's constant infidelities. Hera's frustration with Zeus is palpable; she has lost count of his transgressions and is weary of his cynical attitude towards them. Despite her weariness, Hera remains committed to their marriage, sacrificing much for its stability and proving herself to be a faithful and devoted spouse unlike Zeus.\nThe strain in their relationship is a central theme in many of Hera's blessings, and their tumultuous marriage is symbolized in her unique Duo Boon, \"King/Queen's Ransom.\" In this boon, players must choose between sacrificing all their blessings from Zeus to enhance each of their blessings from Hera, or his husband.\nAlthough it is implied that Hera keeps Zeus in line with a steely gaze, she is also known for her harsh treatment of her stepchildren, a behavior that cannot be excused. Nevertheless, her resentment towards Zeus is understandable given the circumstances. Yet, despite the trials they face, the love between them remains unwavering. They are regarded as soulmates, and if Zeus remains married, it is because he and Hera are in sync in their shared struggles and triumphs.\nAres.\n&lt;a href=\"Ares\"&gt;Ares&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's son.&lt;br&gt;\nHephaestus.\n&lt;a href=\"Hephaestus\"&gt;Hephaestus&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's son.&lt;br&gt;Hera doesn't have as good a relationship with her son Hephaestus. His birth stemmed from Hera's jealousy of Zeus's other children, wishing for someone more akin to Apollo or Athena. She expresses disdain for how \"crude\" and lacking in manners he is, while Hephaestus sarcastically describes her and Zeus as \"proper role models\" who never made an effort to teach him good manners.\nHestia.\n&lt;a href=\"Hestia\"&gt;Hestia&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's older sister.&lt;br&gt;Hera has a rather tense relationship with her older sister, often referring to her as 'hard-headed' and expressing irritation when Hestia interrupts her. However, she does respect Hestia's wisdom and fire powers.\nDemeter.\n&lt;a href=\"Demeter\"&gt;Demeter&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's older sister.&lt;br&gt;\nPoseidon.\n&lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's foster brother and brother-in-law.&lt;br&gt;Hera fought alongside Poseidon in the Titanomachy.\nAthena.\n&lt;a href=\"Athena\"&gt;Athena&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's stepdaughter.&lt;br&gt;Hera has mentioned that Athena prefers to keep her distance from her.\nArtemis.\n&lt;a href=\"Artemis\"&gt;Artemis&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's stepdaughter.&lt;br&gt;\nApollo.\n&lt;a href=\"Apollo\"&gt;Apollo&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's stepson.&lt;br&gt;She doesn't harbor much fondness for her stepson Apollo, but she does recognize his social adeptness. During her conversation with Duo Boon, she mentions that Apollo seems to have inherited both the best and worst traits from his father Zeus. Apollo, taking her words as a compliment, suggests that he shares many similarities with his \"esteemed father,\" and reassures Melino\u00eb that he must have inherited Zeus's finest characteristics.\nHermes.\n&lt;a href=\"Hermes\"&gt;Hermes&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's stepson.&lt;br&gt;\nDionysus.\n&lt;a href=\"Dionysus\"&gt;Dionysus&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's Stepson.&lt;br&gt;\nAphrodite.\n&lt;a href=\"Aphrodite\"&gt;Aphrodite&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's daughter-in-law.&lt;br&gt;\nChthonic Gods.\nThe gods of the underworld, most of whom the Olympians seem to despise, including she.\nHades.\n&lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's foster brother and brother-in-law.&lt;br&gt;Hera fought alongside Hades in the Titanomachy.\nMelino\u00eb.\n&lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's grandniece.&lt;br&gt;In her initial presentation, Hera is very polite, welcoming Melino\u00eb when she reaches the surface. She helps Melino\u00eb, but not willingly like other gods, only because she promised the family protection if Melino\u00eb showed determination. Hera never breaks her vows. Initially, she doesn't even maintain a facade of civility towards Melino\u00eb and clearly only helps her because she doesn't have many other options. Even gifting her nectar doesn't make Hera warmer towards Melino\u00eb. Instead of gratitude, Hera tells Melino\u00eb to drop \"the act,\" as she's not even the queen of the Chthonic goddess. She then remarks that if Melino\u00eb's kindness isn't an act, then she needs to learn how complicated the world is. Even her boons have a noticeably cynical touch, like granting bonuses only if she have no common rarity boons or losing power when the shine of her Bridal Glow boon begins to fade, among other examples. \nDespite this initial distance, Hera gradually develops an affection for Melino\u00eb, seeing her as the little girl who she never had.\nPersephone.\n&lt;a href=\"Persephone\"&gt;Persephone&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's niece.&lt;br&gt;\nThe Titans.\nThe previous rulers of the world, defeated in the Titan War and imprisoned in the pits of &lt;a href=\"Tartarus\"&gt;Tartarus&lt;/a&gt;. Many are relatives and are not malicious.\nHyperion.\n&lt;a href=\"Hyperion\"&gt;Hyperion&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's father.&lt;br&gt;\nTheia.\n&lt;a href=\"Theia\"&gt;Theia&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's mother.&lt;br&gt;\nHelios.\n&lt;a href=\"Helios\"&gt;Helios&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's brother.&lt;br&gt;\nSelene.\n&lt;a href=\"Selene\"&gt;Selene&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's sister.\nEos.\n&lt;a href=\"Eos\"&gt;Eos&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's sister.\nChronos.\n&lt;a href=\"Chronos\"&gt;Chronos&lt;/a&gt;: Hera's father-in-law.&lt;br&gt;Hera fought with her sisters and Zeus and his brothers. She still harbors traumatic memories of Chronos, as she maintains that she never truly believed he had vanished forever, and her apprehensions were brushed aside by Zeus."}
{"id": "2628", "revid": "47838920", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2628", "title": "Heracles", "text": "Heracles is a famous Greek hero and son of &lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt;. \nIn \"&lt;a href=\"Hades%20%28game%29\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;\", he never appears physically, but is frequently referenced by other characters. \nHe appears in \"&lt;a href=\"Hades%20II\"&gt;Hades II&lt;/a&gt;\", and helps &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; on her way up to Olympus. He is encountered in the &lt;a href=\"City%20of%20Ephyra\"&gt;City of Ephyra&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href=\"Rift%20of%20Thessaly\"&gt;Rift of Thessaly&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Mount%20Olympus\"&gt;Mount Olympus&lt;/a&gt;.\nPersonality and characteristics.\nA enigmatic demigod renowned for his strength, he's still revered for his accomplishments. So beloved by &lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt; that upon his death, he ascended to Olympus.\nHe's rugged, tough, and exudes the demeanor of a seasoned warrior. He greets Melino\u00eb coldly, instructing her to leave as he prefers to work alone without any interference and advises her that it's not a wise idea to provoke him.\nHeracles excelled in his endeavors, earning recognition even among other heroes like &lt;a href=\"Theseus\"&gt;Theseus&lt;/a&gt;. However, he harbors bitterness towards the &lt;a href=\"Olympians\"&gt;Olympians&lt;/a&gt; and is weary of constantly fulfilling their requests. Despite his fatigue, he acknowledges the lingering sense of duty.\nIn his book of shadows entry, it is said that wherever he goes, everyone around him becomes unhappy upon seeing him, and that he is a monster with a human face and an animal heart. This may be because, due to having enemies on all sides, many people around Heracles end up getting hurt accidentally.\nHe's harsh towards Melino\u00eb, partly due to his prejudice against witches. When questioned, he remains evasive, refusing to divulge further. Nonetheless, his respect for Melino\u00eb grows gradually upon discovering her non-divine lineage, akin to his own, and her prowess in combat.\nPhysical Description.\nHeracles appears as an imposing man with a tan skin tone, wearing only the Nemean Lion cloak on his back, with its paws serving as a belt, revealing his musclebound and scarred chest. His face is almost identical to his father's, although much younger and with a more sour expression. His beard is blond, wild, and mixed with the fur of the lion pelt on his head.\nHe's seen with multiple weapons of all sorts, some on his hands, others bound to him by ropes and straps. He also adorns more ropes around, namely on his left forearm, on top of his left bracelet, as well as the strap that crosses his chest. The knots seen on some of the ropes are known as \"square knots\".\nHistory.\nHades.\nIt's unclear where is Heracles and how is he doing during the game. However, seeing as his death was before the Trojan War, which has clearly already happened, he's likely residing on &lt;a href=\"Mount%20Olympus\"&gt;Olympus&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a href=\"Achilles\"&gt;Achilles&lt;/a&gt; also mentions Heracles died a death more gruesome than his and briefly stayed in the &lt;a href=\"The%20Underworld\"&gt;Underworld&lt;/a&gt;, but since he's favored by the gods, a pact must have been made that allowed him to leave.\n&lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt; comments that he's still sour from the time the hero came to take &lt;a href=\"Cerberus\"&gt;Cerberus&lt;/a&gt; from him, meaning he has already completed all twelve of his labors. &lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt; also makes comments about wishing to fight him instead of &lt;a href=\"Theseus\"&gt;Theseus&lt;/a&gt;, and can even purchase former weapons of the hero, as well as a statue for the West Hall.\nHades II.\nHeracles can appear in an Encounter in the &lt;a href=\"The%20Surface\"&gt;Surface&lt;/a&gt; to assist &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; as she makes her way to Olympus through a competition to see who can earn the most &lt;a href=\"Gold%20Crowns\"&gt;Gold Crowns&lt;/a&gt; from defeating enemies.\nGallery.\n&lt;tabber&gt;\nConcept=\nIllustration=\nMerchandise=\n&lt;/tabber&gt;"}
{"id": "2784", "revid": "48934972", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2784", "title": "Heracles/Quotes", "text": "The following are quotes from &lt;a href=\"Heracles\"&gt;Heracles&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Hades%20II\"&gt;Hades II&lt;/a&gt;\".\nFirst Meeting.\nDialogue 01 (Outside Encounter).\n Heracles : \n\"You're the help? Oh, that's rich. Friendly word of advice, \"sister: \"Stay out of my bloody way, else you're liable to get hurt. Now scoot, and tell whomever sent you that I work alone.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Your threat is duly noted, Son of Zeus. I'm headed for the docks, but understand this city's sealed shut.\"\n Heracles : \n\"Then you understand you ought turn back. This town is \"dead\", and doesn't let the living pass.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"I'm Daughter of Hades; the dead shall answer to me. They may just need a little encouragement.\"\n Heracles : \n\"Try all you like. But remember you were warned.\"\nDialogue 02 (Inside Encounter).\n Heracles : \n\"You. Things are about to turn ugly, and I require neither assistance nor witnesses, sister.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"I'm passing through. And I'm not leaving here until the traitors to the House of Hades lie broken at our feet.\"\n Heracles : \n\"\"Hah! \"Fine, then. We'll each earn our share. Though the lion's share is coming with me.\"\nKeepsake Dialogue (&lt;a href=\"Lion%20Fang\"&gt;Lion Fang&lt;/a&gt;).\nTBA\nPicking the Keepsake in The Chest.\nTBA\nAbouth the Scenery.\n&lt;a href=\"City%20of%20Ephyra\"&gt;City of Ephyra&lt;/a&gt;.\n Heracles : \n\"You live. By my good graces, granted, but... first I've seen somebody stand against the filth that's overtaken this accursed town.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"I aim to cleanse the filth down to the source. He resides deep in the Underworld, though I've business to attend to on Olympus first.\"\n Heracles : \n\"What a coincidence! I just returned from there not long ago. So the gods are putting all the pieces into place... You watch yourself, sister.\"\nMiscellaneous Conversations.\nAbout Witches.\n Heracles : \n\"I know what you are. You bloody witches. One foreign word... one finger-wagging gesture directed at me... and I'll squeeze you till you pop.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"That won't be necessary. Though, I would know how came you to feel this way about us bloody witches? How many have you met?\"\n Heracles : \n\"Two questions too many. The more you know, the more you can manipulate. Now, off with you.\"\nAbout Olympus.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Olympus is fortunate to have your strength and service, Son of Zeus.\"\n Heracles : \n\"I serve the gods all right. Served them a long time, one tall order after another. They've brought me fame, glory... \"everything. \"They never get enough of me.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"But \"you've \"had enough of \"them. \"Then... what are you doing here?\"\n Heracles : \n\"Oh, my work history can demonstrate I never get enough of \"them\", either. I take a job, I do it.\"\nAbout Fathers.\n Heracles : \n\"Our fathers sure made a mess of things for us, didn't they, sister. Born to the mightiest of gods, yet living like outcasts... like bloody animals.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"It's Chronos that made a mess of things. If he'd have just stayed dead, we'd be at peace. And together with our fathers, no doubt.\"\n Heracles : \n\"Have you \"met \"our fathers? Sure, we're in the midst of an interminable war, but at least we're far away from \"them.\"\nAbout Blood.\n Heracles : \n\"Your blood runs red. You're not entirely a goddess. We truly get the best of both worlds.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"You were born to a mortal mother, weren't you? My mother's half-mortal. Death itself is in our blood. But you're different...\"\n Heracles : \n\"\"Different. \"Neither god, nor mortal, nor Shade. It's as you say; death itself is in my blood. All mortals are born to die. I was born also to kill.\"\nAbout Characters.\n&lt;a href=\"Hera\"&gt;Hera&lt;/a&gt;.\n Heracles : \n\"...You have her blessing, then. Just like that, she gave you her strength. Her approval...\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"You mean Hera? Of course she did; we're all on the same side. More than that, we're family.\"\n Heracles : \n\"\"Family. \"It figures that her grace the Queen presides over the entire concept. Marriage, birthing, and the like. Curses, in a charitable form.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Polyphemus\"&gt;Polyphemus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Heracles : \n\"You made it out before. Cyclops must have caught your scent, though. He's strong, that one.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"That's a ringing endorsement, though you must be stronger still. Ever considered putting him to the test? Could save me a lot of trouble.\"\n Heracles : \n\"He's not my type. Besides, he's a spawn of the gods, just like you and me. Wouldn't be proper if we were all fighting all the time, now would it?\"\n&lt;a href=\"Charon\"&gt;Charon&lt;/a&gt;.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"You seem to know the Boatman pretty well. Worked together before?\"\n Heracles : \n\"I've had occasion to visit your realm in the past. The Boatman is my supplier. And evidently yours as well... buying up all the merchandise.\"\nWith Other Characters.\nTBA\nGifts.\n&lt;a href=\"Nectar\"&gt;Nectar&lt;/a&gt;.\n1st Time.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Great Son of Zeus, I offer you this gift of Nectar, that it may quench your thirst as you labor for the gods. They must be grateful for your might.\"\n Heracles : \n\"\"Heh. \"Saves me having to find another bottle for when next I have to prove my fealty. Here, something for your trouble.\"\n\"Heracles gives &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; the &lt;a href=\"Lion%20Fang\"&gt;Lion Fang&lt;/a&gt;\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"No trouble at all, thank you.\"\n2nd Time.\n Heracles : \n\"Sure you don't want to give me only half the bottle there? Seeing as I'm merely half a god... I got their strength but seldom get their luxury.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Nothing's gained from luxury in excess, anyway. But there are times a little doesn't hurt! May this soothe your spirit when the occasion arises.\""}
{"id": "2789", "revid": "48934972", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2789", "title": "Heracles/Relationships", "text": "Hera.\nHeracles has only disdain for Hera, his voice dripping with quiet fury when he notices her blessing upon Melino\u00eb. Hera's reputation for inflicting nightmares upon him is well-known."}
{"id": "942", "revid": "48112766", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=942", "title": "Hermes", "text": "Hermes is the &lt;a href=\"Olympian\"&gt;Olympian&lt;/a&gt; God of Commerce, Trickery, and Travel, as well as the messenger of the gods. He works with &lt;a href=\"Charon\"&gt;Charon&lt;/a&gt; to guide souls to their proper place in the Underworld, with Hermes delivering the souls to Charon, for him to ferry them down the Styx the rest of the way (giving Hermes the title of psychopomp, or someone who guides souls to the afterlife, which he and Charon share). He offers &lt;a href=\"boons\"&gt;boons&lt;/a&gt; that enhance &lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus's&lt;/a&gt; speed in various ways, including attack speed and special speed. His boons can also improve Zagreus's dash and cast recovery.\nHermes is one of five Olympian gods (the other four being &lt;a href=\"Demeter\"&gt;Demeter&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Aphrodite\"&gt;Aphrodite&lt;/a&gt;) who will not appear in the very first run of a save.\nIn \"&lt;a href=\"Hades%20II\"&gt;Hades II&lt;/a&gt;\", Hermes has become a spy for Olympus and has inflitrated &lt;a href=\"Chronos\"&gt;Chronos&lt;/a&gt;'s army to gain an edge in the fight against him. Despite this, he will provide his boons to &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; in her fight against Chronos.\nCharacteristics and Personality.\nMessenger of the Gods, God of Merchants, and Tricksters, Hermes rushes in to help Zagreus escape. Hermes is quite talkative, frenzied, and rarely pauses to take a breath. Despite his other duties, he is also a psychopomp tasked with guiding the souls of the dead alongside &lt;a href=\"Charon\"&gt;Charon&lt;/a&gt;.\nHermes is free-spirited, has a bright personality, and is an animated and chatty god. He is well-informed and more aware of the situation than any other &lt;a href=\"Mount%20Olympus\"&gt;Olympian&lt;/a&gt;. Hermes speaks extremely quickly, without pauses, making it difficult at times to keep up with him, and causing some things to slip by less attentive ears. His rapid speech is due to the fact that he is always overloaded with messages to deliver.\nHe has a genuine camaraderie with his colleagues guardians of the dead, even appeasing the feared Charon, who is inaccessible even by underworld standards. Charon doesn't seem to find Hermes' energy tiring, and seems to enjoy his company, although &lt;a href=\"Thanatos\"&gt;Thanatos&lt;/a&gt; and many others think that he is irritatingly excitable to listen to.\nDespite the nature of his job dealing with the dead, he is very vivacious. He is a jovial, mischievous god. Even though Hermes seems to be an \"open book\", he is the most \"secretive\" among the Olympians, revealing that not even his fellow Olympians know that he is helping Zagreus, and later Melino\u00eb, and he will omit and keep certain information in secrecy for his own benefit. Although he is Zeus's accomplice, he is hiding the fact that he knows &lt;a href=\"Persephone\"&gt;Persephone&lt;/a&gt; has returned to the underworld and will keep his mouth shut about it, no matter what it costs.\nPhysical description.\nHermes wears wings on his head and a smaller pair on each of his ankles and boots. He wears a slight smirk, is shown with his caduceus in his hands, and has legs that are firm and adapted for running. He wears a cream-colored chiton held by multiple belts, and with his wing symbol on top, and carries a pouch full of parchments, letters, and trinkets he needs to deliver. He also has a &lt;a href=\"Chellen\"&gt;turtle&lt;/a&gt; inside his satchel, which is one of his symbolic animals.\nHis appearance drastically changes in \"Hades II\". Hermes now wears a black with orange and golden details hanging over his right shoulder with his left chest exposed, in a contrary way to Zagreus's own attire, and the hem also has chthonic wings as a pattern. It is held in place by his old belt, which is now further decorated with a golden medallion with a chthonic wing on it. He maintains his scarf and bands on his right leg and left wrist, adding now a golden bracelet on his right wrist. He wears rings on some of his fingers. His caduceus now has two little fabrics tied on it and his satchel remains the same, albeit emptier than before, fully exposing his turtle companion. His hair is now longer and darker, being tied into a tiny ponytail by a brown band, and he has a slightly paler complexion, hinting he hasn't been under the sun as much as before. He also no longer uses earrings. His field model shows his sandals are different than the ones he wore in \"Hades\", since now his toes are exposed.\nHistory.\nPast.\nEven when he was just born, he was incredibly mischievous. With his playful nature, he jumped out of his swaddling clothes and stole &lt;a href=\"Apollo\"&gt;Apollo&lt;/a&gt;'s cattle. To prevent his brother from chasing him, he even threatened to plunder Apollo's temple. What is most known about him is that he is the god of roads, businessmen, and thieves. He once stole the scepter of Zeus, the trident of Poseidon, Apollo's bow, and Ares's sword. His swiftness and dexterity made him the embodiment of vigor, and he was later christened as a messenger of the gods.\nHe also accompanied the souls of the dead to the underworld of Hades and closed their eyes with the snake rod in his hand. He met Charon, a creepy figure, and they ended up becoming great friends.\nHades.\nHermes comes to be aware of Zagreus's escape attempts and lends his own help. However, he requests that his involvement remains hidden, as no one else besides Charon, Skelly and Zagreus himself know he's helping.\nHe comments on a multitude of different subjects, from his family and colleagues to work related matters, namely his job as a psychpomp, and commonly speaks as if delivering a message, sometimes doing truly that.\nUpon Persephone's return to the Underworld, Hermes is aware of the fact, but won't spread the news unless asked to, keeping it to himself in the mean time.\nEpilogue.\nAt first skeptical to join given his non-official involvement, Hermes nonetheless comes to the feast and enjoys it with Charon.\nHe becomes aware of Zagreus' new \"escaping arrangement\" with Hades, and keeps it to himself.\nAffinity.\nIf given &lt;a href=\"Nectar\"&gt;Nectar&lt;/a&gt;, Hermes will give you the &lt;a href=\"Lambent%20Plume\"&gt;Lambent Plume&lt;/a&gt;.\nHermes' affinity gauge is maxed out at 8 hearts.\nFavor.\nHermes' favor requires speaking with him while having the &lt;a href=\"Lambent%20Plume\"&gt;Lambent Plume&lt;/a&gt; equipped and max leveled to 3*. It does not matter how many stacks of its bonus you have.\nGallery.\n&lt;tabber&gt;\nConcept=\nIllustration=\n&lt;/tabber&gt;"}
