s : \n\"You found my special Shrines, good good! Some mortals pray to me both for safe travels and free stuff. \"Almost \"free. Small surcharge, mind! Associate has got to take his cut.\"\nAbout &lt;a href=\"Animal%20Familiars\"&gt;Animal Familiars&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hermes : \n\"Wise move having an animal companion along! I've got a soft spot for the quiet self-sufficient types. My little tortoise Chellen always feels at home wherever we go!\"\nAbout Characters.\n&lt;a href=\"Hecate\"&gt;Hecate&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hermes : \n\"Known Hec a while, and don't envy either one of you. She couldn't just send you off to deal with Gramps before you were ready! You must have \"hated \"having to wait. I know I do!\"\n&lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hermes : \n\"Hec always said you're quick to learn, you know? And sure enough, whenever I'd drop in, you'd be over a cauldron, working some new spell. Well, \"this is it! \"Your time to work some magick for our sake!\"\n&lt;a href=\"Chronos\"&gt;Chronos&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Hermes : \n\"What a customer, the Titan of Time! I've not met Gramps before, though I can imagine what he must be like. Used to wonder how come my pop and his brothers were so dodgy sometimes. Now I know where they got it from!\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hermes : \n\"You'd think the Titan of Time wouldn't be so stuck in the past, caught up in his idea of a \"Golden Age \"when \"he \"used to rule, and mortals hadn't a care in the world? Caring's not such a bad thing I think!\"\nDialogue 03.\n Hermes : \n\"No way you could have already stopped Gramps by now, but going after him right when you did, you're buying us some time to put a little wrinkle in his plan. So \"cheers!\"\n&lt;a href=\"Moros\"&gt;Moros&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hermes : \n\"Hec tells me Moros, son of Nyx, is staying with you for a bit down there? I thought he always stuck with the Three Fates. There's something going on, and I don't like it, M.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hermes : \n\"You found your father down there, M! Never could get close enough myself, hope he's still all right. Hope \"everyone\"'s all right! We'll get them back, keep doing everything we can.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Circe\"&gt;Circe&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hermes : \n\"Ran into Lady Circe on your way last night, did you, M? She's quite the talent with those magick spells of hers. Liked turning mortals to all sorts of things! Bit \"mean \"if you ask me!\"\n&lt;a href=\"Persephone\"&gt;Persephone&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hermes : \n\"Your mum would travel back and forth between Olympus and your father's House, and \"I \"had the pleasure of accompanying her! One day, she didn't show up. I knew right then and there something was off...\"\n&lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hermes : \n\"All this reminds of the time I backed your brother when he was searching for your mum! Had a vested interest in the outcome, sure. But before I knew it, I really started to care! We'll find a way to help them, won't we, M?\"\n&lt;a href=\"Artemis\"&gt;Artemis&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Hermes : \n\"Artemis and I weren't always close, each keeping to ourselves and all. But working with you and Hec brought us closer! We were so busy sneaking around, helped knowing we didn't have to sneak around each other!\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hermes : \n\"You already caught up with Artemis, good good! She and I don't always chat, running around a lot, being discreet and all. But we exchange a knowing look from time to time!\"\n&lt;a href=\"Charon\"&gt;Charon&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n\"You run into a certain Underworld Boatman rowing about, you tell him I said hey? We've not collaborated much as before, what with everything of late. I miss those times!\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hermes : \n\"So the Boatman's been all right, has he? That's good! I know that he's been looking out for Hec and the rest of you for a while now, but do look out for him in turn, would you?\"\n&lt;a href=\"Heracles\"&gt;Heracles&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hermes : \n\"Ran into big old Heracles, did you? My stepmum's sent him on another labor of some sort. Got the feeling that his heart's not in it anymore. But hey, he's tough! And we could use the help.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Fates\"&gt;The Fates&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hermes : \n\"So Gramps somehow got hold of the Three Fates! That isn't good, not sure what we can do about it, M. At least now everybody on Olympus knows, I figured it was time! Got us a bit on edge, though we do hide it pretty well!\"\n&lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hermes : \n\"Heard from my pop tonight already, M? He's always been a very busy god but never tires out. Now that you've got his lightning strength, how about some lightning \"speed \"to boot?\"\n&lt;a href=\"Apollo\"&gt;Apollo&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hermes : \n\"Apollo's lighting up your life? Last thing he ever wants to do is get his hands dirty, but now, things being as they are, he doesn't have much of a choice I guess!\"\n&lt;a href=\"Demeter\"&gt;Demeter&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hermes : \n\"For all that's happened, glad you finally met Demeter, even if only by Boon. She had a funny way of showing it sometimes but \"always \"loved your mum an awful lot. She'll fight to get her back, to the bitter end.\"\n&lt;a href=\"Hephaestus\"&gt;Hephaestus&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue 01.\n Hermes : \n\"You got Hephaestus to come out of his shell! All I can get from him are work orders, \"bring me more bronze \"and such! Glad you can put the fruits of all his labor to good use!\"\nDialogue 02.\n Hermes : \n\"Hephaestus makes a \"mean \"set of armor, and you know what? He makes a mean pair of sandals, too. I wear mine all the time! \"Footwear\", M! I really think it's going to catch on!\"\n&lt;a href=\"Selene\"&gt;Selene&lt;/a&gt;.\n Hermes : \n\"Oh good, Selene got a hold of you already, M! Quite the vantage point the Eye of Night has got! Always looking out for you and all of us. Her steeds are pretty quick as well!\"\nWith Other Characters.\nTBA\nGifts.\n&lt;a href=\"Nectar\"&gt;Nectar&lt;/a&gt;.\n1st Time.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"I'm glad you're here, Hermes, and it's an honor to finally be working together. To our swift victory!\"\n Hermes : \n\"Oh, hey! It's been a minute since I got an offering! Cheers, M, although you needn't have. But here, I've just the thing for you!\"\n\"Hermes gives &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt; the &lt;a href=\"Metallic%20Droplet\"&gt;Metallic Droplet&lt;/a&gt;.\"\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Nothing like a quick exchange of gifts!\"\n2nd Time.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"Hermes, if there's anyone out there who can help me outpace Time, it's you. Please accept this, for your swift and reliable service.\"\n Hermes : \n\"Right charitable of you, really, M, it's just I \"really \"need to move along, so let's get to the blessings if you please?\"\n3rd Time.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"If not for all your speed and bravery, we never would have had a fighting chance against our enemy, Hermes. I don't think we'll soon be able to repay you for this, but I can try!\"\n Hermes : \n\"Right cordial of you, M, though I'm not much for tips and we've got pressing matters to attend to, don't you think? Though I appreciate it, honestly.\"\n4th Time.\n Melino\u00eb : \n\"I know you've been exceptionally busy as of late, but... might I briefly interrupt our routine to give to you this little offering? It isn't much, but down here, it's some of the best we've got.\"\n Hermes : \n\"Don't know how you can find the \"time \"these days, though I am grateful that you thought of me like this! Now straight to business, then? Got lots to \"do!\""}
{"id": "2513", "revid": "47838920", "url": "https://hades.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2513", "title": "Hermes/Relationships", "text": "Family.\nZeus.\n&lt;a href=\"Zeus\"&gt;Zeus&lt;/a&gt;: Hermes's father.&lt;br&gt;Hermes is one of Zeus's many illegitimate children, and he considers his father to be a \"wonderful guy.\" However, he advises &lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt; not to spend too much time with Zeus. \nHermes is deeply involved in the disappearance of &lt;a href=\"Persephone\"&gt;Persephone&lt;/a&gt; and is an accomplice in it alongside his father. He appears to have a certain fear of \"falling\" along with Zeus.\nWhile he keeps his father well-informed, sends messages on Zeus's behalf, and is highly reliable in this role, he doesn't share all the details to prevent Zeus from causing more harm. In reality, Hermes keeps his collaboration with Zagreus a secret, hiding this partnership even from his siblings and initially from Zeus. Hermes acts as a double agent, helping Zagreus and Persephone reunite alongside &lt;a href=\"Charon\"&gt;Charon&lt;/a&gt;.\nHowever, in &lt;a href=\"Hades%20II\"&gt;Hades II&lt;/a&gt;, Zeus reveals he sees his son as lazy and never around when he's most needed, hinting their relationship isn't as good as Hermes likes to portray. This comes from Hermes constantly working behind the scenes, but never revealing as such to his family, an indication of their untrusty nature.\nAthena.\n&lt;a href=\"Athena\"&gt;Athena&lt;/a&gt;: Hermes's half-sister.&lt;br&gt;He comments on how his stepsister thinks a little too much about things, 'and cares a bit too much,' trying to solve everything on her own, insinuating that she may be a bit intrusive. Athena criticized her brother's tendency to withhold information. She is worried that his interference may do more harm than good.\nAres.\n&lt;a href=\"Ares\"&gt;Ares&lt;/a&gt;: Hermes's half-brother.&lt;br&gt;Although Hermes does not directly criticize his older half-brother Ares, he does indirectly comment to his cousin Zagreus that there's \"nothing like a good old fashioned war between mortals to create demand for lots and lots of messages to circulate!\", indicating that he's burdening him even more.\nArtemis.\n&lt;a href=\"Artemis\"&gt;Artemis&lt;/a&gt;: Hermes's half-sister.&lt;br&gt;She usually turns her back on him, not out of disdain, but because she is quiet and he is very talkative. He considers Artemis a very cool distant big sister and comments on how skilled Artemis is, although he is faster, she is still very fast.\nThey both withheld the information of &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt;'s existence from the remaining of their family, demonstrating that, despite their differences, they trust each other mutually and think similarly in regards to their family.\nArtemis and Hermes didn't always talk much, but they've always had a lot in common, as they're constantly on the move, busy, and prefer to keep a low profile. Taking care of themselves and their duties, Hermes realizes that working with Melino\u00eb and &lt;a href=\"Hecate\"&gt;Hecate&lt;/a&gt; brought them closer. Due to their constant business and scouting around, they now recognize they don't need to dodge each other and are more willing to help one another.\nApollo.\n&lt;a href=\"Apollo\"&gt;Apollo&lt;/a&gt;: Hermes's half-brother.&lt;br&gt;Hermes appears surprised at Apollo's intervention in &lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt;'s situation, saying the God of Light doesn't like to dirty his hands. He also sarcastically remarks the snakes of his caduceus remind him of his brother and thus he always carries a piece of him around, 'Stuck together, not so thick-skinned, occasional skirmishes... love them anyway.' This observation, comparing family relationships to snakes is somewhat sardonic and shows that Hermes acknowledges that Apollo may not have always been the best brother, but he still holds memories.\nHephaestus.\n&lt;a href=\"Hephaestus\"&gt;Hephaestus&lt;/a&gt;: Hermes's half-brother.&lt;br&gt;Hermes mentions Hephaestus was the one who made him his sandals, and praises his craftsman abilities. However, he also says Hephaestus is constantly asking him to deliver materials and nothing else, showing they aren't that close despite any efforts put, and implying Hephaestus is one of the gods that keep him the most busy.\nDionysus.\n&lt;a href=\"Dionysus\"&gt;Dionysus&lt;/a&gt;: Hermes's half-brother.&lt;br&gt;Dionysus is Hermes's younger half-brother, and both of them are playful. Hermes tells Zagreus that Dionysus never feels like life is moving too fast. He also comments on Dionysus' ability to throw a great feast, hinting that he's probably attended many such parties with his brother.\nPoseidon.\n&lt;a href=\"Poseidon\"&gt;Poseidon&lt;/a&gt;: Hermes's uncle.&lt;br&gt;He likes to play with his uncle, commenting that his uncle Poseidon gave Zagreus his blessing before him, of course, only because Hermes allowed. Hermes finds it amusing that Uncle Poseidon still thinks of himself as agile. Poseidon is not aware of this fact.\nHestia.\n&lt;a href=\"Hestia\"&gt;Hestia&lt;/a&gt;: Hermes' foster aunt.\nDemeter.\n&lt;a href=\"Demeter\"&gt;Demeter&lt;/a&gt;: Hermes's foster aunt&lt;br&gt;Hermes complains about how much he's been fearing the cold lately, as it has been interfering with his work. He sarcastically remarks, \"We have Demeter to thank for that,\" implying that it's her fault. Hermes doesn't like crossing paths with Demeter, as she doesn't value his services much. He hopes that spending time with Zagreus will lift her spirits and warm her heart.\nShe is happy to receive a letter from her daughter &lt;a href=\"Persephone\"&gt;Persephone&lt;/a&gt; after the Epilogue, courtesy of Hermes himself, showing that he still puts his work above his personal feelings.\nHera.\n&lt;a href=\"Hera\"&gt;Hera&lt;/a&gt;: Hermes' stepmother.\nAphrodite.\n&lt;a href=\"Aphrodite\"&gt;Aphrodite&lt;/a&gt;: The Goddess of Love and Beauty.&lt;br&gt;Hermes comments to Zagreus how amazing Aphrodite is, and how he doesn't usually stop, but always pauses to wave at her. She never complained, so she seems to enjoy the attention.\nChthonic Gods.\nThe gods of the underworld, Hermes frequently visits them, for it is his duty to guide the souls of the dead to the underworld. He usually has a friendly relationship with them.\nCharon.\n&lt;a href=\"Charon\"&gt;Charon&lt;/a&gt;: Fellow psychopomp and bestie.&lt;br&gt;Pals Psychopomp and longtime friends, the relationship of the two is quite impressive as Charon really causes the chills and seems reserved even for the denizens of the underworld. Hermes is responsible for guiding the souls of the dead to the banks of the River Styx, where Charon would take over. Hermes is in real contrast with his dry companion Charon, both apparently, as one being extremely talkative and the other barely saying a word or letting out frightening murmurs. Even so, Charon seems to enjoy interacting with and listening to Hermes, not seeming to be bothered by his frantic voice like the rest of the characters and Hermes will speak highly of Charon to others.\nHermes accepts a favor from Charon and also owes him a debt, concealing the fact that he arranged for both Charon and &lt;a href=\"Skelly\"&gt;Skelly&lt;/a&gt; to assist Zagreus. If Zagreus were to uncover this, Hermes playfully reminds him that he also keeps many secrets, suggesting it's best for him to maintain secrecy as well.\nDuring the events of the second game, both have been key figures in Melino\u00eb's childhood and everyone notes how close they are with each other. Ever since Hermes left for his spy mission, many characters reassure him Hermes is well and will come back. When he finally does, Hermes reveals the first thing he did was go to Charon. Dialogue with the two will reveal they share a mutual longing for each other, as Melino\u00eb is often in charge of delivering a quick \"Hey\" in their stead to the other.\nBoth also operate in similar ways, delivering items to Melino\u00eb and the Crossroads and taking care of the &lt;a href=\"Well%20of%20Charon\"&gt;Wells of Charon&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Shrine%20of%20Hermes\"&gt;Shrines of Hermes&lt;/a&gt;, similar by nature.\nZagreus.\n&lt;a href=\"Zagreus\"&gt;Zagreus&lt;/a&gt;: Hermes's cousin.&lt;br&gt;Zeus trusts Hermes a lot, whether to deliver messages or keep a secret, he has the epithelium of \"messenger of the gods\". Hermes is always delivering messages from him around without complaining or covering up for something rowdy his father caused. Like Zagreus, though not quite, Hermes has spent most of his life in the Underworld, however, he notes that he is some sort of shadow of his father, Hades. As much as Hermes is considered the most honest of his family, like Zeus he is hiding the game of agreu and does not intend to tell it.\nIn the second game, when Melino\u00eb calls upon him, it reminds him of Zagreus asking for help in finding his mother. Initially, he had a mild interest in the outcome, but before he realized it, he actually began to care. His interest now extends to helping Melino\u00eb.\nMelino\u00eb.\n&lt;a href=\"Melino%C3%AB\"&gt;Melino\u00eb&lt;/a&gt;: Hermes's cousin.&lt;br&gt;He was a key figure in her childhood. He calls her M for short, though she is more cordial with him, always refering to him as Lord Hermes.\nDuring their encounter, Hermes expresses gratitude to Melino\u00eb, as being with her and Hecate working together has brought him closer to Artemis. He asks how things are going and if their tasks are progressing well, offering advice on adjusting plans if necessary. Hermes suggests that Melino\u00eb should visit Olympus soon, even if she can't reach the surface yet. Despite this, he bids Melino\u00eb farewell, asking her to promise to keep in touch with him and offering his support.\nHades.\n&lt;a href=\"Hades\"&gt;Hades&lt;/a&gt;: Hermes's uncle.&lt;br&gt;Hermes met his uncle before the events of the game, likely when he was sent to be a psychopomp. He says that this encounter was a memorable moment to him.\nThey're both very given to their work, and Hermes often mentions he respects people like that, so his uncle likely is no exception. Hermes was also present during the making of the Pact of Punishment, and possibly gave his own insights, implying Hades is open to hear his opinion, a rare occurrence.\nThanatos.\n&lt;a href=\"Thanatos\"&gt;Thanatos&lt;/a&gt;: Fellow psychopomp.&lt;br&gt;Although Thanatos ends up bumping into Hermes at some point and likes to stay well informed at work, he finds the way Hermes delivers information irritating. He doesn't like to listen to him talk.\nPersephone.\n&lt;a href=\"Persephone\"&gt;Persephone&lt;/a&gt;: Hermes's foster cousin.&lt;br&gt;He knows all of Persephone and Zeus' plan. He helped her return to the Underworld again, and he's also hiding the fact that Charon was the one who arranged for him and Skelly to help Zagreus find her. Hermes is also the one that guides Persephone up to Olympus.\nHecate.\n&lt;a href=\"Hecate\"&gt;Hecate&lt;/a&gt;: Witch of the Crossroads.&lt;br&gt;She trusts in him to spy on Chronos, as well as keep Melino\u00eb's existence a secret from Olympus. He calls her Hec for short.\nHouse of Hades.\nSkelly.\n&lt;a href=\"Skelly\"&gt;Skelly&lt;/a&gt;: Peer relationship.&lt;br&gt;Skelly is in the service of Charon, and both of them appear to be frenetic conversationalists, maintaining a \"peer relationship.\" Hermes also seems to share confidential matters with Skelly without hesitation.\nDusa.\n&lt;a href=\"Dusa\"&gt;Dusa&lt;/a&gt;: Duty-Bound Gorgon.&lt;br&gt;They were part of a team, along with Charon and Skelly, joining forces to bring Zagreus and Persephone together.\nUnderworld Residents.\nHermes is one of the few gods that will sometimes comment on the shades Zagreus can befriend during his escape attempts. This is because he was the one that brought some of them there, some under better cirscumstances than others, but has since cut contact, likely due to his huge piles of work.\nOne such shade he leaves unnamed, but mentions they \"had it coming\", due to all their lying and cheating in life.\nOrpheus and Eurydice.\n&lt;a href=\"Orpheus\"&gt;Orpheus&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Eurydice\"&gt;Eurydice&lt;/a&gt;: a couple of musicians Hermes has helped before.&lt;br&gt;Hermes will make an honorable mention to these two shades, whom he helped when Orpheus tried to take Eurydice out of the Underworld, commenting on Orpheus's great ability with the lyre and lamenting not having had a proper goodbye last he saw Eurydice. He'll later be privy of information regarding Eurydice's current predicament and be glad that she is well.\nThe Titans.\nHermes is acting as a double agent, pretending to be on their side, and passing information to the surface.\nSelene.\n&lt;a href=\"Selene\"&gt;Selene&lt;/a&gt;: Moon Incarnate.&lt;br&gt;She mentions his welcome help in their cause. He praises her steeds for their speed.\nChronos.\n&lt;a href=\"Chronos\"&gt;Chronos&lt;/a&gt;: Hermes's paternal grandfather.&lt;br&gt;Hermes never met his grandfather before, but now can see similarities between him and his sons, pointing they're all dodgy sometimes. He is against Chronos \"Golden Age\", finding that caring isn't so bad. He also remarks it's ironic how the Titan of Time is stuck in the past."}
